<HEADLINE> N.Irish Man in Court Over Arson Murder </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 21 (Xinhua) -- A man appeared in a Belfast court
Tuesday charged with murdering three young Catholic brothers in an
arson attack.
</P>
<P>
Thomas Gilmour, 23, from Ballymoney, is accused of killing
Richard, Mark and Jason Quinn when their home was petrol-bombed
nine days ago.
</P>
<P>
Police have made several arrests since the arson attack, which
has been blamed on Protestant extremists.
</P>
<P>
Gilmour pleaded not guilty. Another man being held in
connection with the deaths has been released without charge. But
several others are still being questioned.
</P>
<P>
Gilmour has been remanded in custody until August 12, when he
will appear at another hearing at the court attached to Northern
Ireland's top security Maze prison.
</P>
<P>
The attack on the Quinn home took place at the height of a
protest by traditionalist Protestants camped out in a field near
Portadown to insist on their right to parade through a Catholic
area of the town. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
