<DOCNO> XIE19980722.0003 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Housing Construction Starts Up Strongly in June </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 21 (Xinhua) -- Stimulated by lower mortgage
rates and a strong economy, the U.S. housing starts increased
strongly in June, reversing three straight months of decline, the
Commerce Department reported here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Builders started construction in June at a seasonally adjusted
rate of 1,615,000 new housing units, up 5.6 percent from May and
about 8 percent above the level of new starts in June 1997,
according to the report.
</P>
<P>
Construction had slowed in March, April and May after reaching
a nine-year high of 1.62 million units in February.
</P>
<P>
For 10 straight months now, home building has been above a
seasonally adjusted annual rate of 1.5 million units, the longest
building boom since the mid-1980s.
</P>
<P>
However, new building permits fell 1.7 percent in June to 1.52
million units, reflecting an anticipated shortage of skilled
construction workers.
</P>
<P>
But construction of new homes is continuing strong into July,
with interest rates on 30-year fixed mortgages averaging 6.94
percent this month, as compared with 7.0 percent in June.
</P>
<P>
New construction of single-family homes last month rose 2.5
percent from May, to a seasonally adjusted annual rate of 1.25
million units. Townhouse construction, however, fell 19.2 percent
to an annual rate of 42,000 units.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, apartment building construction rose 24.7 percent to
a rate of 323,000 units.
</P>
<P>
By region, housing starts in the Northeast fell 9.3 percent in
June to an annual rate of 136,000 units after rising sharply in
May. But in the rest of the country, the housing boom continued
unabated. New starts rose 1.6 percent in the Midwest to 310,000,
8.9 percent in the South to 760,000, and 9.4 percent in the West
to 409,000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
