<HEADLINE> India, U.S. End Third Round of Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, July 21 (Xinhua) -- India and the United States
ended here Tuesday morning their third round of talks primarily on
nuclear non-proliferation and disarmament without tangible
results.
</P>
<P>
Both sides admitted that differences persisted over
security-related issues but termed the talks as "constructive and
ongoing" and agreed to continue the dialogue process in Washington
in August.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. delegation led by Deputy Secretary of State Strobe
Talbott and the Indian side headed by the prime minister's special
envoy Jaswant Singh held a 90-minute meeting Tuesday morning
mainly to sum up the two-day discussions and to chart out the
broad agenda for the next round of talks, Indian officials said.
</P>
<P>
An American spokeswoman told reporters that both sides were
looking forward to areas of agreement and there has been steady
movement.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. has insisted that India should roll back or freeze its
nuclear weaponization and missile programs while India has made it
clear that this is not negotiable.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. asked India to sign the Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty
(CTBT) unconditionally and forthwith while India said it can not
sign so long as New Delhi is accorded the status of a nuclear
threshold state under the CTBT.
</P>
<P>
Emerging from his meeting with Indian Prime Atal Bihari
Vajpayee Monday, Talbott told reporters that the two countries had
not yet reached a point that was conclusive, adding that "we have
a long way to go."
</P>
<P>
The American envoy conveyed Washington's desire to put
bilateral relations on a solid footing in the aftermath of India's
nuclear tests in May, said Talbott who arrived in New Delhi Sunday
evening.
</P>
<P>
He said that President Bill Clinton's visit to India slated for
November this year was under review.
</P>
<P>
Talbott, who left for Islamabad Tuesday morning, delivered a
letter Monday from President Clinton to Vajpayee, the content of
which is unknown.
</P>
<P>
Talbott is the first high-ranking U.S. official to visit the
South Asian country since India conducted the nuclear tests.
</P>
<P>
The Indian Ministry of External Affairs issued a statement
Monday, saying that Talbott's talks with Indian officials were
marked by a spirit of working together to find common ground and
to narrow gaps in their governments' respective perceptions.
</P>
<P>
The statement said that during his meeting with Talbott Monday,
Vajpayee was informed of the progress towards removal of problems
in Indo-U.S. relations which surfaced after India's nuclear tests.
</P>
<P>
"There is now a clearer understanding of each other's concerns
and certain steps in the direction of addressing those concerns
are contemplated," said the statement.
</P>
<P>
This is the third meeting between Talbott and Singh in less
than 40 days. His first two rounds of talks with Singh -- in
Washington on June 12 and in Frankfurt on July 9 -- reached no
concrete results.
</P>
<P>
The talks came ten days before the scheduled meeting between
Indian Prime Minister Atal Bihari Vajpayee and Pakistani Prime
Minister Nawaz Sharif on the sidelines of the three-day summit of
the South Asian Association for Regional Cooperation (SAARC) in
Colombo beginning on July 29.
</P>
<P>
Both the U.S. and India were reportedly keen on improving the
bilateral relations so as to save the plans of President Bill
Clinton to visit South Asian countries later this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
