<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading U.S. Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 21 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in the leading U.S. newspapers Tuesday:
</P>
<P>
The Washington Post:
</P>
<P>
-- Saying safer schools are "central to the mission of renewing
America," President Bill Clinton Monday urged the nation's
second-largest teacher's union to help him promote greater use of
school uniforms, curfews and old-fashioned crackdowns on truancy.
</P>
<P>
-- House Majority Leader Richard K. Armey (Republican from
Texas) Monday vowed an all-out effort to keep Congress from
approving any allocation more than 3.4 billion dollars for the
International Monetary Fund and, in a reversal, predicted he would
prevail.
</P>
<P>
-- President Bill Clinton will travel to Ireland and Northern
Ireland in September to celebrate and try to reinforce the
historic peace accord his administration helped negotiate earlier
this year, the White House announced Monday.
</P>
<P>
The New York Times:
</P>
<P>
-- From Florida through Louisiana and Texas to Colorado, weeks
of incessant heat and drought are causing scores of deaths,
burned-out homes and withered crops. Although the numbers are
preliminary, local and state authorities blamed the heat for 117
deaths, including 81 in Texas, 22 in Louisiana and 11 in Oklahoma.
</P>
<P>
-- The Clinton Administration and the Republican leadership are
bracing for another showdown over taxes and spending.
</P>
<P>
-- American and Indian officials held a round of talks to ease
the standoff that developed after India conducted underground
nuclear tests in May. But officials on both sides said there were
no breakthroughs.
</P>
<P>
The Wall Street Journal:
</P>
<P>
-- Internet privacy legislation is expected to be urged Tuesday
in FTC testimony to Congress, a departure from the
administration's hands-off stance. The guidelines, among other
things, would require Web sites to tell consumers what data they
collect and how they are used.
</P>
<P>
-- SunTrust Banks is set to acquire Crestar for stock valued at
8.61 billion dollars, creating the nation's 10th-largest bank and
extending the consolidation of the U.S. bank industry.
</P>
<P>
USA Today:
</P>
<P>
-- With official attention in Washington riveted on the U.S.-
Mexican border, crime along the USA's undefended border with
Canada is climbing to levels surpassing the rum-running days of
Prohibition. 
</P>
