<HEADLINE> Pakistan Terms Talks With U.S. Delegation as </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, July 21 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan Tuesday described its
first day of talks with a high-level U.S. delegation led by Deputy
Secretary of State Strobe Talbott as "comprehensive and in-depth."
</P>
<P>
Foreign Secretary Shamshad Ahmad, who is leading the Pakistani
side, and the U.S. deputy state secretary have made an "extensive
review of the entire range of security concerns and issues
including the core issue of Jammu and Kashmir," said a press
release issued by the Foreign Office after the meeting which
lasted more than three hours.
</P>
<P>
The discussions, which took place in a "friendly and positive
atmosphere," also focused on the post-nuclear test environment in
South Asia, the release said.
</P>
<P>
"Pakistan understands the U.S. concerns over the increasing
threat of an arms race and escalation, and welcomes the U.S.
interest in preventing further deterioration of the security
situation in South Asia," it said.
</P>
<P>
The Pakistani side emphasized the need for the effective
engagement of major powers with the security issues and help
Pakistan and India solve their problems, it added.
</P>
<P>
The two sides will continue their talks Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Talbott, who is on a two-day visit to Pakistan, arrived here
from New Delhi where he held similar talks with the Indian
leadership.
</P>
<P>
He will also call on Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif and Foreign
Minister Gohar Ayub Khan Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Talbott's visit is part of the U.S. efforts to try to convince
Pakistan and India to sign the non-proliferation accords including
the Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty.
</P>
<P>
His current South Asian tour takes place a few days after the
Clinton Administration got broad authority to temporarily lift all
economic sanctions against Pakistan and India imposed following
their nuclear tests in May. 
</P>
</TEXT>
