<HEADLINE> Cyprus Tells U.N.: Turkey Violates Airspace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, July 21 (Xinhua) -- Cyprus has strongly protested to
the U.N. over the violations of its sovereign airspace by Turkish
military aircraft.
</P>
<P>
In a letter to the U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan, Cyprus
Permanent representative to the U.N., Sotiris Zackheos, said
Turkish war planes violated Cyprus' airspace and Nicosia flight
information region (FIR) on July 10.
</P>
<P>
Zackheos protested strongly against "these new provocative acts
by Turkey, a member state of the U.N., against the sovereignty and
territorial integrity of the Republic of Cyprus," Cyprus News
Agency reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
He said such intrusions broke international air traffic rules
and run against Security Council resolutions on Cyprus which state
that such overflights increase political tension on the island and
undermine efforts toward achieving a final settlement.
</P>
<P>
These acts, he added, "are in complete disregard of
international law, the U.N. Charter and the relevant decisions of
the organization on the question of Cyprus."
</P>
<P>
This Eastern Mediterranean island has remained divided since
1974 when Turkey landed its troops and took over the northern
third in the wake of a failed pro-Athens coup in Nicosia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
