<DOCNO> XIE19980722.0015 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nepal to Host Int'l Conference on Energy in October </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, July 21 (Xinhua) -- Experts from some 40 countries
will assemble here in October to discuss the role of renewable
energy technology (RET) in rural development, organizers said here
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
At the three-day conference starting October 12, the experts
are scheduled to disseminate successful RET undertaken in their
respective countries and exchange experiences and information.
</P>
<P>
Besides, they will identify ways on how to maintain closer
cooperation among the participating countries and explore the
existing engineering educational activities related to RET, the
organizers said in a press release.
</P>
<P>
The conference is organized jointly by the Alternative Energy
Promotion Center under the Nepali Ministry of Science and
Technology, the Institute of Engineering of Tribhuvan University
and Nepal Solar Energy Society.
</P>
<P>
The conference secretariat has received 87 abstracts of papers
from 22 countries -- Bangladesh, Belgium, Denmark, Germany, India,
Israel, Japan, the Maldives, Nepal, New Zealand, Pakistan, Papua
New Guinea, Romania, Sri Lanka, South Africa, Thailand, Britain,
the United States, Vietnam, Zambia, France and Russia, the press
release said.
</P>
<P>
But about 40 countries have been wishful to attend the
conference, the organizers told a press conference held here
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
There are gaps and bottlenecks to optimize the use of RET for
the benefit of rural people in Nepal, the press release said.
</P>
<P>
The limited knowledge in the area of technology, policy and
program at implementation level is the major reason of
unsuccessful results in some RET-related areas, it added.
</P>
<P>
"In this context, the knowledge and experiences of the
participating countries/experts will certainly be useful for
solving at least some of the problems being faced in Nepal," it
said.
</P>
<P>
In Nepal, fuelwood accounts for 67.6 percent of the energy
consumed, leading to depleting forests in the country.
</P>
<P>
And fuelwood is used mainly for cooking in the country, said
Professor Jagan Nath Shrestha, president of Nepal Solar Energy
Society.
</P>
<P>
He told the press conference that such renewable energies as
micro hydro-power, biomass and solar energy have been used in
Nepal. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
