<HEADLINE> India to Import Currency Notes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, July 21 (Xinhua) -- The Indian government has
permitted the Reserve Bank of India (RBI) to import a total of 3.6
billion pieces of printed bank notes as a measure to overcome the
shortage of the rupee notes in the country.
</P>
<P>
Finance Minister Yashwant Sinha Tuesday told Rajya Sabha, the
Upper House of Parliament, that the RBI would commence full
production of the notes by the end of the year and would be able
to produce 4.77 billion pieces of the notes.
</P>
<P>
He said in a written reply to Members of Parliament that the
production capacity of the government note-printing presses would
increase from 5.876 billion pieces to 8.3 million a year by the
end of 1998.
</P>
<P>
The exchange rate of the Indian rupee against the U.S. dollar
depreciated from 39.48 one dollar in early April to 42.47 at the
end of June, dropping by about seven percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
