<HEADLINE> Hamas Denies Link With Car Bombing Attempt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 21 (Xinhua) -- The Palestinian Islamic group
Hamas denied Tuesday that it was connected with a suspected car
bombing attempt Sunday in Jerusalem, Israel Radio reported.
</P>
<P>
The radio quoted a Hamas spokesman as saying in Gaza that
Hamas "knew nothing about" the vehicle, a small van suspected by
Israeli police as a car bomb when what they called "dangerous
materials" were found on it.
</P>
<P>
The van caught fire Sunday on a main street in Jerusalem and
Israeli police rushing in to the rescue said that they found the
van was actually a car bomb. They claimed that a terror attack was
averted and Hamas was suspected to be behind the plot.
</P>
<P>
Both Palestinian security sources and Hamas activists raised
question Monday about the incident. They maintained that the
driver, who still remained unconscious in hospital after badly
burned, apparently had not intended to commit a suicide bombing.
</P>
<P>
The driver was heading into Jerusalem with materials required
for a construction job, they said. The van was loaded with gas
canisters, fuel oil and several dozen kilograms of nails. No
explosive was found.
</P>
<P>
Jerusalem police, however, stood by their original
assessment: that the van was "definitely a car bomb." Police and
security forces were on high alert Monday in major cities, fearing
that terrorist groups might attempt to finish what they called the
botched terror attack.
</P>
<P>
Exactly one year ago on the Jewish calendar, a suicide bombing
killed 16 and injured hundreds of others in an open market in
Jerusalem. Hamas claimed responsibility for that attack.
</P>
<P>
The Sunday incident also happened just hours before the
Israelis and the Palestinians would hold their first high-level
talks in months. Sources said that the attempted attack was aimed
at preventing progress in the talks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
