<HEADLINE> Palestinians to Reject Israeli Proposals: Sources </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 21 (Xinhua) -- The Palestinians will reject
Israeli proposals on its second redeployment during the next round
of direct talks later Tuesday, reliable Palestinian sources said.
</P>
<P>
Following consultation with Palestinian National Authority
Chairman Yasser Arafat's office, the Palestinian negotiators have
decided to officially turn down the Israeli proposals during the
imminent third round of talks, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that the Israeli team proposed at the last
meeting that Israel carry out a 10 percent withdrawal and turn
the other 3 percent into "nature reserves," where no construction
(of Jewish settlements) will be permitted.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Israel backed down from the demand that Arafat
convene the 460-member Palestinian National Council to reaffirm
the deletion of the clauses in the Palestinian Covenant that call
for Israel's destruction. They suggested that they agree to a
ratification of the changes by the smaller 100-member Palestinian
Liberation Organization Central Committee.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian-Israeli third round of talks will be held at a
kibbutz near Jerusalem where the second round was secretly held
Monday night. The discussions were aimed at reaching agreement on
an American initiative calling on Israel to withdraw from 13.1
percent more of the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
The disclosure of the Palestinian intention to reject Israeli
proposals came amid reports that the Palestinians are prepared to
compromise on the issue of "natural reserve."
</P>
<P>
The talks which began Sunday were the first direct negotiations
between senior Palestinian and Israeli officials in months.
Israeli negotiators described the second round as "very good."
They said the Palestinians responded favorably to their proposals.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians, however, have repeatedly emphasized that the
percentages in the American initiative were "non-negotiable."
</P>
</TEXT>
