<DOCNO> XIE19980722.0027 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Reinforcement of EC-ACP Partnership Calls for </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, July 21 (Xinhua) -- Acting Head of the European
Commission (EC) delegation, Paul Malin Tuesday said the major aim
of future partnership with the African, Carribean and the Pacific
(ACP) states should be to contribute to a global policy of peace
and security.
</P>
<P>
Malin said the the EC had prepared proposals which aimed at
reinforcing the political dimension of European Union-ACP
relations.
</P>
<P>
"Promoting a stable and democratic political environment
conducive to fundamental freedom, the rule of law and good
governance are not only preconditions for the success of
development policies, but they also form an integral part of our
objectives," Malin said.
</P>
<P>
He was presenting a paper on the EU position on post-Lome
Convention negotiations at a workshop organized by the Southern
African Development Community in Harare, the Zimbabwe News
Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Lome conventions are a set of trade arrangements signed in
1975 between ACP states and the EU.
</P>
<P>
The pact will expire in February 2000 and a negotiations for a
successor arrangement will begin in September.
</P>
<P>
Malin said, "We see the expiry of the Lome Convention as a
unique opportunity to rethink and fundamentally adapt our policy.
This convention is an important facet of the EU's external
policy."
</P>
<P>
He said the new partnership should prioritize conflict
prevention and seek ways of dealing with the underlying causes of
violent conflicts.
</P>
<P>
There was also need to refocus the partnership on the
elimination of poverty and to reform management of financial
cooperation, he added.
</P>
<P>
The EU was also proposing a major innovative approach to trade
and economic cooperation.
</P>
<P>
"Under the Lome Convention, trade cooperation largely takes
the forms of preferential tariffs. In future, economic and trade
cooperation should consist of a more comprehensive set of
arrangements," Malin said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980722.0028 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Fed Chief Says Ready to Combat Inflation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 21 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Federal Reserve Chairman
Alan Greenspan said here Tuesday that the central bank was ready
to "resist vigorously" any threatened increase in inflation.
</P>
<P>
While delivering his mid-year report to the Senate Banking
Committee, Greenspan indicated that central bank policy-makers
were more concerned about a potential outbreak of inflation than
they were about the current dramatic slowdown in economic
activity.
</P>
<P>
"Given the current tightness in labor markets, the potential
for accelerating inflation is probably greater than the risk of
protracted, excessive weakness in the economy," he said.
</P>
<P>
Even with his warnings about inflation risks, Greenspan gave no
indication that an increase in interest rates is imminent.
</P>
<P>
The testimony Tuesday stood in contrast to Greenspan's last
economic report to Congress, in February. At that time, the Fed
chairman said the risks appeared equally balanced between higher
inflation coming from the tight labor markets and greater economic
weakness coming from the fallout of the Asian currency crisis.
</P>
<P>
Since then, the U.S. economy has boomed, with overall output of
goods and services rising at an annual rate of 5.4 percent in the
first three months of the year. That surge of growth pushed
unemployment down to a 28-year-low 4.3 percent in the spring.
</P>
<P>
"As evidence piled up that the economy continued to run hot
during the winter, the Federal Reserve's concerns about
inflationary pressures mounted," Greenspan said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Because of the strong growth and low unemployment, Greenspan
said that Fed policy-makers moved in March to a "state of
heightened alert against inflation."
</P>
<P>
The central bank has not changed interest rates since March
1997, when it boosted the federal funds rate by a quarter-point to
5.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
For the past 16 months, the Fed has maintained the rates steady
as inflation has been well tamed. Consumer prices for the first
six months of this year, helped by plunging oil prices, have risen
at an annual rate of just 1.4 percent, even lower than the
11-year best of 1.7 percent in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Greenspan acknowledged that some economists were forecasting the
gross domestic product might have actually declined in the
just-completed April-June quarter, the first time that has
occurred since the end of the 1990-91 recession. But he said that
special factors were involved, including a need to work off a huge
increase in unsold goods from the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
Even if the GDP rate dropped in the second quarter, it should
not be the cause for undue concern because, Greenspan said.
"Underlying trends in domestic final demand have remained strong,
imparting impetus to the continuing economic expansion," he added.
</P>
<P>
Greenspan also acknowledged in his testimony to Congress that
considerable uncertainty remained about effects of the Asian
crisis, especially with respect to spreading economic weakness in
Japan, the world's second-largest economy.
</P>
<P>
The Fed chief warned, "The risks of further adverse
developments in these economies remain substantial." He said Fed
policy-makers were aware that raising U.S. interest rates "could
have outsized effects on the very sensitive financial markets in
Asia, a development that could have substantial repercussions on
U.S. financial markets and, over time, on our own economy."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980722.0029 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> German Money Supply Registers Quick Expansion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, July 21 (Xinhua) -- Germany's M3 money supply registered
a clear increase in June, expanding by an annual rate of 5.3
percent compared with the 4.4 percent recorded in May, the German
central bank Bundesbank announced Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The M3 money supply, the broad measure of money circulating in
the economy, serves as the German central bank's key indicator of
the country's inflation trends, which could influence its
decisions on interest rates.
</P>
<P>
Despite the latest increase, experts said they did not expect
an interest rate hike in Germany because the M3 growth rate was
still within the target range of 3 to 6 percent set by the
Bundesbank for this year.
</P>
<P>
The Bundesbank said that the money supply expansion in June was
boosted by higher borrowings by the public sector. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980722.0030 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-21 17:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cypriot Government Ready to Resume </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, July 21 (Xinhua) -- The Cypriot government Tuesday
reiterated its willingness to resume the U.N.-sponsored
negotiations for a solution to the Cyprus problem.
</P>
<P>
The government's position was outlined by Foreign Minister
Ioannis Kasoulides in a meeting with the visiting European Union
(EU) envoy for Cyprus David Hannay, who arrived here Monday for a
three-day visit.
</P>
<P>
"I was given the opportunity to repeat our side's readiness
to participate in a dialog for the solution to the Cyprus
problem, based on U.N. resolutions, at any time," Kasoulides
told reporters after the meeting.
</P>
<P>
The Cyprus peace talks hit a snag last July after Turkish
Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash walked out of the U.N.-sponsored
peace talks with Greek Cypriot leader Glafcos Clerides to protest
against an EU decision to start accession talks with the
Clerides-led Cypriot government.
</P>
<P>
Denktash has said he will not participate in intercommunal
peace talks unless his breakaway entity in northern part of the
island is recognized and Cyprus withdraws its application to join
the EU.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the Cypriot government's invitation to Turkish
Cypriots to participate in the EU negotiations, Kasoulides said
that despite the negative developments in efforts to settle the
Cyprus problem "we are ready to talk to them, if they accept
President Clerides' invitation."
</P>
<P>
Cyprus opened accession talks with the EU in March 1998, but
the Turkish Cypriot side has turned down an invitation from
Clerides to nominate representatives in the official negotiating
team.
</P>
<P>
On security matters, Kasoulides underlined the government's
concern for security, but said it would never take measures that
would lead to tension or are beyond its legal rights.
</P>
<P>
He noted that U.S. State Department Special Coordinator for
Cyprus, Thomas Miller, is expected to discuss security issues
during his brief Cyprus trip beginning on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. and some EU countries have criticized Cypriot
government's decision to buy Russian-made surface-to-air S-300
missiles in a bid to boost its air defenses.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has threatened to strike the missiles if they are
deployed, but the Cypriot government has said that it would not
cancel the missile plan unless progress is made in resuming the
stalled peace talks and on its proposal for demilitarizing the
island.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has remained divided since 1974 when Turkey landed its
troops and took over the northern third of the island in the wake
of short-lived pro-Athens coup in Nicosia.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has maintained a 35,000-strong forces in Northern
Cyprus, which was declared unilaterally in 1983 by Turkish
Cypriots as a breakaway "Turkish Republic of Northern Cyprus",
recognized only by Ankara. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
