<HEADLINE> IBM Services Business Growing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, Julys 21 (Xinhua) -- U.S. International Business
Machines Corp. (IBM) is earning more and more from international
computer technology services although its sales of computers and
software have been hurt by the Asian economic slump.
</P>
<P>
IBM, best known as a company making computers and software,
reported late Monday that its revenue from the global services
unit increased by 22 percent in the second quarter. The unit has
been helping larger corporations set up computer systems and
networks worldwide.
</P>
<P>
As dispensing high-tech advice has become an increasingly
important money-maker for the world's computer giant, IBM was less
hurt by slower sales of personal computer, price wars in computer
chips and reduced consumer demand for products in a wave of Asian
economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
Overall, IBM said that its profits were flat in the second
quarter. The results slightly beat Wall Street forecasts.
</P>
<P>
IBM's stock rose 6.8 percent, or 8.25 U.S. dollars per share,
to 130.25 U.S. dollars on the New York Stock Exchange Tuesday
morning. 
</P>
</TEXT>
