<DOCNO> XIE19980722.0032 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dutch Budget Deficit Down to 0.9 Pct in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, July 21 (Xinhua) -- The Dutch national budget deficit
in 1997 accounted for 0.9 percent of the gross domestic product,
lower than the forecast made this March, it was announced Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The Statistics Netherlands in the National Accounts reported
that the 1997 government's budget deficit declined to 0.9 percent,
from 2 percent a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
It was the lowest level since 1977, the statistical bureau
said.
</P>
<P>
The March deficit forecast of 1.4 percent enabled the
Netherlands to meet the criteria for entry into the European
Economic and Monetary Union or better known as the single currency
mechanism, euro.
</P>
<P>
Lower interest rates, the Statistics Netherlands claimed, were
the chief reason behind the fall in the deficit while at 3.6
percent, the rate of economic growth in the country was well above
the average of the 15-nation European Union, which was also part
of the reason for the decline.
</P>
<P>
The union-wide economic growth was at 2.6 percent in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Exports, especially of chemicals and metal products, made the
biggest contribution to the acceleration in growth last year.
</P>
<P>
But the statistical bureau admitted that Dutch households drew
less benefit from the economic growth than did the government and
business community despite the fact that interest and profit
distributions received from abroad reached record levels. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
