<HEADLINE> Nigerian Military Ready to Go Back to Barricks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 21 (Xinhua) -- The Nigerian military, which has ruled
the most populous African country for more than a decade, is "really
and very prepared" to go back to the barricks, a presidency spokesman
said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
David Attah, Chief Press Secretary to the head of state, made the
remarks in the capital Abuja one day after General Abdulsalam Abubakar
announced that the military government will handover power to an
elected civilian president next May.
</P>
<P>
The press secretary refuted the speculation that some members of
the military do not want to go back to the barracks while others think
the army is the only institution that can keep Nigeria together.
</P>
<P>
"I don't think that is the correct reflection of the situation in
the military today," Attah said.
</P>
<P>
In fact, the military believes "it's about time they went back to
the barracks. It's not just physical movement. It is equally
psychological. They are really and very well prepared for this."
</P>
<P>
They also believe that the wind of change that is blowing across
Nigeria is very positive, he said, adding: "The prospect of the future
society of Nigeria is very great."
</P>
<P>
The press secretary also dismissed the saying that the announcement
of the military's new transition to civil rule program by General
Abubakar is simply a case of making the best out of the bad job.
</P>
<P>
"It's more than making the best out of a situation as some of the
policies initiated are very profound in the meaning of significance,"
Attah said.
</P>
<P>
According to him, broad consultations have been held involving
every one without conflict before arriving at such major decisions,
including the release of all political prisoners, the dissolution of
the political parties and transitional institution set up before
Abubakar and the cancelation of all elections.
</P>
<P>
Currently the interantional response to the new transition program
is generally positive while there are mixed reactions among Nigerians.
</P>
<P>
Some politicians welcome the new timetable while others insist that
Abacha keep to the October 1 this year deadline set by his predecessor
General Sani Abacha.  
</P>
