<HEADLINE> Israeli Labor Party to Motion for Early Elections </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 21 (Xinhua) -- Israeli opposition Labor Party
will present a bill to the Knesset (parliament) next Wednesday
calling for early general elections.
</P>
<P>
According to a report of Israel Radio, the move was announced
by Labor whip Micha Goldman on Tuesday after his meeting with
Knesset Speaker Dan Tichon.
</P>
<P>
This came after threats by several ruling coalition partners to
oust Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu over a U.S. proposal on the
next redeployment of Israeli troops in the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
Goldman said that before next Wednesday, the last day of the
Knesset summer session, it would be clear whether an agreement
with the Palestinians would be reached on the further withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
Then the coalition parties should redeem their pledges and
topple the current government for holding early elections, he said.
</P>
<P>
Israeli-Palestinian negotiators restarted their direct talks on
Sunday after the peace process has been stalled for months due to
Israel's intransigent policy.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu, who had been resisting the U.S. proposal calling for
a 13 percent Israeli pullback, now wants to reach an agreement
with the Palestinians on something watered down under
international pressure.
</P>
<P>
The right wing in the Netanyahu government, however, rejected
any yield to pressure. Rafael Eitan, the Tzomet Party leader,
warned Monday that the government would be brought down if the
scope of the second redeployment would be more than 7 percent.
</P>
<P>
On the other side, the dovish Third Way Party has also threaten
that the party would leave the coalition government if no progress
was made in the negotiations with the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
Currently, Netanyahu government has only a slim majority of 61
in the 120-seat Knesset. The departure of any coalition member
will force his government to step down. 
</P>
