<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe's Manufacturing, Mining Sectors Operate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, July 21 (Xinhua) -- Studies show that between 72
percent and 73 percent of Zimbabwe's manufacturing and mining
firms, operated below capacity in the first four months of the
year.
</P>
<P>
The Central Statistical Office (CSO) Tuesday said although the
trend showed an improvement in business sentiment compared with
the previous survey done in December last year, companies in the
two sectors, Zimbabwe's key economic sectors, indicated
lower intentions to invest this year.
</P>
<P>
"Negative balances of 26 percent and 75 percent for firms in
manufacturing and mining respectively indicated that their order
books were below normal," the CSO said.
</P>
<P>
"Firms in manufacturing and mining indicated that they had a
drop in orders and deliveries for both the home and export
markets in the four months ending April 1998," it said, adding
that the trend was likely to continue until August.
</P>
<P>
Employment levels in manufacturing and mining also dropped as
weak demand on both domestic and export markets, as well as
cash-flow difficulties, continued to be major constraints
affecting industry.
</P>
<P>
A total of 164 companies out of 204 firms approached responded
to the CSO survey.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe's business sector is struggling to survive high
interest rates in the region of 40 percent, rising inflation, an
unstable currency and a weak domestic market.
</P>
<P>
Local analysts said gross domestic product growth will be 2.5
percent this year compared with 3.7 percent last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
