<HEADLINE> Iraq Warns: No Longer Accept U.N. Sanctions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, July 21 (Xinhua) -- Iraq warned on Tuesday that it can
no longer accept the U.N. sanctions, Iraqi News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The warning was announced at Tuesday's joint meeting of the
powerful Revolution Command Council and the ruling Baath Party,
chaired by President Saddam Hussein.
</P>
<P>
The joint meeting warned that Iraq can no longer accept that
the United States or U.N. Special Commission (UNSCOM) on
disarmament in Iraq) "uses flimsy, minor or fabricated pretext as
covers to mar Iraq's position and distract the attention of the
public opinion with the end of prolonging the sanctions."
</P>
<P>
The meeting discussed Iraq's relationship with the
U.N. Security Council and UNSCOM in the light of Saddam's speech
on the 30th anniversary of July 17-30 Revolution and the open
letter to the U.N. Security Council and the secretary-general on
May 1 this year.
</P>
<P>
In a nationally broadcast speech on the 30th anniversary of
July 17-30 revolution, the Iraqi president vowed to have the
U.N. sanctions imposed after Iraq's 1990 invasion of Kuwait lifted
in 1998.
</P>
<P>
Saddam, in that speech, also mentioned the open letter
addressed to the U.N. Security Council and the secretary-general,
which demanded immediate lifting of trade embargo as a prelude to
lift the overall sanctions.
</P>
<P>
He warned that Iraq will consider "alternative strategy" if its
cooperation with UNSCOM can not bring about the lifing of
sanctions.
</P>
<P>
The Tuesday meeting also announced that "the fact that all that
has been implemented by Iraq of requirements under Security
Council resolution 687 (on disarmament in Iraq) over a span of
more than seven years necessitate the immediate lifting of the
sanctions."
</P>
<P>
The joint meeting also warned that anyone, "with the intention
of obstructing the lifting of sanctions or prolonging them would
be met with firm opposition by the people and leadership of Iraq,"
adding "Iraqi leadership will continue watching the situation and
will take the appropriate action to handle it."
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi leadership issued this stern warning just after
UNSCOM announced that its head Richard Butler would visit Baghdad
early next month to hold talks with Iraqi Deputy Prime Minister
Tariq Aziz.
</P>
<P>
During his last Baghdad trip in June, Butler and the Iraqi
side agreed upon a working program for two months. Butler said in
Baghdad that "the light at the end of tunnel (of disarmament) is
more visible" than ever before.
</P>
<P>
However, it was reported that an American army laboratory had
found traces of deadly VX gas on some remnant of Iraqi missile
warheads. Butler also said he had no doubt about the findings.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has admitted experimenting with VX gas, but denies it
ever deployed the gas in weapons. 
</P>
</TEXT>
