<HEADLINE> Iraq Complains About Delay in Spare Parts Delivery </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, July 21 (Xinhua) -- An Iraqi oil official complained
Tuesday about the delay by foreign companies in delivering the
badly-needed spare parts for its oil sector.
</P>
<P>
General Director of Planning and Studying Department of the Oil
Ministry Falih Hasan Marhon said that although Iraq had signed 70
contracts valued at 70 million U.S. dollars with foreign firms to
import spare parts, no spare parts had been delivered so far.
</P>
<P>
Under the fourth phase of oil-for-food deal approved by the
United Nations, Iraq is allowed to export 5.2 billion dollars
worth of oil to buy food, medicine and other humanitarian supplies
for its suffering people.
</P>
<P>
But Iraq has repeatedly said that it cannot meet the export
target due to the severe lack of spare parts in its oil sector and
the sharp decline of oil prices on world markets.
</P>
<P>
At the suggestion of a U.N. team of oil experts, the
U.N. Security Council allowed Iraq to import 300 million dollars
worth of oil spare parts to increase its oil production and
exporting capacity.
</P>
<P>
Marhon said that the 300 million dollars cannot meet even the
minimum need of its oil sector, which has been badly effected by
the eight-year crippling U.N. economic sanctions imposed in 1990
after its invasion of Kuwait. 
</P>
