<HEADLINE> Oversupply Threatening Tea Price </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, July 21 (Xinhua) -- Over-production of tea is
threatening to push the price of the crop down on the world
market, United Kingdom-based tea council chief executive Illtyd
Lewis said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Lewis said tea had the potential to seek three times more than
its current average price but there was need to keep a check on
production levels to prevent oversupply.
</P>
<P>
He was addressing journalists at a news conference here in
Harare.
</P>
<P>
At the moment world tea production stands at 2.5 million tons
per year while the average price is between 1.94 U.S. Dollars and
2.22 U.S. Dollars per kilogram.
</P>
<P>
"Although the surplus has been small over the last 10 years at
an average of 100,000 tons per annum, this still has the
potential to depress the price of tea which is very volatile," he
said.
</P>
<P>
"We have to keep production levels at reasonable figures to
keep the demand for tea high," he said.
</P>
<P>
He added that tea was facing stiff competition from carbonated
soft drinks, a trend which also threatened the viability of the
crop.
</P>
<P>
The food agricultural organisation in conjuction with the tea
council have embarked on a 200,000 U.S. Dollar campaign to
promote tea as a healthy drink in a bid to keep demand high, he
said.
</P>
<P>
The)dda council is a non-profit making organisation sponsored
by governments of all countries exporting tea to the U.K.
</P>
</TEXT>
