<HEADLINE> Malawi Top in Sub-Saharan Africa on Reproductive </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 21 (Xinhua) -- Wide media coverage and concerted
efforts by government and non-governmental organizations (NGOs)
on reproductive health has put Malawi among twenty three top
Sub-Saharan African countries, a Malawian minister said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Malawian Minister of State in the office of the president and
cabinet responsible for human resource, management and
development, Edda Chitalo said this upon her return from Port
Louis, Mauritius where she had attended a conference for female
ministers and parliamentarians in Sub-Saharan Africa on
reproductive health.
</P>
<P>
Malawi News Agency quoted Chitalo as saying that the week-long
conference in Mauritius had been convened to review the
implementation of what the countries in the region have embarked
upon in terms of reproductive health.
</P>
<P>
"The conference was aimed at looking at the progress female
parliamentarians are making to assist women in reproductive
health," Chitalo said, adding that the conference also drew up a
declaration on women, reproductive health and rights.
</P>
<P>
Among other things, the Malawian female minister said, the
participants agreed in principle to act on a program to help
girls to avoid early marriages and also to sensitize them on
their rights concerning marriage.
</P>
<P>
Women should exercise their rights of the freedom to marry,
whom to marry and also decide how many children they are to bear,
Chitalo said, adding that "such a domain should not be a monopoly
of men."
</P>
<P>
The minister said that Malawi won applause at the conference
for its efforts in the field of reproductive health which has
been tremendously successful because of the joint efforts by the
government and other NGOs.
</P>
<P>
"Apart from reproductive health, the Malawian government was
also hailed for its tireless efforts in the promotion of girls'
attainment of basic literacy education," Chitalo added. 
</P>
