<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jordan's Aqaba Airport to Lift Limitation on </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, July 21 (Xinhua) -- The airport in Jordan's Red Sea port
city of Aqaba will soon start to accept passengers of different
nationalities and allow them to travel to either Aqaba, Amman or
the Israeli city of Eilat.
</P>
<P>
"After three years of heated arguments, we managed to convince
the Israelis that carrying passengers of different nationalities
would not be dangerous for Israel's national security," the
semi-official Jordan Times Tuesday quoted Director General of
Jordanian Civil Aviation's Jasser Zayyad as saying.
</P>
<P>
Jordan signed an agreement with Israel on the joint operation
of the Aqaba airport in August 1997, allowing international
flights to Eilat to use the Aqaba airfield. This was aimed at
easing the over-crowding of the Israeli airport at Eilat, a
booming tourism city situated just across the Jordanian border.
</P>
<P>
But the old agreement only permitted passengers of certain
nationalities destined for Israel to transit the airport.
</P>
<P>
By opening Aqaba and Amman to passengers transiting the
airport, Jordan wants not only to collect landing fees, but also
to encourage passengers to come to Jordan as well, said Zayyad
during his meeting with a visiting Israeli aviation delegation.
</P>
<P>
"The new terms of the agreement will help boost the tourism in
Aqaba and create more jobs in the port city," said Zayyad.
</P>
<P>
Zayyad also urged the Israelis to allow an increase in
passenger capacity and frequency of cargo flights between the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
Further subcommittees from both sides will meet to discuss the
implementation of the new terms of the agreements in the coming
weeks.
</P>
<P>
Israel used to divert three flights a week to the Aqaba
airport, but with the implementation of the new terms, the number
will be decreased to one each week. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980722.0047 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-22 </DATE_TIME>
