<HEADLINE> Nigeria's 1st New Party Launched </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 21 (Xinhua) -- Less than 24 hours after the
Nigerian military administration scrapped former political
parties for new ones to come for fresh elections, the first party
was launched here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The Democratic Advance Movement (DAM) was launched by a
Lagos-based lawyer and politician Tuesday morning, prior to the
announcement by the to-be-constituted electoral commission of
guidelines for the formation of parties.
</P>
<P>
The organizer whose name was yet unavailable said that he had
formed the party and picked the date for the launching before
Head of State General Abdulsalam Abubakar made his nationally
televised address Monday night.
</P>
<P>
In the eight-page broadcast speech which took 40 minutes,
Abubakar announced the shift of date of the military's hand-over
to civilian rule from October 1 this year to May 29 next year.
</P>
<P>
He also announced the dissolution of the five registered
parties and transition institutions set up under his predecessor
late General Sani Abacha.
</P>
<P>
All elections which had been conducted on the basis of the
parties and institutions were also cancelled.
</P>
<P>
According to Abubakar, an independent electoral commission
will be constituted soon to supervise the coming elections.
</P>
<P>
International response to Abubakar's new transition program is
generally positive so far, while there are mixed reactions among
Nigerian politicians.  
</P>
</TEXT>
