<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, July 21 (Xinhua) - The Zanzibar government is
seeking funds to remove its headquarters from the centuries-old
houses in the famous Stone Town to a new place, sources from
Zanzibar said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The Minister of State in the Chief Minister's Office, Iddi
Pandu Hassan, was quoted by the sources as addressing the House
of Representatives on Monday that the move to build new buildings
for the government headquarters at the Chuini area, a few
kilometers from the Stone Town, was aimed at abandoning the
dilapidated buildings.
</P>
<P>
"Almost all buildings housing public offices in the Stone Town
have been built before the 19th century and most of them are on
the verge of collapse due to lack of repair for a long time,"
Hassan said.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that several workers of the Communications and
Transport Ministry cheated death a few month ago when their
offices, which are in a state of disrepair, sagged.
</P>
<P>
The minister said that the government will look for temporary
alternative offices to protect its assets and staff.
</P>
<P>
Lying in the west of the Indian Ocean and 40 kilometers off
the mid-Tanzanian coast, Zanzibar consists of Unguja, its sister
island Pemba and dozens of small isles.
</P>
<P>
It is famous for the Stone Town with Arab style, the widely
planted cloves and the clear and smooth beaches. 
</P>
