<HEADLINE> Russian, German Defense Chiefs Discuss Kosovo, </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, July 21 (Xinhua) -- The defense ministers of Russia and
Germany Tuesday called for a political settlement to the Kosovo
conflict that is threatening to spill over the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
Russian Defense Minister Igor Sergeyev and his German
counterpart, Volker Ruehe, held an informal meeting in the Russian
resort city of Sochi, the Interfax news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Sergeyev described the talks as successful and constructive,
adding that "in the course of the meeting our positions became
closer."
</P>
<P>
The two discussed implementation of understandings on
cooperation of defense and defense technology, Sergeyev said.
</P>
<P>
The views of Moscow and Bonn on Kosovo largely coincide, but
Germany has "its own accents," Ruehe said.
</P>
<P>
Kosovo is a region in the Yugoslav republic of Serbia. Ethnic
Albanians, which account for 90 percent of the total population
there, are seeking independence.
</P>
<P>
Armed clashes between militant Albanians and the Yugoslav
security forces have resulted in dozens of deaths.
</P>
<P>
Tension increased over the weekend when the Kosovo Liberation
Army (KLA), the armed wing of the Albanian separatists, tried to
storm a police station in Orahovac and capture its first town in
the five-month conflict.
</P>
<P>
Ruehe said neither Serbia nor the ethnic Albanians can maintain
the status quo in Kosovo on their own.
</P>
<P>
Both Russia and Germany are members of the five-nation Contact
Group seeking peace in the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
The Russian defense minister said developments in Kosovo
threaten peace in the Balkans and reinforcements for the KLA are
arriving.
</P>
<P>
"This jeopardizes attempts to settle the conflict," Sergeyev
said.
</P>
<P>
In a related development, Russian Foreign Ministry spokesman
Vladimir Rakhmanin hinted Tuesday that Moscow would not object if
a political party representing the KLA took part in negotiations
with the Yugoslav government.
</P>
<P>
However, the spokesman said "Russia's conviction that it is
political parties that should represent the Kosovo Albanians at
negotiations with Belgrade remains unchanged," Interfax reported.
</P>
</TEXT>
