<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Congressmen, Business Urge Congress for Renewed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 21 (Xinhua) -- Some congressmen and small
American business Tuesday urged Congress to vote for China's
renewed Most-Favored Nation (MFN) trading status.
</P>
<P>
Representative Philip M. Crane, chairman of the House Committee
on Ways and Means, told a press conference on the Capitol Hill,
"Normal trade with China is the right policy for America and the
best way to expand democratic values and freedom for the Chinese
people."
</P>
<P>
The House is scheduled to vote Wednesday on President Bill
Clinton's decision to renew China's MFN for another year. Clinton
informed Congress of his determination in early June.
</P>
<P>
"Trade with China is also the right policy for hundreds of
thousands of American families and jobs," Crane told the press
conference sponsored by the powerful U.S. Chamber of Commerce.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Chamber of Commerce, representing more than 3 million
businesses and organizations, released a report at the conference
entitled "Small Business Success Stories in China" one day before
the House vote.
</P>
<P>
"I'm proud to be with the U.S. Chamber of Commerce to highlight
how U.S.-China trade has helped American small business," said
Crane, who is from the state of Illinois where over 1 billion U.S.
dollars of products were exported to China last year.
</P>
<P>
He added that the timing of this vote is "critical in light of
the Asian economic crisis." "We must reassure our friends in that
region that America will not turn its back at this sensitive
stage."
</P>
<P>
Representative Calvin Dooley from California also expressed
support for the renewal of China's MFN, believing that both
peoples of the United States and China benefit from a normal trade
relationship.
</P>
<P>
Dooley's home state earned more than 2.27 billion dollars from
exports to China in 1997. He said that it is important to continue
the trade ties and contribute to financial stability in Asia.
</P>
<P>
Willard Workman, chamber vice president for international
policy, introduced several small business representatives at the
press conference, calling them "prime examples of the successes
resulting from continued trade with China."
</P>
<P>
"Clearly, American companies of all sizes and the workers they
employ have a stake in the expansion of China trade. Last year
alone, the U.S. exported 12.8 billion dollars in goods and
services to China, supporting thousands of high-wage American
jobs," said Workman.
</P>
<P>
He urged the congressmen to "remember these small businesses
around the country that have invested people, time and capital
into building a trade relationship with China."
</P>
<P>
It is said that some 30 percent of the U.S. exports to China
were conducted by the small businesses in 1997. Their business
volume doubled in the past decade.
</P>
<P>
Asked if the vote in Congress would be affected by the alleged
political contribution and possible satellite technology transfer
to China, Crane said that the allegations have to prove factual.
</P>
<P>
Representative Dooley believed that President Clinton's recent
visit to China has eased much of the people's anxiety.
</P>
<P>
Workman predicted that the voting result would be of little
difference from the 259-173 of last year because the people have
been alerted to the Asian financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
The Congressmen "must remember that the people are going to
choose their congressional representatives later this year," he
told Xinhua after the press conference, referring to the mid-term
congressional election scheduled in November. 
</P>
</TEXT>
