<HEADLINE> Britain Unveils Crime Reduction Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 21 (Xinhua) -- The British government Tuesday
unveiled plans to spend 250 million pounds (some 410 million U.S.
dollars) over the next three years on a crime reduction strategy.
</P>
<P>
Home Secretary Jack Straw told parliament that the plans "will
be the first time a centrally coordinated program of such
magnitude... has been put in place anywhere in the world."
</P>
<P>
The program is based on a survey by officials at Straw's
ministry of the methods that work around the world in reducing
crime and disorder.
</P>
<P>
Straw said crime had been rising at an underlying rate of 5
percent a year in Britain since the 1920s.
</P>
<P>
"Increases in crime have, to many, appeared inexorable.... The
assumption has been that nothing works, that nothing could be done
to reverse this long-term rise in crime. I disagree," Straw said.
</P>
<P>
The Home Office was allocated an extra 3 billion pounds (4.92
billion dollars) early this month by the Finance Ministry over the
next three years in anti-crime push in the country.
</P>
<P>
According to Straw, the program will tackle the social causes
of crime, target crime "hot spots" and work to combat repeated
attacks on victims.
</P>
<P>
It will also focus on burglary and on work with offenders to
cut re-offending.
</P>
<P>
The police would get an extra 1.2 billion pounds (1.968 billion
dollars) over three years, and the Probation Service is to get an
extra 127 million pounds (208.28 million dollars), Straw said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
