<HEADLINE> Egypt Starts Land Reclamation Via Huge Projects </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 21 (Xinhua) -- Egypt has embarked on several huge
projects to turn its uninhabited deserts into a valuable source of
energy, food and dwelling space for a surging population in the
coming century.
</P>
<P>
This was announced by Egyptian Prime Minister Kamal el-Ganzouri
Tuesday before the Major National Projects Committee of the ruling
National Democratic Party (NDP).
</P>
<P>
"The aim of these mammoth national projects in various parts of
Egypt is to increase the inhabited area in the coming 20 years to
27.5 percent (of the whole land) compared to no more than 5
percent at present," he said.
</P>
<P>
Among these projects is the cultivation of altogether 1.678
million feddans (704,760 hectares), respectively at Toshka in the
southern desert, in the areas along Al Salam canal in the
northeast, in the Dakhla and Kharga oases in the Western Desert,
and in the northwestern desert area along the Mediterranean.
</P>
<P>
The canal being built at the Toshka area is designed to pump 5
billion cubic meters of water a year from Lake Nasser into the
Western Desert to bring 1 million feddans (420,000 hectares) under
cultivation in several decades.
</P>
<P>
Uninhabited deserts account for some 95 percent of Egypt's 1
million square kilometers, of which only 35,189 square kilometers,
that is 3.6 percent are populated.
</P>
<P>
The pinch of a dwindling share of resources is acutely felt as
the population which is over 60 million, is growing at the rate of
2.1 percent per year at which it can be expected to double every
30 years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
