<HEADLINE> U.S. Exploring Alternative Way for Lockerbie Trial </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 21 (Xinhua) -- The United States said Tuesday
it was exploring the possibility of trying two Libyans suspected
of the Lockerbie explosion in a third country before a Scottish
judge and under Scottish procedures.
</P>
<P>
State Department spokesman James Rubin told reporters that the
United States still insisted that the two Libyan men "must face
justice before British or Scottish courts," but said it was
considering whether a trial could be held in a third country under
Scottish procedures and before a Scottish judge.
</P>
<P>
In effect, Rubin said, the venue would still be a Scottish
court. "If it were in another location, it is still a Scottish
court. The point is to bring them to justice," he said.
</P>
<P>
Rubin was speaking at a briefing after Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright and National Security Adviser Sandy Berger
spoke to 11 relatives of 270 victims of the 1988 bombing of Pan Am
flight 103 over the Scottish town of Lockerbie.
</P>
<P>
According to a relative called Rosemary Wolf, Albright and
Berger had told them "they were exploring options that would lead
to a Scottish, not an international, trial with Scottish judges
and Scottish law, in another country."
</P>
<P>
"They are talking to the Dutch to discuss conditions for a
Scottish court sitting in the Netherlands, but there has been no
resolution of this," she said.
</P>
<P>
Rubin confirmed that Washington had not made decision whether
it would take any practical alternative way other than its
position to try the two Libyans in Britain or the United States.
</P>
<P>
"We have been exploring alternative ways to bring the suspects
to justice," he said. "So far, we haven't found any practical
alternatives to a trial in the United States or Scotland."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
