<HEADLINE> Zambia Will Not Reintroduce Forex Control </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, July 21 (Xinhua) -- The Bank of Zambia Tuesday
reiterated that it will not reintroduce foreign exchange control
and assured investors that stability in the country's financial
market will soon be achieved, Zambia National Broadcasting
Corporation reported.
</P>
<P>
The central bank's governor Jacob Mwanza said in his official
opening speech at a one-day bond market workshop in Lusaka that
investors should not be frightened with the unstable foreign
currency flows in the country because the problem will be
overcome.
</P>
<P>
The Zambian government has no intention to reverse the
liberalization policies being pursued, he said, adding that the
central bank will continue with its monetary policies which are
already showing signs of growth.
</P>
<P>
Mwanza explained that the falling copper prices coupled with
dwindling donor funding are responsible for the shortage of forex
in the Zambian market.
</P>
<P>
He, however, said once the mines are privatised and donor
funding inflows stabilised, there will be enough forex in the
country to meet the demand.
</P>
<P>
In the past few months, copper prices have kept falling in the
world market, which is attributable to the acute shortage of
forex in Zambia since it depends heavily on the traditional
copper export.
</P>
<P>
Mwanza challenged the financial sector to come up with
financial managment styles that will suit the changing global
financial market and the needs of local investors. 
</P>
</TEXT>
