<HEADLINE> Burundi Peace Talks Prove Tough </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, July 21 (Xinhua) -- The second round of Burundi
peace talks started Tuesday in Arusha in north Tanzania, but
negotiations of conflicting parties, lasting three hours in the
morning, proved to be tough.
</P>
<P>
The bone of contention was whether the issue of "nature of the
conflict in Burundi" should be discussed at the plenary session
or at sub-committee level, reports reaching here said.
</P>
<P>
Sources attending the meeting, chaired by Tanzania's former
president Julius Nyerere, said that the Burundian government
officials at the peace talks are of the opinion that the issue
should be handled by a sub-committee and its proposals be
forwarded to the plenary session whereas the armed groups --
CNDD, FROLINA and PALIPEHUTU wanted it to be directly discussed
at the plenary session.
</P>
<P>
Nyerere, the international mediator on Burundi, adjourned the
meeting to allow leaders of all warring parties to discuss the
issue among themselves and propose their positions when plenary
session resumes on Wednesday morning.
</P>
<P>
Nineteen parties are taking part in the talks aimed at ending
a bitter ethnic conflict in which more than 150,000 people have
died since October 1993 in a series of bloody conflicts between
the Tutsi-dominated army and rebels who claim to represent the
country's Hutu majority. 
</P>
</TEXT>
