<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pentagon: No Evidence to Support CNN Allegations on </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 21 (Xinhua) -- A Pentagon review has found no
evidence to support allegations by CNN and Time magazine that U.S.
troops used sarin nerve gas during a 1970 operation in Laos to
hunt down American defectors, Defense Secretary William Cohen said
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The allegations were made during a report on "Operation
Tailwind" broadcast by CNN on June 7, followed by an article in
Time magazine under the bylines of two CNN employees. But by early
July, the network retracted the story.
</P>
<P>
"We studied scores of documents about 'Operation Tailwind,' and
conducted interviews with soldiers and officials at all levels of
command," Cohen said in a statement. "We found no evidence to
support the CNN/Time assertions on defectors or the use of sarin
nerve gas.
</P>
<P>
"No document -- military order, after-action report, briefing
paper or official military history -- mentions pursuit of U.S.
defectors as Tailwind's mission. While sarin was stored in Okinawa
in 1970, we found no evidence sarin nerve gas was ever sent to or
used in Vietnam or Laos," Cohen said at the Pentagon.
</P>
<P>
In its June 7 report, CNN alleged U.S. Special Forces troops
were put into Laos to locate and kill American defectors. It said
the troops destroyed a village and killed American defectors as
well as enemy troops and civilians. U.S. aircraft dropped the
sarin gas to suppress the enemy as the Americans were to be taken
from the scene by helicopter, the CNN report alleged.
</P>
<P>
The Pentagon study said the operation was launched as a
reconnaissance mission "to engage the enemy and to divert enemy
attention" from an offensive mission designed to gain control of
terrain in Laos.
</P>
<P>
"No records or personal recollections were discovered to
suggest that targeting U.S. defectors played any part in the
operation," the report said.
</P>
<P>
On the allegations of sarin use, the report noted that U.S.
policy since World War II had been to prohibit the use of lethal
chemical agents, unless first used by the enemy. "No evidence
could be found that the nerve agent sarin was ever transported to
Southeast Asia (Vietnam, Cambodia, Thailand).... No evidence could
be found that sarin was used in Operation Tailwind," the report
stated.
</P>
<P>
Air Force personnel involved in the mission have stated CS tear
gas was used, the study said.
</P>
<P>
Cohen ordered a Pentagon investigation shortly after the story
was broadcast.
</P>
<P>
In its retraction, CNN apologized for "serious faults" in its
reporting and that a CNN-requested investigation by a prominent
media attorney concluded that its joint "NewsStand" report with
Time magazine could not be supported.
</P>
<P>
The report's two main producers, Jack Smith and April Oliver,
were fired after a CNN-requested investigation by a prominent media
attorney. Senior producer Pam Hill resigned, while the lead
reporter, Peter Arnett, was reprimanded.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980722.0065 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chissano Calls for Dialog Among Govt., Employers, </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, July 21 (Xinhua) -- Mozambican President Joaquim
Chissano Tuesday called for dialog among the government,
employers and trade unions to resolve their disagreements.
</P>
<P>
Dialog should be considered as a major priority "weapon" in
solving the problems facing the government, employers and the
unions, Chissano said at the opening of the National Symposium on
the Role of Trade Unions in Mozambique's Development.
</P>
<P>
The president said that the improvement of the people's living
standards depends upon the concerted efforts by all walks of the
society.
</P>
<P>
Chissano praised the Mozambican people for their efforts in
the implementation of the structural adjustment, noting that the
economic policy is bearing fruits.
</P>
<P>
According to the figures released by the National Statistics
Bureau recently, the gross domestic product of the southern
African country grew by 14 percent last year. And it is predicted
that the growth rate will be 10 percent in 1998.
</P>
<P>
However, the president acknowledged that much has to be done
so that the economic growth can have a positive impact on the
living of the Mozambicans.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the issue of privatization, the Mozambican
president pointed out that the policy is in the interests of the
employed and can keep the vitality of the enterprises and it is
"the only option to overcome the difficulties facing the
industries."
</P>
<P>
It was reported that there are now 100,000 people who have
lost their jobs as a result of privatization and they complained
a lot.
</P>
<P>
Chissano called on all his people to come up with good ideas
to help their nation solve the social and economic problems.
</P>
<P>
With the support from the International Confederation of Free
Unions, the symposium was sponsored by the Mozambican
Organization of Workers.
</P>
<P>
Representatives from the government, employers and some unions
participated in the conference. The main purpose of the workshop
is to discuss the role of trade unions in the national
development.
</P>
<P>
The symposium was scheduled to end on Thursday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
