<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IMF Approves Three-Year ESAF Credit for Central </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 21 (Xinhua) -- The International Monetary Fund
(IMF) Tuesday approved a three-year credit under the Enhanced
Structural Adjustment Facility (ESAF) equivalent to about 66
million U.S. dollars to back the Central African Republic's
economic program for 1998-2000.
</P>
<P>
The first annual credit of about 22 million dollars is
available in two equal semiannual installments, the first of which
will be made available shortly.
</P>
<P>
The country's medium-term program seeks to maintain an average
annual real GDP growth of about 5 percent, stabilize inflation at
about 2.5 percent per annum, and contain the external current
account deficit at 5 percent of GDP by 2000.
</P>
<P>
Consistent with the strategy, the 1998 program projects a real
GDP growth of 5.5 percent, an inflation rate of 2.6 percent on an
average annual basis and an external account deficit of 6.1
percent of GDP, assuming a continuous strong growth in agriculture
and a recovery of manufacturing output.
</P>
<P>
Central African Republic joined the IMF in July 1963. Its quota
is about 55 million dollars and its outstanding use of IMF
financing currently totals about 10 million dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
