<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Updates Consumer Price Index Calculation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, July 22 (Xinhua) -- The European Commission welcomed
Wednesday a decision by the Council of Ministers to update the
consumer price index to make it a better measurement for
inflation.
</P>
<P>
European Monetary Commissioner Yves-Thibault de Silguy
described the ministers' decision as concrete progress toward
harmonized statistics in Europe.
</P>
<P>
"Accurate inflation statistics are vital for the European
Central Bank's management of monetary policy in the euro-zone from
January 1, 1999," said the commissioner.
</P>
<P>
He added that the EU inflation index, with the transformation
decided by the ministers Wednesday, will be more comprehensive
than most national consumer price indices.
</P>
<P>
The Council of Ministers decided to incorporate into the
European-wide inflation index financial services and cross-border
shopping as well.
</P>
<P>
The incorporation will fill the gaps in the existing Harmonized
Consumer Price Index (HCPI) which the European Central Bank will
use as a yardstick for its monetary policy.
</P>
<P>
Services, hitherto omitted like health, education, refuse
collection, sewage service, water supplies, social services and
house rentals, will be included in the index calculation starting
in December next year.
</P>
<P>
Cross-border shopping will also be covered by the HCPI in the
country where the purchase is made.
</P>
<P>
The two additions will make up 10 percent of the new HCPI.
</P>
<P>
Eurostat, the statistical bureau of the European communities,
publishes the HCPI every month for each of the 15 European Union
countries, the entire European Union and the 11-country euro-zone.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
