<HEADLINE> Philippine President Urges Amicable Settlement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 22 (Xinhua) -- President Joseph Estrada Wednesday
appealed to the management and striking employees of the
Philippine Airlines (PAL) to be open to an amicable settlement
since the continued labor unrest is harmful to the economy.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a news briefing, Estrada offered anew to mediate a
lasting solution to the indefinite strike staged by thousands of
ground crew of the national flag carrier starting Wednesday
morning.
</P>
<P>
Estrada invited the officers of the PAL Employees Association
(PALEA) to meet with him soon so they could discuss their
grievances and come up with a just and fair solution.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, Estrada ordered Labor Secretary Bienvenido
Laguesma to push a compromise formula that would ensure a lasting
resolution of the PAL row which, he said, was hurting the economy
and the tourism industry.
</P>
<P>
Laguesma said he might call a dialogue with management and
labor so they could work out a speedy settlement that is fair and
beneficial to all parties concerned.
</P>
<P>
Estrada has directed the Department of Transportation and
Communications to mobilize its resources in order to help stranded
passengers get to their destination.
</P>
<P>
Estrada said he had arranged to meet with PALEA officials last
week but they did not come, although he voiced the hope that they
would honor his invitation this time.
</P>
<P>
The PALEA went on strike early Wednesday morning in protest of
the retrenchment of some 5,000 employees who were fired last month
under a massive downsizing program.
</P>
<P>
The PAL began to massively downsize its operations after its
620 pilots staged a wildcat strike in early June, bringing huge
financial losses to the already financially-troubled airline.
</P>
<P>
The strike has delayed most of the PAL's international and
domestic flights. But the airline managed to mount all flights in
early evening except a U.S.-bound international flight. 
</P>
</TEXT>
