<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Surplus Spindles Move from Eastern China to Pakistan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
QINGDAO, July 22 (Xinhua) -- Another 50,000 spindles will soon
leave the bulky textile industry of the coastal city of Qingdao in
east China's Shandong Province.
</P>
<P>
Under the joint investment contract signed recently between
Qingdao cotton textile mills and a Pakistani partner, Qingdao will
contribute 50,000 spindles, 500 looms and other equipment,
equivalent to 40 percent of the venture's registered capital.
</P>
<P>
Thus far, 98,000 spindles were reduced in Qingdao in some six
months of this year alone.
</P>
<P>
Spindle-reduction is one of the essential measures needed to
allow China's textile industry to get out of the red. China is
expected to reduce its spindle supply by 10 million, and those
employed in the industry by 12 million, by the turn of the century.
</P>
<P>
Aside from simply destroying spindles, Qingdao city seeks to
move them to foreign countries whose textile industries do not
suffer from export quota limitations.
</P>
<P>
The massive transportation of 50,000 spindles follows the
movement of 20,000 spindles from the Qingdao No.9 Cotton Textile
Mill to Cambodia.
</P>
<P>
Under the recent pact, 23,000 spindles will be moved to the
Pakistan-China Cotton Textile Co., Ltd. Tuesday, and the remaining
27,000 will be arriving soon thereafter.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
