<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 1500 GMT July 22 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL -- South Korean President Kim Dae-jung will invite his
four predecessors to dinner about the end of July, a presidential
spokesman said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The invitation to Kim Young-sam, Roh Tae-woo, Chun Doo Hwan and
Choi Kyu-hah, all Kim's former rivals or oppressors, is an effort
to seek national harmony amid a downturn in the national
economy. (SKorea-President-Predecessors)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
SEOUL -- The Korean Confederation of Trade Unions (KCTU) said
Wednesday it will join the strike staged by the Korean Metal
Workers' Federation (KMWF) to protest rising unemployment.
</P>
<P>
About 6,500 KMWF members went on strike Wednesday,the second
strike organized by the federation within a week, despite
government warnings of tough action.
</P>
<P>
They will be joined by 600,000 members of the KCTU, said KCTU
chief Lee Kap-yong at a press conference. (SKorea-Strike)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
TEHRAN -- Iranian Foreign Minister Kamal Kharrazi reaffirmed
here Wednesday that Iran would answer the U.S. overture for a
rapprochement between the two rivals.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference, Kharrazi said that the promise
made by Iranian President Mohammad Khatami on July 1 to answer the
U.S. overture was still valid and "we will give the answer if
necessary." (Iran-US-Ties)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BEIJING -- Chinese and Russian foreign ministers urged India
and Pakistan Wednesday to enter into the Comprehensive Nuclear
Test Ban Treaty and the Nuclear Non-proliferation Treaty
unconditionally.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Foreign Minister Tang Jiaxuan and his Russian
counterpart Yevgeny Primakov discussed the recent nuclear tests
conducted by India and Pakistan during Wednesday's talks and
jointly reaffirmed their positions not to recognize India and
Pakistan as nuclear powers. (China-Russia-FMs-Talks)
