<HEADLINE> South Korea: 600,000 More Workers to Join Strike </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, July 22 (Xinhua) -- The Korean Confederation of Trade
Unions (KCTU) said Wednesday it will join the strike staged by the
Korean Metal Workers' Federation (KMWF) to protest rising
unemployment.
</P>
<P>
About 6,500 KMWF members went on strike Wednesday,the second
strike organized by the federation within a week, despite
government warnings of tough action.
</P>
<P>
They will be joined by 600,000 members of the KCTU, said KCTU
chief Lee Kap-yong at a press conference.
</P>
<P>
South Korea's unemployment rate had already shot up to 6.9
percent in May, as against just 2.6 percent in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Labor unions hold that the recent massive layoffs are in
violation of a labor-management-government accord that stipulates
the pain from economic reforms should be evenly distributed.
</P>
<P>
However, the government said the layoffs had been legalized.
</P>
<P>
The law enforcement authorities Wednesday renewed the
government's tough stand against illegal strikes at a meeting
attended by officials from the Prosecutor General's Office, the
National Police Agency, the Labor Ministry and the Agency for
National Security Planning.
</P>
<P>
The government has threatened to mobilize riot police to defuse
illegal strikes and take stern legal action against alleged
illegal strikers.
</P>
<P>
Under an agreement reached last December with the International
Monetary Fund for a bailout loan of 57 billion U.S. dollars, South
Korea has to restructure its economy, open markets and shut down
ailing financial institutions and companies this year.
</P>
<P>
In a restructuring program released last month, the government
ordered 55 manufacturing firms to be closed and forced five weak
banks to merge with stronger ones.
</P>
<P>
The government also decided to privatize 11 state firms,
including Pohang Iron and Steel Co., the world's second-largest
steel maker.
</P>
<P>
There is fear the restructuring program will leave an
increasing number of workers jobless. 
</P>
</TEXT>
