<HEADLINE> Mubarak Urges Israeli People to Promote Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 22 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak
Wednesday appealed to the people of Israel to adopt a stance that
helps promote the Mideast peace process.
</P>
<P>
"I call on the people of Israel, who share with us the
responsibility to build peace, to adopt the stance that
corresponds to the current danger, the inevitable repercussions of
the collapse or stagnation of peace," Mubarak said in the
nationwide televised speech made at the closing session of the
seventh congress of the ruling National Democratic Party Congress.
</P>
<P>
He noted that rigid policies and unjust practices could not
build "bridges of amity and co-existence" among nations.
</P>
<P>
"They only widen the gap among nations and shatter any hope for
a better future," he added in the keynote speech to mark the 46th
anniversary of the 1952 revolution ending Egypt's monarchy.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak also reviewed Egypt's efforts to establish a just and
comprehensive peace in the region, the required U.S. role in
unblocking the long-standing peace deadlock as well as the peace
efforts exerted by Europe.
</P>
<P>
The Egyptian leader called on peace-loving forces to persist in
their efforts to further peace and contribute to the elimination
of obstacles on its road, because "every incident in this
sensitive region must leave strong echoes and wide repercussions
behind in the various parts of the world."
</P>
<P>
The Mideast peace process has come to a standstill on various
tracks in the past two years since the hard-line Likud government
took power in Israel in mid-1996.
</P>
<P>
For the past 16 months, the Israeli-Palestinian talks have been
stalled due to Israel's actions to expand settlements and its
repeated delay in carrying out the long overdue further troop
redeployment in the West Bank. 
</P>
</TEXT>
