<HEADLINE> Philippine Central Bank to Have More Powers to Fight </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 22 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government will ask
Congress to arm the country's central bank with more muscles to
deal with upheavals affecting the banking sector, the official
Philippine News Agency reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The amendment of the General Banking Act is one of the proposed
priority legislative measures that President Joseph Estrada is
submitting to Congress when it opens on July 27, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Estrada wants to strengthen the supervisory and regulatory
powers of the central bank so that it can invigorate the banking
sector and help power the economy out of the currency storm that
sent business firms into doldrums.
</P>
<P>
The Estrada administration is confident that with these new
powers, the central bank would be better equipped to parry
external economic storms such as the region-wide currency upheaval
that led to the sharp devaluation of the Philippine peso.
</P>
<P>
A stronger central bank is among the financial and monetary
reforms set to be initiated by the new government to help deflate
the prevailing high interest rates in order to spur new
investments from both domestic and international sources. 
</P>
</TEXT>
