<HEADLINE> IMF Urges Seoul Not to Intervene in Foreign Exchange </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, July 22 (Xinhua) -- South Korea should not intervene in
its foreign exchange market as the South Korean won might start
losing strength against the U.S. dollar the second half of the
year, an IMF official warned Wednesday
</P>
<P>
John Richard Dodsworth, director of the IMF's Seoul office,
told a seminar sponsored by the Federation of Korean Industries
that South Korea will see its current account surplus sharply
diminish during the second half this year due to recessions in
Japan and Southeast Asian countries.
</P>
<P>
The reduced exports pressed down by the weakening Japanese yen
and enlarged raw material imports would cut down the country's
current account surplus, Dodsworth said.
</P>
<P>
Given the uncertainties of the other regional currencies, it is
especially important for South Korea to keep an exchange rate
policy with a non-interventionist tone, letting interest rates
move according to foreign exchange trends, he said.
</P>
<P>
Referring to Seoul's efforts to lower interest rates, the IMF
official said exchange rate movements did not affect interest
rates and the recent downturn in interest rates did not lead to
inflation.
</P>
<P>
"While lower interest rates are beneficial, many companies are
concerned with the availability rather than the cost of credit,"
Dodsworth said.
</P>
<P>
He predicted that it will take three to five years for South
Korea to fully ride out the current crisis. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
