<DOCNO> XIE19980722.0084 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Issues Provisions on Abolishing Illegal Financial Bodies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 22 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese State Council, or the
central government, today issued The Provisions on Cancellation of
Illegal Financial Institutions and Activities with an aim to
safeguard the country's financial order and the public interest.
</P>
<P>
The provisions, comprising five chapters and 30 articles, go
into effect today.
</P>
<P>
The provisions define illegal financial bodies as those which
have been set up without official permission from the People's
Bank of China, China's central bank, and are engaged in banking
practices including deposits, loans, clearings, bill-cashing,
inter-bank loans, trust and investment, financial leasing,
financial guarantee and foreign exchange trading.
</P>
<P>
The provisions specify as illegal four types of activities
carried out without official permission from the central
bank: illegal receiving of deposits from the public; illegal
raising of funds from the public under various names; illegal
issuing of loans, making of bank clearings, cashing of bills,
issuing of inter-bank loans, conducting of financial leasing, and
guaranteeing of financing; and trading of foreign exchange.
</P>
<P>
According to the law, cancellation of illegal banking
institutions and activities is to be carried out by the People's
Bank of China, while local governments in places where illegal
financial bodies have been set up, or illegal financial activities
have occurred. are responsible for organizing, coordinating and
supervising the relevant cancellation work.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, cancellation of illegal securities institutions and
activities is to be carried out by the China Securities Regulatory
Commission, while concrete practical methods are to be worked out
in accordance with the principles of the provisions.
</P>
<P>
Cancellation of illegal commercial insurance institutions and
activities is to be carried out by the State Council's regulatory
departments in charge of the commercial insurance sector, while
concrete practical methods are to be worked out in line with the
principles of the provisions.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980722.0085 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Leads Asian Athletics with 26 of 43 goldsJ </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FUKUOKA, July 22 (Xinhua) -- Chinese team took 14 of the 19
gold medals at stake on the final day of the Asian Athletic
Championships on Wednesday, which gave China 26 of the meet's 43
golds.
</P>
<P>
Host Japan was far behind China at the gold table leaving only
six golds at home. Qatar had three and Kazakstan and Sri Lanka
grabbed two each.
</P>
<P>
Sprinter Yan Jiankui of China became a double gold medalist
Wednesday when she edged teammate Huang Mei 23.00 seconds to
23.21 in the 200 meters, adding that gold to her 100 meters win
Monday.
</P>
<P>
Chinese women missed only one of nine gold medals on
Wednesday, and finished with 17 in all.
</P>
<P>
"I knew I could win both events," Yan said. "And I thought I
could run much faster today. Maybe I was a little tired."
</P>
<P>
India's P.T. Usha, in her first international meet after
several years of self-imposed retirement, was third in 23.46,
taking her second bronze medal of the meet.
</P>
<P>
The 33-year-old Usha hopes to be better fit and run faster in
the Asian Games.
</P>
<P>
Later Wednesday, she anchored India's victorious 4 x 100-meter
relay quartet. That was the only women's event on Wednesday that
China didn't win.
</P>
<P>
Usha also anchored her country's silver medal team in the 4 x
400, which finished .16 behind China.
</P>
<P>
Japan won three of the 10 men's gold medals Wednesday, and
Qatar won one, when Mubarak S. Al-Nubifaraj took the men's
400-meter hurdles.
</P>
<P>
For Japan, Koji Ito edged China's Han Chaoming by 0.07 second
in the 200 meters, winning in 20.70. Toshinari Takaoka beat
India's Gulab Chand by more than a second in the 5,000. And Japan
won the 4x400-meter relay, more than a second ahead of South Korea.
</P>
<P>
Chinese women's triple jump winner Ren Ruiping came 0.55
meters short of her 2-year-old Asian record of 14.66.
</P>
<P>
In the women's discus, 192-centimeter-tall Yu Xin threw 57.47
meters for the gold, beating the 56.81 of Neelam J. Singh of
India and 53.32 of Asian record-holder Xiao Yanling, also of
China. Xiao said she has almost recovered from a leg injury she
suffered in April.
</P>
<P>
In the distance races, China's Liu Shixiang, silver medalist
in the 5,000, spurted ahead of Japan's Chiemi Takahashi with 100
meters left and won in 32 minutes, 28.49 seconds for the women's
10,000 gold. Takahashi was second in 32:32.99.
</P>
<P>
A sumo fan from Mongolia, Dashdendev Mahashiri, will take
home his nation's only medal, a silver he won with 57.00 meters
in the men's discus.
</P>
<P>
China's Li Sahojie took the gold with 60.28, while Ajit
Badhuria won the bronze at 55.46.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
