<HEADLINE> Beijing Progresses in Foreign Trade, Economic Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 22 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese capital made
notable progress in foreign trade and economic cooperation in the
first half of this year, according to officials at the Beijing
Municipal Foreign Trade and Economic Cooperation Commission.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Xuequn, an official with the commission, told the press
today that Beijing approved 12 investment plans to be carried out
by local enterprises in Russia, Mongolia, Indonesia, Romania, and
Hungary. The Chinese enterprises will invest a total of 2.27
million U.S. dollars in these countries.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, transactions for labor export and businesses
contracting overseas engineering projects account for an estimated
210 million U.S. dollars, with 2,860 Beijing labors working in
Singapore, Malaysia and Africa.
</P>
<P>
The commission also approved 423 applications for overseas
companies to set up branch offices in Beijing. The number of
branches and offices of overseas commercial entities now doing
business in Beijing had reached 6,826 by the end of June.
</P>
<P>
About 128 technology-export transactions were accomplished in
the first half, valued at 103 million U.S. dollars. The city also
imported 89 new technologies at a cost of 98.3 million U.S.
dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
