<HEADLINE> Manila to Give Top Priority to Quality Education </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 22 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Joseph Estrada
has placed education in his priority agenda during his first 100
days in office in order to equip the Filipino poor with skills and
knowledge.
</P>
<P>
Several measures to give the poor better access to quality
education and strengthen the country's educational system have
been included in the president's priority agenda to be presented
to the new Congress on July 27, the Philippine News Agency said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
These measures include a bill giving poor but deserving college
students preferential access to quality tertiary education through
the adoption of a tuition financing scheme that will make use of
the voucher system.
</P>
<P>
Under this system, poor students can obtain vouchers or
certificates that will serve as their ticket to enter the school
of their choice. Their education will be paid for by the
government, which will set up a fund for this purpose.
</P>
<P>
Estrada will also ask Congress to earmark funds for his
proposed School Building Act, which will establish a program for
the acquisition of school sites and the construction, maintenance,
rehabilitation and repair of school buildings in public elementary
and secondary schools nationwide. 
</P>
</TEXT>
