<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Committed in Efforts to Eliminate Racial Discrimination, Says Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, July 22 (Xinhua) -- David Lan, Secretary for Home
Affairs of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (SAR), said
here Wednesday that the SAR government perseveres in the
opposition to racial discrimination and is making efforts to
eliminate discriminatory practices and attitudes.
</P>
<P>
Lan made these comments while answering a question raised in
the Legislative Council meeting here.
</P>
<P>
The question was related to a recent local press report that
the operators of some bars and clubs in Hong Kong had charged
non-white customers at higher rates.
</P>
<P>
After learning about the incident which happened last month,
Lan said, the authorities decided that the best way to address
this issue was to write to the 500 bars and clubs in Hong Kong,
explaining the SAR government's opposition to racial
discrimination and encouraging them to join the authorities in
their efforts to eliminate discriminatory practices and attitudes.
</P>
<P>
Public education and persuasion was the best and most suitable
approach to address this issue, Lan said. The SAR government had,
besides other efforts, recently conducted TV announcements of
public interest, TV variety show, drawing competition/exhibition,
as well as launching a 2.5 million HK dollars (0.32 million U.S.
dollars) funding scheme to sponsor community projects aimed at
promoting equal opportunities and support for the needs of
minority groups.
</P>
<P>
Lan said that the authorities believed that the various
educational initiatives taken were expected to gradually and
progressively foster a culture of racial equality within the local
community.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
