<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Anti-Organized Crime Body Created in Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 22 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Joseph Estrada
Wednesday ordered the creation of a presidential anti-organized
crime commission and a presidential anti-organized crime task
force to investigate and prosecute criminal elements in the
country.
</P>
<P>
Under the decree, Estrada appointed himself chairman of the
anti-crime commission. The task force will be headed by Chief
Superintendent Panfilo Lacson.
</P>
<P>
The commission members include Justice Secretary Serafin
Cuevas, National Security Adviser Alexander Aguirre, Armed Forces
Chief of Staff Joselin Nazareno and national police chief Roberto
Lastimoso.
</P>
<P>
The commission also includes four civic leaders from
non-governmental anti-crime organizations.
</P>
<P>
The task force will be composed of 800 to 1,000 men from the
police, the military and the National Bureau of Investigation
(NBI).
</P>
<P>
Among the offenses over which the task force and the commission
are empowered to gain jurisdiction are gun running, illegal
logging, robbery-hold-up, kidnapping for ransom, smuggling,
piracy, drug trafficking and other heinous crimes.
</P>
<P>
Estrada expressed the hope that organized crime groups will be
eliminated within the period covered by the Estrada administration
and the two anti-crime bodies will not be permanent government
agencies.
</P>
<P>
Estrada has promised to restore peace and order in the country
where organized crimes such as kidnappings and robberies have been
rampant for years.
</P>
<P>
The new president vowed earlier to eliminate major crime
syndicates within his first six months in office. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
