<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Threat of Cardiovascular Illness May Lessen Next Century </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 22 (Xinhua) -- The latest breakthrough in the
study of hypertension has made it possible for the mankind to
minimize the risk of cardiovascular illness sometime in the next
century.
</P>
<P>
The Symposium of International Study on Hypertension Optimal
Treatment (HOT), which opened here today, disclosed that six years
of research, in which nearly 19,000 patients in 26 countries
received Plendil (felodipine)-based antihypertensive treatment,
has helped medical scientists to determine the optimal blood
pressure for patients with hypertension.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that among more than 690 million patients with
hypertension worldwide, some 2.9 million die of the illness
annually.
</P>
<P>
The HOT, the world's largest project for the study of
hypertension, was endorsed by the European Society of Hypertension
to find the optimal blood pressure for hypertension patients.
</P>
<P>
The study shows that patients who had their systolic pressure
reduced to 138 mm Hg and their diastolic pressure reduced to 83 mm
Hg experienced a 30 percent reduction in the risk of death from
cardiovascular illness.
</P>
<P>
Prof. Liu Lisheng, chairwoman of the Chinese Association of
Hypertension, said that international health organizations will
regard the achievement of the HOT study as the worldwide criterion
in the future treatment of hypertension patients.
</P>
<P>
"And the achievement has been a blessing for Chinese patients,
as this treatment is particularly effective for Asians," she
said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
