<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai Sees Stable Economic Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, July 22 (Xinhua) -- The gross domestic product (GDP)
of Shanghai, China's largest trade and financial city, reached
173.6 billion yuan in the first half of this year, up 9.4 percent
over the same period of last year.
</P>
<P>
According to official statistics released today, the product
value of the city's foreign-funded enterprises increased by 17.1
percent in the first half, despite the negative effects of the
financial crisis in Southeast Asia.
</P>
<P>
The export volume of local foreign trade companies witnessed a
9.5 percent growth to reach eight billion U.S. dollars due to
fast-expanding business in European and American markets and the
enhanced competitiveness of their products.
</P>
<P>
However, the growth rate of the city's exports in the first
half dropped by 3.2 percent compared with the same period last
year.
</P>
<P>
The city's combined export volume to Europe increased by 35
percent in the first five months of this year, with shipments to
the United States up 28.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai's industrial product value also grew by 9.1 percent to
281.6 billion yuan over the past few months as a result of
expanding home demand and greater investment.
</P>
<P>
The consumer price index for Shanghai residents increased by
only 2.8 percent over the past few months, with retail commodity
prices lower by 3.9 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980722.0100 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Go-Ahead Given for EU-MERCOSUR Negotiations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, July 22 (Xinhua) -- The European Commission gave the
go-ahead on Wednesday for negotiations leading up to the formation
of an inter-regional association between the European Union (EU)
and Mercosur plus Chile.
</P>
<P>
The commission, the executive body of the 15-nation European
Union, gave its approval by adopting two recommendations from EU
agriculture ministers who met on Monday.
</P>
<P>
European Commission Vice-President Manuel Marin said the
commission made a positive decision after intense discussions, and
the go-ahead was given by "a very broad majority" of the 22-member
commission.
</P>
<P>
Disagreement arose mainly from the agricultural sector within
the union that fears cheap imports of Latin American agricultural
products, especially cereals, sugar and beef, would flood the EU
markets after the formation of the inter-regional association.
</P>
<P>
Marin stressed that the formation of the inter-regional
association was not a new concept in that the initiative was taken
when the EU signed an agreement with the South American free-trade
zone on December 15, 1995 and with Chile on June 21 the following
year.
</P>
<P>
Mercosur, consisting of Argentina, Brazil, Paraguay and
Uruguay, is ranked the fourth largest single market in the world
after the EU, the United States and Japan.
</P>
<P>
Marin said the EU should not lose its advantageous negotiating
position after the U.S. Congress voted against President Bill
Clinton's fast-track initiative.
</P>
<P>
But he said the actual negotiation for the formation of the
EU-Mercosur association could not be started until after next year
because of necessary paperwork.
</P>
<P>
Marin said that now that the issue of the go-ahead was fixed,
the issues of when and how would become the focus of attention in
the commission and the European Council of Ministers.
</P>
<P>
Trade between the EU and Mercosur increased 76 percent between
1990 and 1996, totaling 33.35 billion ECU (36.67 billion
U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
In 1996, EU enjoyed a trade surplus with Mercosur of 3.6
billion ECU (3.96 billion dollars). 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980722.0101 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-22 14:27 </DATE_TIME>
