<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Microsoft Launches Software for Chinese Small Businesses </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, July 22 (Xinhua) -- Even for a small Chinese business
equipped with only two computers and no computer engineers,
management can be much easier and more efficient by running the
latest Microsoft software on its computer system.
</P>
<P>
This is made possible by Microsoft, the world's leading software
producer, which launched here today a new Chinese
BackOffice version that is specially designed for small and
medium-sized enterprises.
</P>
<P>
According to a Microsoft engineer, the new product offers
businesses with only two to 25 computers a platform linking staff
members, customers and management.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show there are 10 million small and medium-sized
enterprises in China, accounting for 99 percent of all its enterprises.
</P>
<P>
These small enterprises generate 60 percent of the national industrial
output, and employ 70 percent of the nation's workers.
</P>
<P>
An authoritative survey shows that small companies using
computers connected to the Internet or platforms have 20 percent
more per capita annual turnover than the ones that do not.
</P>
<P>
In order to survive in intensifying market competition, small
businesses in China are increasingly aware of the importance of
information technology in management, and have started to take
measures in this regard.
</P>
<P>
Against this backdrop, Microsoft, IBM, Compac, Hewlett-Packard,
and China's largest computer company, the Legend Group, announced
an alliance as the new BackOffice version became available on the
Chinese market.
</P>
<P>
The alliance will work with local software developers and
Internet providers on business computing solutions for small
companies.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980722.0103 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysian Prime Minister to Visit S. Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 22 (Xinhua) -- Malaysian Prime Minister
Mahathir Mohamad will pay a working visit to South Africa Friday
and Saturday, South African Foreign Ministry said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
A statement from the ministry said that the main purpose of
Mahathir's visit was to open the new chancery of Malaysian High
Commission in Pretoria and to hold discussions with acting
president Thabo Mbeki on a wide range of issues.
</P>
<P>
Within the framework of Malaysia's commitment to strengthening
people-to-people relations, the statement said, Mahathir would
launch a week-long Malaysian food festival in Johannesburg.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia is the second largest foreign investor in South
Africa. In 1997, U.S.-based SBC Communications Inc. and Telkom
Malaysia acquired a 30-percent stake in Telkom South Africa,
marking the largest direct investment in South Africa with an
inflow of 1.26 billion U.S. Dollars.
</P>
<P>
Petornas Company had also acquired a 30-percent stake in the
South African oil company, Engen Ltd., said the statement.
</P>
