<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Great Lakes Cleaner Than Before, Commission Says </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, July 22 (Xinhua) -- The Great Lakes are cleaner now
than they have been for 50 years, but people and wildlife still
face threats from toxic substances, the International Joint
Commission says.
</P>
<P>
The commission, a bi-national organization that oversees
trans-boundary issues between the United States and Canada, is to
release an assessment Wednesday in its ninth biennial report on
water quality in the Great Lakes, the largest fresh-water system
in the world.
</P>
<P>
Mercury, dioxin, toxins within the PCB group and agricultural
pesticides are among the chemicals that the commission said are
posing major threats to about 40 million Canadians and Americans
living in the Great Lakes area, and the 25 million who depend on
the Lakes for drinking water.
</P>
<P>
But the Great Lakes environment has improved significantly over
the past 25 years, the report notes. Viable bald eagle communities
have returned to the shorelines, and recently four species of fish
-- sturgeon, lake trout, lake herring and deep-water sculpin --
reappeared in Lake Ontario after long absence.
</P>
<P>
Success is attributed to government imposed bans or production
limits on some of the most toxic substances, such as DDT and
PCBs. However, more subtle and insidious injuries caused by
pesticides and industrial chemicals are continuing to occur, the
report notes.
</P>
<P>
The commission makes 19 recommendations in its report to the
Canadian and U.S. governments.
</P>
<P>
Among these, it calls for a strategy for heavier industry to
reduce its emissions of mercury, a nerve toxin, and nitrogen
oxides, the pollutant that causes smog and contributes to acid
rain. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
