<HEADLINE> Philippines to Privatize National Railways </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 22 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government is bent
on pursuing the privatization of cash-strapped Philippine National
Railways (PNR), the official Philippine News Agency reported
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Transportation and Communications Secretary Vicente Rivera was
quoted as saying that "the only way to make PNR efficient and
profitable is to give it to the private sector."
</P>
<P>
Rivera said this was the same recommendation made by
international consulting firm Price Waterhouse in a study it
conducted on the agency in 1992.
</P>
<P>
"The need to privatize the PNR is largely due to the problems
besetting the company," he said. "For one, the company has been
solely dependent on the financial assistance coming from foreign
governments to rehabilitate its dilapidated facilities."
</P>
<P>
As this developed, a bill has been filed in the House of
Representatives calling for the privatization of the PNR.
</P>
<P>
If the bill is approved, the PNR will enter into separate
operating leases with private firms for commuter service, freight
service and long-distance passenger service.
</P>
<P>
The private company may also employ its own personnel and have
free reign over operation decisions such as fares, schedules and
compensation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
