<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Tightening Down On Smuggling (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 22 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese government is planning
a large scale anti-smuggling campaign for the second half of this
year to demonstrate its determination to assure the healthy
economic growth to protect stability.
</P>
<P>
The drive is, according to President Jiang Zemin, "a major
economic struggle" as well as a "political struggle" that will
have a bearing on the reforms, opening-up, and modernization.
</P>
<P>
Jiang told a conference on smuggling earlier this month that,
to win the campaign, China will deal with major cases in an
efficient way and it plans to reform its system and set up a
national police force especially for that purpose.
</P>
<P>
The reforms include asking departments to turn all fines and
confiscated goods from smuggling cases over to the state
treasury, and much of the profit will be used to fight smuggling.
</P>
<P>
Although China has achieveed a great deal in its endeavor
against smuggling in the past few years, there is still a lot of
smuggling of oil products, automobiles, cigarettes and other items
along coastal areas and borders.
</P>
<P>
The General Administration of Customs reports that in the first
five months of this year, they dealt with 2,322 smuggling cases,
involving 2.78 billion yuan (334.94 million US dollars) worth of
goods, a 10 percent increase from the same period last year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980722.0111 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kim Dae-jung to Invite Predecessors for Dinner </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, July 22 (Xinhua) -- South Korean President Kim Dae-jung
will invite his four predecessors to dinner about the end of July,
a presidential spokesman said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The invitation to Kim Young-sam, Roh Tae-woo, Chun Doo Hwan and
Choi Kyu-hah, all Kim's former rivals or oppressors, is an effort
to seek national harmony amid a downturn in the national economy.
</P>
<P>
"The president is inviting the former presidents to express his
gratitude for their attendance at his inauguration, and to hear
their views on state affairs," spokesman Park Jie-won said.
</P>
<P>
It will be the first time for the president to meet his
predecessors since Kim's February 25 presidential inauguration
this year.
</P>
<P>
The four former presidents have accepted the invitations.
</P>
<P>
A high-ranking official said the move was Kim's effort to
achieve national harmony and unity at a time of economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
South Korea, once an economic powerhouse in the world, has
plunged into economic standstill since late last year.
</P>
<P>
The dinner will, perhaps, pave the way for Kim to ask the
ex-presidents to play some role in the future, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
President Kim might ask his predecessors to act as his advisors
or envoys to end regional rivalry or reduce rampant regionalism,
they said.
</P>
<P>
Kim Young-sam, Roh Tae-woo and Chun Doo Hwan are all from the
south-eastern Kyongsang province while President Kim came from the
south-western Cholla province. 
</P>
</TEXT>
