<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Tightening down on Smuggling (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Since China started its reforms and opening up in the late
1970s, its economy has maintained an annual growth rate of 10
percent. Even this year, though it was affected by the Asian
financial crisis and serious flooding, it still registered a 7
percent growth in the first half of this year.
</P>
<P>
Economists have praised the economic achievements, but they
still pinpointed that smuggling has done a great deal of damage to
industry and has caused a substantial loss of tax revenues.
</P>
<P>
In the past six months, the price of domestic petroleum dropped
by more than 300 yuan (36 US dollars) per metric ton, causing
industry profits to edge down. Some analysts describe smuggling as
one of the chief factors.
</P>
<P>
The automobile industry has suffered a similar fate. Domestic
auto makers have found themselves caught in a squeeze between a
slump in the market and rampant smuggling and find it difficult to
breathe.
</P>
<P>
A Customs official said that China's annual losses from
smuggling may be as large as approximately 100 billion yuan (12
billion US dollars) when one considers the large number of
smugglers who escape the net of justice.
</P>
<P>
No country is lucky enough to completely get away from
smuggling, he acknowledged, but he referred to the rampant
situation in China "shocking". The resolve of the Chinese
government is admirable, he said and he believed smuggling can in
fact be checked with the intense campaign.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980722.0115 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pakistan, U.S. for Close Consultation on Afghanistan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, July 22 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan and the United States
Wednesday decided to "consult each other closely on the evolving
situation in Afghanistan."
</P>
<P>
The decision was taken during an exclusive discussion on
Afghanistan between U.S. Assistant Secretary of State Karl
Inderfurth and Pakistani Foreign Secretary Shamshad Ahmad
Wednesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
The two sides exchanged views on the ground situation
prevailing in Afghanistan emphasized the need for a negotiated
political settlement and decided to consult each other closely on
the evolving situation in Afghanistan, said a press release issued
by the Foreign Office.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, Shamshad gave a detailed briefing on the
initiatives taken by Pakistan, under the directions of Prime
Minister Nawaz Sharif, for promoting the Afghan peace process.
</P>
<P>
He urged the U.S. to seriously engage itself in promoting an
early resolution of the conflict in Afghanistan, adding that
Pakistan fully supported the efforts of the U.N. and the
Organization of Islamic Conference towards this end.
</P>
<P>
Inderfurth lauded Pakistan's initiative and sincerity in
facilitating an Afghan settlement.
</P>
<P>
He noted that this had been deeply appreciated at the
U.N-sponsored meeting on July 16 of the six countries bordering
Afghanistan plus the U.S. and Russia.
</P>
<P>
Inderfurth is accompanying Deputy Secretary of State Strobe
Talbott on a two-day visit to Pakistan. 
