<HEADLINE> Inquiry on HK New Airport to Be Conducted </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, July 22 (Xinhua) -- Justice Woo Kwok-hing, chairman
of the Commission of Inquiry on New Airport, pledged here
Wednesday that the commission would be absolutely independent and
impartial in conducting an inquiry into the operation of the new
Hong Kong International Airport.
</P>
<P>
The commission, comprising Woo and Edgar Cheng, former chairman
of the Hong Kong Stock Exchange, was appointed by the Chief
Executive-in-Council on Tuesday to probe into various matters
relating to the operation of the new airport at Chek Lap Kok,
which was opened on July 6 this year.
</P>
<P>
These matters include the decision to open the airport on July
6, the planning and preparation for its opening and problems which
arose thereafter.
</P>
<P>
"We will ensure that the entire process will be highly
transparent," Woo said at a press conference on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Woo said that the commission plans to exercise the powers
appropriately under the Commissions of Inquiry Ordinance (Chapter
86) to summon witnesses to give evidence and produce documents.
</P>
<P>
Local and overseas experts may be invited for assistance if
necessary, he said. A thorough report will be submitted to the
Chief Executive after the inquiry is completed and depending on
circumstances, an interim report may be submitted within six
months, he added.
</P>
<P>
Tung Chee Hwa, chief executive of the Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region, said Tuesday that the appointment of an
independent statutory commission demonstrates clearly the
government's determination to find out what went wrong, to
establish where the responsibilities lie, and to help prevent
similar incidents from happening again.
</P>
<P>
The chief executive inspected the new airport on Monday. After
his two-hour tour, Tung said that tremendous progress had been
made on the passenger services, yet much had to be done to improve
the cargo operations.
</P>
<P>
The cargo operations were affected due to the breakdown of the
Super Terminal One, which handles 80 percent of the total air
cargo in Hong Kong. The franchisee Hong Kong Air Cargo Terminal
Ltd. has planned to gear up the throughput at the terminal step by
step till it runs in full strength in mid-August. 
</P>
</TEXT>
