<DOCNO> XIE19980722.0120 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Interview: SAARC Progress Great But Slow, </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, July 22 (Xinhua) -- The achievements made by the
South Asian Association for Regional Cooperation (SAARC) are
"great," but "unfortunately the progress is slow," Bangladeshi
Ambassador to Nepal Mohiuddin Ahmed said here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"What we would like SAARC to achieve has not been achieved," he
told Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
He said that cooperation among the member countries is new, and
unlike Association of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN) whose member
countries do not have a big difference in size, SAARC has a small
member country like Bhutan and a giant like India.
</P>
<P>
"So economic cooperation between these kinds of countries is
not very easy. It takes time," he said.
</P>
<P>
He added that as a whole, SAARC has different economies which
are not complementary. For India, Pakistan, Bhutan, the Maldives
and Bangladesh, the priority differs.
</P>
<P>
"Bangladesh has a huge population, our priority is agriculture,
education and health," he said.
</P>
<P>
This makes it very difficult to bring them together and work
out very ambitious plans, he said.
</P>
<P>
But some success has been made in certain fields like
agriculture, telecommunications and health, he said.
</P>
<P>
He said that the idea of SAARC came from Bangladesh, and from
the very beginning, his country has been very serious and fully
committed to SAARC.
</P>
<P>
"We sincerely believe that cooperation among the seven
countries of the region is beneficial to all the member countries.
The progress has been slow, but we are hopeful. It will go faster
now as SAARC has become mature," the ambassador said.
</P>
<P>
"We believe that in this region in South Asia, it is very
important for us to work together. Unless we work together, we
cannot achieve economic development," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
"We're all aware of the great potentials of the whole region.
We're optimistic that the whole potential can be fully tapped," he
added.
</P>
<P>
SAARC was formed in December 1985 to promote regional
cooperation in economic development and other areas among its
seven member countries -- Bangladesh, Bhutan, India, the Maldives,
Nepal, Pakistan and Sri Lanka.
</P>
<P>
It launched the SAARC Preferential Trading Arrangement (SAPTA)
in December 1995 as a first concrete measure for economic and
trade cooperation.
</P>
<P>
And SAARC leaders decided last year to go for South Asian Free
Trade Area (SAFTA) preferably by the year of 2001.
</P>
<P>
Two rounds of trade negotiations have been completed under
SAPTA and the member countries have exchanged more than 2,000
items of products for preferential treatment.
</P>
<P>
Special treatment has been offered to Bangladesh, Bhutan, the
Maldives and Nepal, the four least developed countries in the
region.
</P>
<P>
The 10th SAARC summit, to be held on July 29-31 in Colombo, Sri
Lanka, will study and analyze the report submitted by the Group of
Eminent Persons which was commissioned last year to conduct a
comprehensive review of SAARC and map out future strategy for the
regional grouping.
</P>
<P>
"We hope that the report has identified such areas where
special treatment is given to the least developed countries,"
Ambassador Ahmed said.
</P>
<P>
He said that the common problem facing all the member countries
is poverty, so the priority should be poverty alleviation.
</P>
<P>
Attention should also be given to health, education,
communication and transportation, he said.
</P>
<P>
On sub-regional cooperation among Bangladesh, Bhutan, India and
Nepal, he said, "If you look at the SAARC, the map and the
economies of different countries, it is very logical that there
should be sub-groups."
</P>
<P>
In December 1996, Nepal initiated the Growth Quadrangle
comprising the above four countries with a view to jointly
developing the eastern Himalayan rivers for rapid economic
development.
</P>
<P>
Ambassador Ahmed said that Bangladesh was very enthusiastic
about the idea and immediately gave its support. "This is one way
where development can be made," he added.
</P>
<P>
He observed that sub-regional cooperation may help expedite the
SAARC process and this is the beginning for smaller groups to
appear in the region.
</P>
<P>
At the ninth summit in May 1997, SAARC leaders encouraged the
development of specific projects relevant to the specific
individual needs of three or more member countries.
</P>
<P>
On the upcoming SAARC summit, the ambassador said that the
summit is very important as it will study the report of the Group
of Eminent Persons, which will have repercussions on SAARC itself.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile the summit provides an opportunity for leaders of
India and Pakistan to sit down together and discuss their own
problems bilaterally following their nuclear explosions in May, he
said.
</P>
<P>
He said that there is no major problem affecting regional
cooperation in South Asia. "Kashmir problem is there since 1947,
but that never affected the cooperation within SAARC," he
stressed.
</P>
<P>
However, "we sincerely hope that it is resolved bilaterally
between India and Pakistan," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
