<HEADLINE> South Korea to Assist Small Businesses </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, July 22 (Xinhua) -- The South Korean government
Wednesday announced a nine-point package for helping small
businesses overcome their difficulties.
</P>
<P>
The package includes debt rescheduling and provision of tax and
financial privileges.
</P>
<P>
The announcement was made after an agreement was reached
between the government and the Korea Federation of Small
Businesses, at a meeting chaired by President Kim Dae-jung,
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, small businesses, which are suffering
under the current financial crisis, will get a six-month extension
of loans, which can be used to buy facilities and equipment.
</P>
<P>
The loans will amount to 42.5 billion won (33 million
U.S. dollars) in total.
</P>
<P>
Another 300-billion won (232.7 million dollars) from post
office savings accounts will be injected into small firms in the
information and telecommunications industries. 
</P>
