<HEADLINE> ASEAN Extends Sympathy to Papua New Guinea Over </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 22 (Xinhua) -- Philippine Foreign Secretary
Domingo Siazon, on behalf of ASEAN, Wednesday conveyed his
sympathy to the Papua New Guinea government for the losses
sustained from the tidal wave that hit the country last Friday.
</P>
<P>
Siazon, who is currently chairman of the Association of
Southeast Asian Nations' (ASEAN) Standing Committee (ASC),
expressed his sympathy in a statement.
</P>
<P>
The ASC just concluded its two-day meeting here to prepare for
the ASEAN Ministerial Meeting and associated meetings.
</P>
<P>
"On behalf of ASEAN," the statement said, "I would like to
express heartfelt sympathy to the government and people of Papua
New Guinea for the tragic loss of human lives and enormous damage
to property caused by three tsunamis."
</P>
<P>
"The association extends its deepest condolences to the
bereaved families of the victims of this terrible calamity, and
hopes that immediate medical and relief assistance could be
extended to those who have been injured as well as to the
thousands left homeless by the incident," the statement added.
</P>
<P>
Earlier reports said that over 1,500 Papuans perished in the
tidal waves which also wrecked hundreds of houses.
</P>
<P>
Papua New Guinea enjoys an observer status in the ASEAN
Regional Forum (ARF) which is due to meet in Manila on July 27. It
will also participate in the ASEAN Post Ministerial Conference
(PMC) on July 28-29.
</P>
<P>
It was not immediately ascertained if Papua New Guinea Foreign
Minister Roy Yaki will be able to make it to Manila for the ARF
and PMC consultations.
</P>
<P>
Papua New Guinea is due to accede to the ASEAN Treaty to Amity
and Cooperation (TAC) during the two-day ASEAN Ministerial Meeting
that opens Thursday. 
</P>
