<HEADLINE> Bangladesh to Build Five More Fertilizer Factories </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, July 22 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh will set up five more
fertilizer factories, including some in the northern region, to
meet the growing demand of fertilizer in the country, Commerce and
Industries Minister Tofail Ahmad said here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"After satisfying domestic demands, excess fertilizer would be
exported to different countries," Ahmad told a two-day annual
conference of the Bangladesh Chemical Industries Corporation
(BCIC).
</P>
<P>
The minister did not mention when the construction of the new
fertilizer factories would start and where they would be located.
</P>
<P>
The BCIC consists of seven large fertilizer factories and has
been a losing organization for the last 22 years. It managed to
reduce the loss by 1.43 billion taka (30.43 million U.S. dollars)
during the 1997-98 fiscal year as a result of efficient management
effected by the government, according to Ahmad.
</P>
<P>
He urged all concerned to make industries under the BCIC
profitable organizations to meet the challenges of the open market
economy.
</P>
<P>
Industries Secretary K.M. Ejazul Huq also called on officials
and employees of the BCIC-run industries to turn themselves into
skilled manpower by undergoing training.
</P>
<P>
The BCIC produced 182.4 million tons of fertilizer during
fiscal 1997-98, about 12.3 percent higher than that in the
previous year, according to BCIC Chairman M. Anwarul Huq.
</P>
<P>
"If there was no gas shortage, around 50 million tons of
additional fertilizer would have been produced," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
