<HEADLINE> Border Crossings Hit Record High </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 22 (Xinhua) -- The number of departures and
arrivals through Chinese Customs offices reached a record high of
68.06 million in the first half of this year, 9.77 percent more
than the figures for the corresponding period last year.
</P>
<P>
Sources at the Exit-Entry Administration Bureau under the
Ministry of Public Security say that in recent years a series of
measures have improved the services of Customs departments around
the country.
</P>
<P>
In the first six months, Chinese citizens made 4,135,400 exits,
which are equivalent to the figure of last year's first half, with
their main destinations including Hong Kong, Macao, Thailand,
Japan, Russia, the United States, Singapore, the Republic of Korea
(ROK), the Democratic People's Republic of Korea, and Australia.
</P>
<P>
In the same period, foreign nationals from 251 countries and
regions made 3,379,700 entries into China, 2.44 percent less than
the figure of last year's first half.
</P>
<P>
Due to the current financial turmoil in Asia, arrivals by
Malaysians and ROK visitors fell by 20 percent and 22 percent,
respectively, compared with the figures of last year.
</P>
<P>
Local Customs offices also caught 23,763 persons who had
violated China's exit-entry laws and regulations, including 3,172
who crossed the border clandestinely, up 29 percent and 2.5
percent, respectively, over the same period of last year.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, local Customs officers captured 202 people involved
in economic crimes and recovered 230 million yuan for the
state. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
