<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran to Answer US Overture: FM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, July 22 (Xinhua) -- Iranian Foreign Minister Kamal
Kharrazi reaffirmed here Wednesday that Iran would answer the
U.S. overture for a rapprochement between the two rivals.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference, Kharrazi said that the
promise made by Iranian President Mohammad Khatami on July 1
to answer the U.S. overture was still valid and "we will
give the answer if necessary."
</P>
<P>
Following repeated goodwill signals from Washington, President
Khatami confirmed "a change in tone" in the statements of the
U.S. officials, but stressing that Iran would judge the
U.S. sincerity only through actions.
</P>
<P>
Kharrazi also said that the change in tone would be valuable
only when the U.S. changed its policies and behavior toward
Iran.
</P>
<P>
He criticized U.S. politicians for lagging behind the new
developments in the international relations at the threshold of
the new century by keeping the mentality of the cold war era.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. extraterritorial legislation and its disregard for
other civilizations and cultures were the clear evidence to show
that Washington had not changed that mentality, he noted.
</P>
<P>
The minister said that the world has entered a new era and even
the European states resisted the U.S. policies, a proof that
today's world is not a unipolar one and all the nations should
have a say in global policy-making.
</P>
<P>
Welcoming the policy of dialog by the European states,
Kharrazi said that as long as they honor the principle of mutual
respect, Iran would have good relations with them.
</P>
<P>
On the relations with Britain which were strained by the
Rushdie dispute, he said Iran would welcome any move by the
British government to improve bilateral ties.
</P>
<P>
But he signaled no compromise on the issue of Salman Rushdie,
the British writer condemned to death by late Iranian supreme
leader Ayatollah Khomeini, saying Rushdie insulted 1 billion
Muslims through his book "The Satanic Verses."
</P>
<P>
Kharrazi said if Britain intended to enter the new era, it
should abandon the old mentality of civilization confrontation and
refrain from insulting others' sanctity.
</P>
<P>
During a recent visit to Tehran, a European Union Troika
delegation asked Iran to revoke the award for killing Rushdie
according to the fatwa issued by Khomeini, but Iran rejected the
demand. 
</P>
</TEXT>
