<HEADLINE> Strikers in Philippine Airlines Ready for New Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 22 (Xinhua) -- Members of the Philippine Airlines
(PAL) Employees Association (PALEA), who went on strike early
Wednesday morning in a bid to paralyze the firm's operations, said
that they are ready for new talks with the management.
</P>
<P>
"This (the strike) is the ultimate decision, after efforts to
reach a compromise with management proved futile," said Alex
Barrientos, PALEA president.
</P>
<P>
But a certain Capili, a PALEA member who joined the dawn picket
at the domestic airport, said that sincere negotiations by the PAL
management can lead them back to work.
</P>
<P>
This means that the management should re-hire all the 5,000
dismissed PAL employees who were fired under a massive downsizing
program.
</P>
<P>
The PAL management was forced to massively downsize its
operations last month after its 620 pilots staged an illegal
strike on June 5, further aggravating the financial position of
the debt-ridden airline.
</P>
<P>
The PALEA, which represents the PAL's thousands of ground crew,
mounted the strike in protest of the retrenchment of the 5,000
employees, more than one-third of the company's 13,500-strong
workforce.
</P>
<P>
About 200 PALEA members carrying placards and streamers
picketed the Manila domestic airport trying to stop pilots and
other workers from launching early morning flights.
</P>
<P>
The indefinite strike has delayed most international and
domestic flights, leaving thousands of passengers stranded in
Manila and other cities in the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
