<DOCNO> XIE19980722.0134 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 3,625 People Kidnapped in Jammu, Kashmir in 10 Years </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, July 22 (Xinhua) -- A total of 3,625 people
including 21 foreigners and 128 politicians were kidnapped by the
militants in Jammu and Kashmir in the past 10 years, Indian Home
Ministry said in a report released Wednesday in Jammu.
</P>
<P>
Among the victims from abroad, the Press Trust of India (PTI)
reported from Jammu, 7 were Israeli, 4 British, 2 Swedish, 2
American, 2 Dutch, 1 Japanese, 1 French, 1 German and 1 Norwegian.
</P>
<P>
The fate of 4 foreigners, abducted in July 1995, remained
unknown despite government efforts to trace them, said the report
which recorded incidents since 1989 to the end of March 1998.
</P>
<P>
The victims included 145 women and 307 government officers, the
report said.
</P>
<P>
In about 2,183 incidents in the valley during the period, 1,076
were killed by militants and the year 1996 saw the death of 345
people, the highest number of victims in a single year.
</P>
<P>
However, the report said, militants also released 862 people
after keeping them as hostages for varying periods.
</P>
<P>
In most of the cases, it added, those abducted were released by
their captors after extortion, torture, rape and exchange of
militants.
</P>
<P>
The highest number of 759 cases of kidnapping took place in
1996, followed by 657 in 1995 and 521 in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Militants destroyed 13,563 structures in 4,763 incidents by
setting them ablaze during the period, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Home Minister L. K. Advani said Wednesday in a
written reply in the Upper House of Parliament that 310 militants
were killed in security forces operations in Jammu and Kashmir
from January to June this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
