<HEADLINE> Australian Dollar Backtracks as Japanese Yen Stumbles </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, July 22 (Xinhua) -- The Australian dollar was forced
to backtrack Wednesday by further weakness in the Japanese yen
against the U.S. dollar.
</P>
<P>
At the close here, the local currency was trading at 62.37 U.S.
cents, from 62.93 Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
A dealer from the ANZ Bank said the unit had looked heavy since
the morning, when it opened at 62.68 U.S. cents.
</P>
<P>
"Once the U.S. dollar/Japanese yen exchange rate started
looking bid and broke through on the topside it gave the market a
bit of momentum to go for stops at 62.40 U.S. cents," she said.
</P>
<P>
Citibank chief economist Stephen Koukoulas said the wait for
meaningful Japanese policy reform would guide the Australian
dollar in the short-term.
</P>
<P>
"We would not be surprised to see spikes lower in the
Australian dollar, but a broad 61.00 U.S. cents to 63.00 range is
expected to hold in the near term, with a gentle appreciation to
65.00 U.S. cents by year end as cyclical factors start to turn
positive," he said.
</P>
<P>
Such policy reform could be a step closer by the weekend with
the first ballot by lawmakers for the position of Japanese prime
minister being held Friday.
</P>
<P>
News on the future of the remaining two-thirds of Telstra
caused the Australian market to end weaker.
</P>
<P>
The federal government announced it would not sell the entirety
of its remaining stake in Telstra and would cap the sell-off at 49
percent.
</P>
<P>
The federal government sold 33 percent of Telstra in a public
float in November last year and will look to sell the next 16
percent in one hit, if it is returned to government after the next
national election.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the local currency was buying 87.81 Japanese yen
from 87.57 late Tuesday and 1.1138 German marks from 1.1216.
</P>
</TEXT>
