<HEADLINE> Scientists Find No Evidence of Antimatter During Space Flight (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 22 (Xinhua) -- Scientists so far found no
evidence of antimatter during experiments carried on the American
shuttle "Discovery" on a ten-day space mission.
</P>
<P>
Experiments to detect antimatter and missing matter in space
were conducted by the Alpha Magnetic Spectrometer, a 3.5-ton
particle detector was carried into space by the Discovery on June
2. The shuttle wound up a successful mission and returned to the
Kennedy Space Center on the evening of June 12.
</P>
<P>
"It is impossible to draw any conclusions on the existence of
antimatter in space during such a short mission," according to
Chinese scientist Prof. Chen Hesheng.
</P>
<P>
"However, the detector did find some antiprotons which are
often produced during collisions of cosmic rays, but not
antimatter, said Prof. Chen, a researcher with the Institute of
High-Energy Physics under the Chinese Academy of Sciences (CAS),
who directed China's participation in the experiments.
</P>
<P>
The detector also found protons and various atomic nuclei
during the trip, Chen added.
</P>
<P>
The research was an international cooperation effort led by
Chinese-American scientist and Nobel Prize Winner Dr. Samuel Ting
and involved more than 30 Chinese scientists from the Institute of
High-Energy Physics, the Institute of Electrical Engineering and
the Chinese Academy of Launch Vehicle Technology.
</P>
<P>
China produced the permanent magnet which was the key component
for the detector and produced some of the unit's mechanical
structure, according to Chen. Related components functioned as
expected during the flight.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980722.0141 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-22 </DATE_TIME>
