<HEADLINE> IMF Director Arrives in Indonesia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, July 22 (Xinhua) -- The International Monetary Fund's
(IMF) director for the Asia Pacific Hubert Neiss arrived here
Wednesday afternoon to review use of the IMF funds already
disbursed to Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
Talking to reporters upon arrival at the Soekarno-Hatta
international airport, Neiss said during his two-week visit he
will discuss three issues concerning the country's economic
rehabilitation.
</P>
<P>
The three issues are availability of the basic requirements by
the common people, examination program of banking restructuring
and solving private debts problem, he added.
</P>
<P>
The IMF agreed to resume loan payments to Indonesia last week,
after suspending payments following the May riots which led to the
resignation of former president Soeharto.
</P>
<P>
At a recent meeting in Washington, the IMF board of directors
approved the release of one billion U.S. dollars as part of its 43
billion U.S. dollars rescue package for Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
Indonesian Coordinating Minister of Economy, Finance and
Industry Ginandjar Kartasasmita told reporters Monday that the
loan would be used to strengthen the country's balance of payment
and cover state budget deficits. 
</P>
