<HEADLINE> Scientists Find No Evidence of Antimatter During Space Flight (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Various components in the detector were overheated during the
flight, and the related problems promptly resolved, said Chen,
adding that the mission provided Chinese scientists with greater
insight into the country's future work on space stations.
</P>
<P>
The permanent magnet retrieved more than 220 hours of data and
200 million samples, some 80 percent of which were protons and 20
percent nuclei.
</P>
<P>
"The flight represented the first time human beings successfully
used a large magnetic detector to observe cosmic ray particles in
outer space," Chen noted. "The mission propelled the science of
physics into a brand-new unknown world."
</P>
<P>
The Institute of High-Energy Physics has obtained data
collected during the flight through the Internet, and numerous
Chinese physicists are attempting to download even more extensive
data to carry out related studies.
</P>
<P>
The magnetic detector will be placed aboard the American Alpha
Space Station in the year 2002 to carry out observations over a
3-5 year period, with the project expected to provide scientists
with an even large database.  
</P>
