<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UNEP Calls for Urgent Action on Climate Change </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 22 (Xinhua) -- Following scientific reports that
1998 is shaping up to be the hottest year on record, the U.N.
Environment Program (UNEP) Wednesday urged policy-makers to take
urgent action to limit emissions of carbon dioxide and other
greenhouse gases.
</P>
<P>
"Record warming and severe summer heat waves in the U.S.,
India, China, and elsewhere are a wake-up call," said Klaus
Topfer, UNEP's Executive Director.
</P>
<P>
"We cannot afford to wait several years for the Kyoto Protocol
to enter into force before making significant emissions cuts," he
stressed at the UNEP headquarters in the Kenyan capital.
</P>
<P>
Scientists confirmed in 1995 that the global climate might
have already started responding to past emissions and predicted
that the global temperature will rise by one to 3.5 centigrade
degrees by 2100.
</P>
<P>
The increase will also cause sea levels to rise by 15 to 95 cm
and climatic zones (including ecosystems and agricultural zones)
to shift towards the poles by 150 to 550 kilometers in the
mid-latitude regions, said the Inter-governmental Panel on
Climate Change (IPCC).
</P>
<P>
The IPCC, a network of over 2,000 scientists and experts, is
sponsored by UNEP and the World Meteorological Organization.
</P>
<P>
"There is still uncertainty about how the climate will change
at the regional or national level, and it is still not possible
to prove that individual heat waves or extreme events are caused
by global warming," said Topfer.
</P>
<P>
"But, we have more than enough credible evidence to know that
global climate change poses tremendous risks. We must take out
insurance now against future catastrophic climate change by
urgently adopting energy efficiency and other win-win measures,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
Solar cells which currently produce less than one percent of
global power supplies, as well as other renewable energy
technology sources will be an essential part of the solution, the
UNEP noted in a statement.
</P>
<P>
Regulatory standards, tradable emissions permits, information
and public awareness programs, voluntary programs for business,
better urban transport planning, and the phase-out of
counterproductive subsidies can also play a role, the UNEP added.
</P>
<P>
Developed countries are responsible for the bulk of past and
present emissions and must take the lead in limiting emissions,
the UNEP urged.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. environment authority said that at the same time,
cleaner energy technologies should also be promoted in developing
countries through the Kyoto Protocol's Clean Development
Mechanism (CDM).
</P>
<P>
Under the CDM, developed countries will be able to receive
credit for investments in emissions-limiting projects in
developing countries, said UNEP.
</P>
<P>
"This kind of incentive for making large-scale transfers to
developing countries of energy-efficient and renewable-energy
technologies can go a long way towards achieving both
developmental and environmental objectives," said Topfer.
</P>
<P>
He called on governments to create an economic and regulatory
framework that encourages both energy consumers and producers to
adopt the most energy-efficient technologies available so as to
cut carbon dioxide emissions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980722.0145 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-22 12:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mordechai Asks U.S. Help on Redeployment Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 22 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Defense Minister Yitzhak
Mordechai has asked the United States to help reach an agreement
between Israel and Palestinians on the further redeployment of
Israeli troops in the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
Talking to reporters Wednesday in the Knesset (parliament),
Mordechai urged U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright and
peace envoy Dennis Ross to send senior officials to the region to
bridge the gap between Israel and Palestinians on the issue.
</P>
<P>
Mordechai said U.S. intervention could be the only way to help
reach an agreement in the shortest time, suggesting the ongoing
Israeli-Palestinian direct talks could end in failure.
</P>
<P>
Mordechai met with Palestinian peace negotiator Abu Mazen on
Sunday in Tel Aviv, kicking off the first direct peace talks in
months between the two sides. Their negotiations were stalled in
March last year when Israel decided to build a Jewish settlement
in controversial Har Homa, south of Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Following Sunday's meeting, low-level discussions were also
held between the two sides on the redeployment issue, but so
specific agreement was reached so far.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli side suggested a undercut version of the
U.S. proposal for a 13 percent Israeli pullback - 10 percent will
be handed over while the other 3 percent will be defined as
"natural preserves," in which no construction by either side will
be allowed.
</P>
<P>
Israel also demanded the convening of the smaller 100-member
Central Committee of the Palestinian Liberation Organization,
instead of the 460-member Palestinian National Council, to delete
the anti-Israel clauses in the Palestinian Covenant.
</P>
<P>
Rejecting all these demands, the Palestinian side said the
required changes to the Covenant have already been made in 1996 and
the question remains of which side has jurisdiction over the
so-called "natural reserves" of the 3 percent of the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian side said that no progress was made in this
direct negotiations and warned the talks would break up again
unless the Israeli side endorses U.S. proposal for a 13.1 percent
withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
As the peace talks moved on, Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu
held a series of meetings during the last two days with right wing
coalition party leaders to discuss the pullback issue.
</P>
<P>
The National Religious Party told Netanyahu Tuesday that it
will leave the coalition if he decided to accept the
U.S. proposal.
</P>
<P>
Another coalition partner Tsomet said the same day that any
pullback over 7 percent would lead to the party's quitting the
coalition.
</P>
<P>
The opposition Labor Party said Wednesday that key party
members will further discuss whether to provide assistance to
Netanyahu on this issue on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian side said on Tuesday that it gave another two
days for Israel to make a decision on accepting the U.S. proposal.
</P>
<P>
Holding direct talks with the Palestinians was Netanyahu's
idea. Mordechai's call for U.S. intervention showed it is almost
impossible for the two sides to solve such key issues without
being ready to make compromises. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
