<HEADLINE> China to Boost Automotive Market (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 22 (Xinhua) -- China's automotive output
increased by 0.6 percent and sales grew by 3.37 percent in the
first half of 1998 compared to the previous year's period.
</P>
<P>
The State Bureau of Machinery Industry forecasts slow growth
for both sales and output through the end of this year.
</P>
<P>
An official with the National Automotive Industry Association
(NAIA) held that the flat consumption market and the existing
product mix and circulation system of the sector have hindered
the expansion of the automotive market.
</P>
<P>
The automotive industry not only accounts for 2.4 percent of
the country's total industrial output value, but also has direct
links with many other industries which involve 12 percent of the
total work force in urban areas.
</P>
<P>
Economist Li Yining said expansion of the automotive market
will have immediate impact on spurring the economy to this year's
growth target of eight percent.
</P>
<P>
Recent estimates indicate that the nation's top three
automotive manufacturers earn between 20-30 billion yuan from
installment sales annually. Economists stress that the time is
ripe for banks to provide automobile loans to individual consumers.
</P>
<P>
In June this year, the Aeolus-Citroen Automobile Co. Ltd., a
Sino-French joint venture in central China's Hubei Province,
signed agreements with three major Wuhan banks calling for the
institutions to grant related loans to customers.
</P>
<P>
According to Zeng, a marketing representative of the joint
venture, the company sold more than 10,000 automobiles in
Beijing last year, with less than ten percent of units sold
under the installment plan.
</P>
<P>
Economists predict that bank financing will help to increase
both output and sales.
</P>
<P>
However, Teng Bole, general secretary of NAIA, said that
relevant authorities are considering how to effectively spread
risk between manufactures, participating banks and consumers prior
to taking the major step of pushing banks into field of automotive
sales.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
