<DOCNO> XIE19980722.0149 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australia First in Reserves of 8 Mineral Commodities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, July 22 (Xinhua) -- Australia now has the world's
largest reserves of eight key mineral commodities, according to a
report released Wednesday by the Australian Bureau of Resource
Sciences.
</P>
<P>
The eight minerals are bauxite, lead, mineral sands (ilmenite,
rutile and zircon), nickel, silver, tantalum, uranium and zinc.
</P>
<P>
The report, entitled Australia's Identified Mineral Resources
1998, was released by Australian federal Resources and Energy
Minister Warwick Parer.
</P>
<P>
Australia's measured and indicated bauxite resources of 8.7
billion tons rank number one in the world ahead of Guinea, Brazil,
Jamaica and India, the report said.
</P>
<P>
"Australia is the world's largest refiner of bauxite and fourth
largest producer of primary aluminum," it added.
</P>
<P>
The report said Australia's identified resource stocks of zinc,
lead and silver total 86.3 million tons, 54.6 million tons and
92,000 tons, respectively.
</P>
<P>
The nation's economic demonstrated resources estimates, or
commercially exploitable deposit estimates, for zinc (36.3 million
tons), lead (17.5 million tons) and silver (41,500 tons) represent
19 percent, 27 percent and 15 percent of the world's totals
respectively, the report said.
</P>
<P>
At the end of 1997, Australia had 24 percent, 42 percent and 37
percent of the world's economic demonstrated resources of ilmenite
(143.5 million tons), rutile (17.35 million tons) and zircon
(23.26 million tons), respectively, and produced 35 percent, 58
percent and 49 percent, respectively, of world output of these
minerals.
</P>
<P>
Australia's share of world economic demonstrated resources of
nickel was 15.6 percent in 1997, or 6.72 million tons, followed by
Russia, Cuba, and Canada. Australia produced 1.08 million tons of
nickel in 1997, about 11.5 percent of the world's total output.
</P>
<P>
Australia remains the world's premier holder of tantalum
economic demonstrated resources, accounting for 54 percent of the
world's total.
</P>
<P>
It produced about 302 tons of contained tantalum in 1997,
compared with the world's total output of 407 tons.
</P>
<P>
Australia has the world's largest resources of uranium in the
low cost Reasonably Assured Resources category, accounting for 26
percent of world resources in this category, followed by
Kazakhstan (19 percent), Canada (14 percent), and South Africa (9
percent).
</P>
<P>
Australia, which is also rich in industrial diamond, coal,
copper, iron ore and gold resources, is one of the world's major
producers and exporters of the mineral products, the report said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980722.0150 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jayasinghe Cleared of Drug Charges </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, July 22 (Xinhua) -- World silver medalist Susanthika
Jayasinghe has been cleared of drug charges on a majority decision
by a disciplinary committee appointed by the Sri Lanka's Amateur
Athletics Association (AAA).
</P>
<P>
Jayasinghe, 200m runner-up at last year's world championships
in Athens, was temporarily suspended from international
competition after she failed a random drug test conducted by the
International Amateur Athletics Federation (IAAF) in April.
</P>
<P>
Two members of the committee said in a statement that they has
failed to prove beyond reasonable doubt that the alleged doping
test offense has been committed by Jayasinghe.
</P>
<P>
The third member held her guilty of the charge.
</P>
<P>
Jayasinghe was the first Sri Lankan in 49 years to win a medal
at an international championship.  
</P>
</TEXT>
