<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-22 12:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran, Egypt Need to Expand Cooperation: Iranian FM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, July 22 (Xinhua) -- Iranian Foreign Minister Kamal
Kharrazi said here Wednesday that Iran and Egypt, as two
important countries in the Middle East region, should expand their
cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference, Kharrazi said that Iran and
Egypt have found the ground for mutual understanding, and need to
cooperate further, considering the important developments in the
region and Israel's expansionist policies.
</P>
<P>
He did not mention any possible upgrading of relations. But,
during past months, officials of the two countries have voiced
readiness to improve the bilateral ties.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak said on Sunday that the two
sides are in contact and the bilateral trade and economic
relations are growing.
</P>
<P>
Diplomatic relations between Tehran and Cairo were severed in
1979 after Egypt granted asylum to the ousted Iranian shah. In
1991, they agreed to open interests offices in each other's
capital as a prelude to normalizing relations.
</P>
<P>
Kharrazi said Iran's relations with the rest of the world based
on mutual respect, dialogue and consultation have entered a new
era since President Mohammad Khatami came to power last August.
</P>
<P>
Iran and Saudi Arabia have turned a new chapter in their
relations, particularly in the political field, as a result of
exchange of visits by senior officials, he said.
</P>
<P>
Tehran-Riyadh economic cooperation is keeping pace with warming
political climate, he said, adding Iran is content with expanding
relations with Saudi Arabia, a key country in the Gulf and the
Islamic world.
</P>
<P>
Referring to a forthcoming ministerial meeting of the
Organization of the Islamic Conference (OIC) in Rabat, Morocco,
Kharrazi expressed hope that it would take decisive measures
against Israeli expansionist policies, particularly that of
judaization of Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
On June 21, the Israeli government approved a plan to expand
the municipal authority of Jerusalem over eight Jewish settlements
in the West Bank, regarded by the Muslim world as an attempt to
change the status of the holy city.
</P>
<P>
The OIC has decided to hold an emergency meeting to explore
ways of confronting the Israeli move. 
</P>
</TEXT>
