<DOCNO> XIE19980722.0155 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Boost Automotive Market (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In addition to prices, quality, fees and performance also
represent the important factors consumers consider when purchasing
motor vehicles, Teng noted.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that some local governments have adopted various
measures beyond pricing to limit the number of automobiles
purchased by individuals.
</P>
<P>
Teng added that most Chinese manufacturers lack product lines
which fulfill the demands of middle income households hoping to
purchase medium to low cost vehicles.
</P>
<P>
The market still lack mechanisms to prevent price wars which
damage the interests of manufacturers, he said.
</P>
<P>
Recent projections indicate that individuals purchase more
automobile than institutions for the first time ever during
1998. However, reports also indicate that growing problems are
expected in terms of after-sales services.
</P>
<P>
A recent investigation conducted by the quality control
department in northwest China's Shaanxi Province revealed the
inferiority of some 60 percent of products on local automotive
parts markets.
</P>
<P>
China has addressed related problems by adopting a strategy
urging hundreds of the nation's automotive manufacturers to form
as many as five enterprise groups.
</P>
<P>
Experts predict that the automotive industry will achieve a
total output of between 1.65 million and 1.7 million units and
total sales of as many as 1.66 million unit during 1998.
</P>
<P>
However, they caution that effective measures must be adopted
to promote automotive market in order to ensure the targeted
economic growth rate of eight percent.  
</P>
</TEXT>
