<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Share Market Pushed Lower on Back of Wall </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, July 22 (Xinhua) -- The overnight slump on Wall
Street rubbed off on the Australian share market Wednesday, with
banks among the blue chip stocks to suffer as the local bourse
slid into negative territory, brokers said.
</P>
<P>
The benchmark all ordinaries index dropped 20.4 points to close
2,767.5 points, with the all industrials index tumbling 25.8
points to 4,856.4 and all resources index sagging 17.5 to close at
its low for the day at 1,082.2 points.
</P>
<P>
Alan Greenspan, the United States Federal Reserve chairman,
sent Wall Street on a dive with the Dow Jones Industrial Average
sliding 105.56 points to 9,190.19 following his comments in
Washington on a potential rise in inflation and concern over the
value of equities.
</P>
<P>
Morgans dealer Neil Gynther said the Wall Street slump fueled
the downward slide in the Australian market.
</P>
<P>
"We think the (U.S.) fall was a bit of an over-reaction to
Greenspan's comments and Wall Street will probably correct itself
tonight," Gynther said.
</P>
<P>
ANZ Securities associate director Michael Sargent said the
sentiment remained cautious and nervous on the Australian market.
</P>
<P>
The bank index shed 36.7 points to 6,061.3, with the "Big 4"
all losing ground.
</P>
<P>
National Australia Bank slid 23.7 cents, spooked by rumors that
chief executive Don Argus was likely to leave at the end of the
year.
</P>
<P>
Commonwealth shares fell 15 cents, ANZ dropped seven cents and
Westpac eased 0.1 cents to 10.62 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
Elsewhere in the financial sector, AMP fell 9.4 cents, News
Corp. lost 22.3 cents.
</P>
<P>
Telstra installment receipts topped turnover with 13.89 million
 receipts changing hands for 63 million Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
On the resources side, BHP tumbled 30 cents, while fellow
diversified miners WMC lost seven cents and Rio Tinto gained four
cents.
</P>
<P>
The gold index dropped 20.8 points to 1,113.6, as the price of
the precious metal weakened. The spot price of gold bullion in
Sydney was 294.25 U.S. dollars an ounce, compared with Tuesday's
close of 295.75.
</P>
<P>
National turnover was 306.89 million stocks traded for 878.4
million Australian dollars (549 million U.S. dollars), with
falling stocks outnumbering rising stocks 605 to 378. 
</P>
</TEXT>
