<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Navigation Resumes on Yangtze River </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YICHANG, July 22 (Xinhua) -- The temporary shiplock at the
Three Gorges Dam Project resumed operation at eight o'clock today
after being shut down for 11 days because of recent heavy floods.
</P>
<P>
It took about 20 minutes for the first six ships that were
blocked at Maoping Port in Yichang City, site of the Three Gorges
Dam Project, to pass through the shiplock this morning.
</P>
<P>
A total of 1,098 passenger and cargo ships have been stranded
at the port for the past few days and the 165,000 passengers on
board have been moved to safety.
</P>
<P>
Ships can pass through the shiplock safely when the water flow
through the Three Gorges Dam Project drops below 45,000 cubic
meters per second, according to a spokesman for the Yangtze
Navigation Administration Bureau.
</P>
<P>
He said that the water flow was measured at 41,000 cubic meters
per seconds at 5:00 pm today, which means that the shiplock is
safe for ships to pass.
</P>
<P>
However, the river canal at the Three Gorges Dam will not be
open until the water flow drops further.
</P>
<P>
According to weather forecasts, heavy rains might fall at the
upper reaches of Yangtze River in the next few days, and the Three
Gorges Dam may have to suspend navigation for a third time if the
water flow reaches 45,000 cubic meters again. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980722.0161 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Old Stone Age Site Unearthed in Central China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZHENGZHOU, July 22 (Xinhua) -- A workshop dating back to the
Old Stone Age recently unearthed in Luoyang, Henan Province, once
again proves that central China was a melting pot for southern and
northern Chinese cultures.
</P>
<P>
The site, located in Beiyao at the foot of Mangshan Mountain,
has yielded a large cache of stone articles.
</P>
<P>
Archeologists believe the site was a workshop for producing
stone articles during the middle to late periods of the Old Stone
Age some 200,000 years ago. They point out that stone articles
with quite different characteristics provide a piece of important
evidence proving that central China was a melting pot for southern
and northern cultures. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980722.0162 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-22 </DATE_TIME>
