<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Chinese Private Firms Form Trade Unions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, July 22 (Xinhua) -- East China's Jiangsu Province
leads the nation with some 11,000 trade unions set up in private
enterprises.
</P>
<P>
Jiangsu's private sector has witnessed robust growth in recent
years. Currently, with the province's 56,660 private firms have
total registered capital of 18.99 billion yuan (2.29 billion US
dollars) and work force of over 650,000 people.
</P>
<P>
Official statistics show that a wooden furniture workshop in
the city of Yancheng in northern Jiangsu was the first private
Chinese firm to form its own trade union in 1987.
</P>
<P>
In April 1996, the municipal congress in Nanjing, the
provincial capital, unveiled China's first set of detailed
regulations governing trade unions in private enterprises.
</P>
<P>
More than 95 percent of Nanjing's private enterprises with 25
or more employees have now founded trade unions.
</P>
<P>
Jiangsu neighbors on Shanghai Municipality, China's largest
economic and financial center, and is one of the nation's leading
provinces in terms of economic development. 
</P>
</TEXT>
