<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Southern Africa to Have Gas-Fired Power Plants </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 22 (Xinhua) -- Two gas-fired power stations
will be built in Namibia and South Africa in the next six years,
which would be the first gas-fired power plants in southern
Africa.
</P>
<P>
Officials of Shell Exploration and Production Namibia Tuesday
announced plans to built the two stations, the first at
Oranjemund, on the Namibian coast near the border with South
Africa, and the second in Cape Town, Business Day paper reported
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Both would use the gas from the Kudu field, 107 kilometers off
the Namibian coast, the company officials said in Windhoek.
</P>
<P>
The first phase of the project, which includes development of
offshore facilities, a pipeline to Oranjemund, and a 750 MW power
plant and its associated power transmission connection, requires
about 5.3 billion Rand (855 million U.S. Dollars) of capital
investment.
</P>
<P>
The company said it was expected to be in operation by 2002
and half the power would be exported to South Africa's Western
Cape Province, which lacks strong primary fuel support.
</P>
<P>
The second phase of the project is to pipe the Namibian gas to
South Africa's Western Cape Province to feed a new power station
in Cape Town as well as support the province's industrial steel
production.
</P>
<P>
Shell's investment in phase two was estimated at 9 billion
Rand (1.45 billion Dollars), including that for offshore
infrastructure development, an overland pipeline to the Western
Cape, and the power station in Cape Town.
</P>
<P>
The company said the second phase was planned to be in
production toward the end of 2003 and it would bring about
significant benefits for Namibia and South Africa. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
