<HEADLINE> State Development Bank To Increase Loans To Northwest China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LANZHOU, July 22 (Xinhua) -- The State Development Bank,
China's primary policy bank, plans to increase loans for
infrastructure construction projects and focus on supporting
economic development in the northwest.
</P>
<P>
The bank, established in 1994, has attached great importance to
improving economic growth in northwest China and complying with
the the country's strategies for regional development.
</P>
<P>
The bank had granted loans of some 0.6 billion yuan to related
areas by the end of June, with the outstanding loans in excess of
7.2 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
Most loans went for 251 projects, including 75 state
projects. Gansu ranks first in the region in the use of related
bank loans and accounts for 33 percent of total outstanding funds.
</P>
<P>
The bank provided loans totalling seven billion yuan to the area
during the first half of the year, up 2.7 billion yuan on the 1997
period. The major portion of loan funds were used for the
construction of power plants, transmission lines and transformers,
as well as the development of coal mines, petroleum and natural
gas resources and improvements of railway lines.
</P>
<P>
The bank raises both domestic and overseas funds and grants
mid- to long-term loans for infrastructure projects, and both
basic and pillar industries in accordance with the nation's laws,
regulations and policies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
