<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-22 10:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 1stLd Writethru: Iranian Majlis Approves Naming of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, July 22 (Xinhua) -- Iran's conservative-dominated
Majlis (parliament) on Wednesday approved the nomination by
President Mahammad Khatami of Abdolvahed Mousavi Lari as the new
interior minister.
</P>
<P>
Lari, who is vice president for legal and parliamentary
affairs, won a vote of confidence following a four-hour heated
debate at the 270-seat Majlis' opening session.
</P>
<P>
Lari won 177 votes out of a total of 266, with 67 against and
22 abstentions.
</P>
<P>
Khatami nominated Lari for the post on July 15, after Adollah
Nouri, the previous interior minister who bore the brunt for
allowing pro-government political demonstrations across the
country, was impeached by the Majlis last month.
</P>
<P>
In order to convince the right-wing parliamentarians, Khatami
personally attended session and urged the lawmakers to support his
government through a vote of confidence to Lari.
</P>
<P>
He praised Lari as a "clear-sighted, rational and committed
personality" in the country, "who is fully capable of performing
his duties, and serves as a consolidating factor within the
government."
</P>
<P>
Khatami said he believed Lari's experiences in and knowledge
about the Majlis would help consolidate the relations between the
government and the Majlis.
</P>
<P>
Lari, 44, once served as a Majlis member and was appointed a
vice president after Khatami was elected president May last year
in a landslide victory over the conservative candidate, Majlis
speaker Ali Akbar Nateq-Nouri.
</P>
<P>
Before the Majlis debate, Lari attended a meeting of the
right-wing legislators Tuesday night, answering questions about
his belief in the supreme leadership, his attitude towards the
Guardians Council and the Constitution as well as his future
program.
</P>
<P>
A leading conservative lawmaker, Mohammad Reza Bahonar, said
the Majlis majority faction (conservative) decided to approve
Lari's appointment in a bid to reduce tension between the
conservatives and moderates, although he spoke against him at the
Majlis session, the official news agency IRNA reported.
</P>
<P>
Factional struggle has become sensitive after the former
interior minister was ousted by the conservative Majlis, and
Tehran Mayor Gholamhussein Karbaschi, a close ally of Khatami, was
put on an open trial on embezzlement charges last month.
</P>
<P>
Despite the Majlis' approval of the new interior minister, the
hardliners are expected to put more pressure on Khatami due to the
wide differences over political development and economic
reforms. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
