<HEADLINE> Russian Oil Firms Blame Government for Yielding to IMF </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, July 22 (Xinhua) -- Eight oil and gas conglomerates in
Russia Wednesday accused the government of yielding to the
pressure of international financial institutions and pursuing
policies "fraught with serious social consequences."
</P>
<P>
In a message sent to President Boris Yeltsin, the eight
companies -- YUKOS, LUK, Gazprom, Sidanko, Sibneft,
Surgutneftegaz, Tyumen and Eastern Oil Company -- said that the
international lending agencies' policy toward the Russian basic
industries was "irresponsible," the Itar-Tass news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
"It deepens the crisis, aggravates the social situation and is
fraught with bankruptcy of enterprises which are (otherwise) able
to work efficiently," the message added.
</P>
<P>
They warned of "irreversible social and economic consequences"
which could happen over the next two or three months.
</P>
<P>
They believed that the perceived social and economic disorder
ahead would be "a direct consequence of actions by the government
which had sufficient possibilities to influence the situation."
</P>
<P>
The International Monetary Fund (IMF) Monday announced to
provide 11.2 billion U.S. dollars to support the Russian
government's economic program for 1998. 
