<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Small Businesses Embrace Internet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, July 21 (Xinhua) -- Small businesses in the United
States accessing the Internet increased dramatically from 19.7
percent in 1996 to 41.2 percent in 1998, according to a new study
of the International Data Corp (IDC).
</P>
<P>
IDC's survey of 1,011 U.S. firms with fewer than 100 employees
confirmed the dramatic growth of small business online cuts across
all company size categories.
</P>
<P>
The percentage of companies with under five employees that
access the Internet more than doubled from 1996 to 1997, climbing
from 17.2 percent to 36.4 percent. However, smaller companies do
lag behind larger ones in overall online penetration.
</P>
<P>
The Internet is widely viewed as a vital business resource for
specific industry and competitive information. Small businesses
are overwhelmingly accepting the Internet as critical to the
operation and management of their business.
</P>
<P>
IDC's study shows Internet usage among U.S. small businesses is
gaining momentum, with penetration forecast to approach 4.3
million small firms by 2001.
</P>
<P>
The study also found that the professional service sector, such
as law firms, insurance agencies, real estate agencies and
accounting firms, leads in Internet usage, with 63 percent of PC
owners online.
</P>
<P>
Among the laggards are retail and health care industries.
Internet users in manufacturing companies log onto the Internet
most frequently and for the broadest range of applications.
</P>
<P>
PC-owning small business with home pages will increase from 9
percent in 1997 to 20.1 percent by 2001, according to IDC.
</P>
<P>
Thirty-six percent of small businesses that plan to go online
expect to use the Internet to sell products. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980722.0179 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kuala Lumpur Stocks Close Lower </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, July 22 (Xinhua) -- Share prices on the Kuala
Lumpur Stock Exchange closed broadly lower Wednesday due to lack
of interest and continued selling pressure by institutional
players on blue chips.
</P>
<P>
At the close, the 100-quality stocks Composite Index fell 15.91
points to close at 421.91, a 3.63 percent lower from 437.82 points
at Tuesday's close.
</P>
<P>
The all-share Emas Index fell 3.09 points to 106.97, the
Industrial Index lost 20.54 points to 888.83 and the Second Board
was down by 0.70 of a point to 91.64.
</P>
<P>
Losers overwhelmed gainers by 423 to 115, while 149 counters
were unchanged, 235 untraded and 44 suspended.
</P>
<P>
The day's total turnover declined to 101.459 million shares
valued at 175.438 million ringgit (about 42.274 million U.S.
dollars) from 103.729 million shares valued at 202.464 million
ringgit (about 48.786 million dollars) on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The main board turnover fell to 96.700 million shares valued at
169.898 million ringgit (about 40.939 million dollars) from
100.458 million shares worth 198.079 million ringgit (about 47.729
million dollars) on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The second board turnover increased to 4.759 million shares
worth 5.540 million ringgit (about 1.334 million dollars) from
Tuesday's 3.272 million shares valued at 4.384 million ringgit
(about 1.056 million dollars).
</P>
<P>
Off market deals decreased to 1.336 million shares valued at
3.215 million ringgit (about 0.774 million dollars) from Tuesday's
6.781 million shares worth 16.264 million ringgit (about 3.919
million dollars).
</P>
<P>
On a sectoral basis, consumer products accounted for 5.074
million shares traded on the main board, industrial products 7.304
million shares, construction 9.394 million shares,
trading/services 30.294 million shares, infrastructure 322,000
shares, finance 23.195 million shares, hotels 210,000 shares,
properties 8.470 million shares, plantation 3.302 million shares,
mining 213,000 shares, trusts 58,000 shares, closed/fund 56,000
shares and loans 8.808 million shares. 
