<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Joint Year 2000 Council Has New Chairman </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, July 22 (Xinhua) -- U.S. banker Roger W. Ferguson
Jr. has become chairman of the Joint Year 2000 Council, according
to a press released Tuesday by the Basel-based Bank for
International Settlements (BIS).
</P>
<P>
The Joint Year 2000 Council, formed in April 1998, is meant to
ensure a high level of attention to the Year 2000 computer problem
(Y2K) on the part of the global financial supervisory community.
</P>
<P>
The Year 2000 computer problem, also known as "millennium bug,"
will cause many computers to recognize the new millennium as the
year 1900. Many computers and programs read only two digits for
the year and cannot tell 2000 from 1900.
</P>
<P>
"I am pleased to have been selected to chair the Joint Year
2000 Council," said Ferguson, who is a member of the Board of
Governors of the Federal Reserve System.
</P>
<P>
"Preparing for the Year 2000 is of vital interest globally," he
added. "I am eager to work with the council to provide guidance
and assistance for financial supervisors and market participants
in all countries regarding the steps they need to take to meet the
challenge."
</P>
<P>
The Joint Year 2000 Council comprises senior representatives of
its four sponsoring organizations: the Basel Committee on Banking
Supervision, the Committee on Payment and Settlement Systems, the
International Association of Insurance Supervisors and the
International Organization of Securities Commissions. Its
secretariat is provided by the BIS. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
