<DOCNO> XIE19980722.0181 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria's New Transition Plan Welcomed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 22 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria's new transition to civil
rule program due to end May 29, 1999 have received general
welcome from both internal and the international society.
</P>
<P>
United Nations Human Rights Commissioner Mary Robinson
welcomed the announcement of release of political prisoners,
respect for human rights and free elections, as made by Nigerian
Head of State, General Abdulsalam Abubakar in a national
broadcast Monday night.
</P>
<P>
Robinson said in Geneva Tuesday that her office was "ready to
assist Nigeria's success in its process of transition, which in
order to be successful must take full account of all human
rights."
</P>
<P>
Commonwealth Secretary-General Chief Emeka Anyaoku said the
new program was further evidence of Abubakar's commitment to
national reconciliation and establishment of a credible process
to democracy in Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
"It is my sincere hope that the new transition program
announced by the Head of State will lead to an open transparent
political process in which Nigerians can participate," Anyaoku
said Tuesday on the British Broadcasting Corporation (BBC).
</P>
<P>
He announced that the Commonwealth will watch closely the
implementation of the program, adding that Nigeria's suspension
from the organization will remain until the civilian government
was sworn in.
</P>
<P>
The United Kingdom also welcomed the development. A Foreign
Office statement said Britain will persuade its European Union
partners to remove the visa ban on senior Nigerian officials,
which, it said would help the transition program and promote
constructive dialog.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Office Minister Tony Lloyd who recently visited
Nigeria said: "This is the best news we have had from Nigeria for
a long time."
</P>
<P>
U.S State Department Spokesman James Rubin said on the Voice
of America (VOA) that Abubakar's "reform goals meet U.S. concerns
and conform largely with U.S. recommendations for Abuja."
</P>
<P>
South Africa and Japan also gave their support to the new
transition program.
</P>
<P>
Within Nigeria, the program had also been well received, but
with apparent cautions.
</P>
<P>
Alhaji M.D. Yusuf, a presidential aspirant under the
transition program of General Sani Abacha said in Lagos that
Abubakar's broadcast contained some solutions to fundamental
problems facing the nation.
</P>
<P>
He expressed disappointment over the extension of military's
hand over date from October to May next year, but quickly added
that the explanations by Abubakar "are quite acceptable."
</P>
<P>
Former Supreme Court Judge Kayode Eso said the program is
excellent and prayed that it will not be hijacked.
</P>
<P>
Former Speaker of House of Representatives, Chief Agunwa
Anaekwe said he believes that the transition program is real and
achievable. As for the dissolved parties, he said the injury was
caused by the parties themselves so they should not complain.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
