<HEADLINE> UK to Press EU to Lift Ban on Nigeria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 22 (Xinhua) -- Britain pledged Tuesday to ensure
an early lifting of the travel sanctions imposed on senior
Nigerian government officials by the European Union.
</P>
<P>
The move made just as the Commonwealth assured that a return
to credible democracy will facilitate the country's return to its
fold, would promote constructive dialog as well as ensure the
success of the political transition program unveiled by Nigerian
Head of State General Abdulsalam Abubakar Monday night, the Daily
Times reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Reflecting London's view, Foreign Office Minister Tony Lloyd
said General Abubakar's statement committing himself to the
restoration of democratic civilian government next May after free
and fair elections and his undertaking to respect human rights
and democracy were commendable.
</P>
<P>
"This is the best news we have heard from Nigeria for a long
time," the minister was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
"Britain is ready to help General Abubakar and his new
administration with the speedy and credible implementation of
this difficult but essential program," he said.
</P>
<P>
According to him, Britain will work to ensure that EU partners
allow Nigerian government officials to visit EU member states
where this would help General Abubakar's program and promote
constructive dialog.
</P>
<P>
In a nationally televised address Monday night, General
Abubakar announced that the date for the military to hand over
power to a civilian government was re-set on May 29 next year,
against the October 1, 1998 date fixed by his predecessor General
Sani Abacha who died of heart attack on June 8.
</P>
<P>
The extension is made for fresh elections to be held,
involving all Nigerians irrespective of their political leanings
or tribal backgrounds.
</P>
<P>
Abubakar also announced the release of all political prisoners
in the country, among other things.
</P>
<P>
Apart from Britain and the Commonwealth, United Nations
Secretary-General Kofi Annan and the governments of the United
States, Japan and South Africa have also expressed welcome to the
new transition program.
</P>
<P>
The positive response from the international community so far
is seen by analysts here as a major breakthrough for the present
military administration in this most populous African country.
</P>
</TEXT>
