<HEADLINE> Share Prices Extend Losses on Singapore Stock Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, July 22 (Xinhua) -- Share prices extended their
losses on Singapore Stock Market after taking a hammering on
Tuesday when the market ended 3 percent lower from the previous
day.
</P>
<P>
The benchmark Straits Times Industrials Index (STII) Wednesday
dropped 9.80 points to close at 1052.66 points, reacting to
overnight weakness on Wall Street and a slide in regional
currencies as well as a decline in global semiconductor prices.
</P>
<P>
The total turnover was 108.77 million shares, valued at 218.64
million Singapore dollars (about 127.93 million U.S. dollars).
Falls outstripped rises by 206 to 60, while 323 stocks remained
unchanged.
</P>
<P>
TAC 200 remained the most active stock as it finished on a
turnover of 7.10 million units. It was followed by UIC which had
6.53 million counters done. MBF was next with 6.23 million shares
changing hands.
</P>
<P>
CenProp was the top gainer of the day as it edged up 45 cents
to finish at 9.65 Singapore dollars. Asean inched up 20 cents to
end at 6.00 U.S. dollars. RothmansI was up 20 cents to close at
8.10 Singapore dollars.
</P>
<P>
On the downside, Creative 50 remained the biggest loser of the
day as it lost 60 cents to end 20.30 Singapore dollars. KepFELS
shed by 40 cents to finish at 3.86 Singapore dollars while SIA F
slipped by 40 cents to finish at 8.40 Singapore dollars.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said the more than 100 points drop in DOW on Tuesday
was in part fueled by U.S. Federal Reserve Chairman Alan
Greenspan's warning about the economy's inflationary risks.
</P>
<P>
They said market players in the U.S. liquidated stocks even
though Greenspan gave no indication of a change in interest rates.
</P>
<P>
The news that global semiconductor prices fell 25 percent in
the second quarter of 1998 also contributed to the losses.
</P>
</TEXT>
