<HEADLINE> Arab Nations Urged to Tighten Boycott on Israeli </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, July 22 (Xinhua) -- Palestine Wednesday urged
Arab nations to tighten their boycott on Israeli commodities and
sever whatever form of relationship they may have with Jerusalem
to protest against Israel's adamant attitude towards the
Palestine-Israel peace accord.
</P>
<P>
"We should tighten our boycott on Israeli commodities and
freeze our relations and close our liaison offices established
after the peace process was launched by the U.S.," Palestinian
Foreign Minister Farouk Khadoumi told a news conference here
Wednesday at the end of his five-day visit to Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
He said that the Arab countries had, since 1996, imposed
sanctions on Israel commodities for violating the peace accord.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian foreign minister also asked other Islamic
nations to continue to stand by Palestinian side in their
struggle.
</P>
<P>
The support is vital even though the international community
has said that the peace accord was "collapsing" due to Israel's
adamant attitude, he said.
</P>
<P>
To a question on whether terrorism and tensions will re-emerge
as Israel continues to ignore the peace agreement, he said: "I
don't know how the Palestinians can be patient when their living
conditions are becoming worse and worse."
</P>
<P>
He said Israel had contained Palestinian's economy by
controlling its airport and disallowing Palestine from building a
port, among others.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian foreign minister, who called on Malaysian Prime
Minister Mahathir Mohamad and had talks with his Malaysian
counterpart Abdullah Ahmad Badawi during the visit, thanked
Malaysia for its continuous support of the Palestinian struggle.
</P>
<P>
He said Palestine would resort to "all means" to defend its
legal national rights and free itself from foreign occupation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
