<HEADLINE> Share Prices Nosedive in Tokyo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, July 22 (Xinhua) -- Stock prices plunged in Tokyo
Wednesday as blue chips fell and banking issues continued their
downward spiral.
</P>
<P>
The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues on the First
Section of the Tokyo Stock Exchange lost 263.63 points, or 1.59
percent, from Tuesday's close to end at 16,293.06.
</P>
<P>
The broader-based Tokyo Stock Price Index (TOPIX), covering all
First Section issues, fell 19.32 points or 1.51 percent to
1,257.85.
</P>
<P>
Turnover on the major section went up slightly to an estimated
390 million shares from 363.29 million shares Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Sakura Bank was the day's most heavily traded issue.
</P>
<P>
Wednesday marked the third straight trading day of decline in
the key Nikkei index and resulted in a fall of 438.86 points, or
2.62 percent, over this period.
</P>
<P>
But traders were not worried by the fall, saying the market was
due for a correction after its 640-point, 4 percent rise last week.
</P>
<P>
Investors sold a wide variety of issues, from construction to
retailers, throughout the day.
</P>
<P>
Traders said some selling may have been sparked by news reports
that Foreign Minister Keizo Obuchi has gained the initial lead in
the ruling Liberal Democratic Party's presidential election as he
won support from the heavyweights of the party.
</P>
<P>
Last week, the index rose on the news that Seiroku Kajiyama
would enter the race for Japan's top political post. The former
chief cabinet secretary is seen as being more aggressive about
banking sector reform than Obuchi.
</P>
<P>
Of the 1,332 issues listed on the First Section, losers
overwhelmed gainers 885 to 250, with 133 issues remaining
unchanged.
</P>
<P>
On the Tokyo Foreign Exchange, the U.S. dollar climbed to
140.95 yen as declining stock prices slowed purchases of yen.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. currency was quoted at 140.65-75 yen at 5 p.m. (local
time), up from 140.22-25 yen at 9 a.m. in Tokyo and from 140.30-40
yen late Tuesday in New York. 
</P>
</TEXT>
