<HEADLINE> Rainstorm Hits Dongting Lake Area </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGSHA, July 22 (Xinhua) -- Heavy rainfall hit the Dongting
Lake area in central-south China's Henan Province over the past
few day, adding to problems resulting from torrential rains in
June and once again placing some dikes and dams in great danger.
</P>
<P>
The city of Yueyang recorded a rainfall of 79 mm and strong
winds over a two-hour period on July 20. A pontoon belonging to
the local armed police unit sunk during the storm, with a 600
meter crack opening in the embankment surrounding Caisang Lake.
</P>
<P>
The city has organized 230,000 people and some 140 boats to
fight heavy flooding.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the storms have also created serious problems in a
1,500 meter section of dikes in Linxiang City, with the local
government taking emergency measures to secure all local dikes. In
addition, a 3,000 meter section of recently constructed dikes have
washed away in Huarong County.
</P>
<P>
Water levels along 27 dikes in the lake area remain above the
warning marks.
</P>
<P>
Torrential rains have also hit the city of Zhangjiajie and the
Western Hunan Tujia-Miao Autonomous Prefecture over the past two
days, causing damages of varying degrees in 110 villages of three
counties.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980722.0195 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Guangzhou Developing Private Sector </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, July 22 (Xinhua) -- Guangzhou, capital of south
China's Guangdong Province, is engaged in an extensive effort to
encourage development of the local private sector.
</P>
<P>
The city recently adopted a regulation granting private
ventures the same legal status state-owned firms enjoy in terms of
foreign trade and land-use rights, and obtaining bank loans.
</P>
<P>
The regulation also stipulates that private businesses have the
right to determine the legal responsibility of those infringing on
their property rights.
</P>
<P>
The private sector paid 1997 taxes of over 1.37 billion yuan,
or five percent of the city's total industrial and commercial tax
revenue. The sector's work force of some 600,000 laborers
represents close to 30 percent of the total number for state-owned
enterprises.
</P>
<P>
The sector has also been granted preferential policies to
attract talent people. For example, private firms are allowed to
directly select university graduates, with related firms hiring
over 200 graduates during 1997.
</P>
<P>
A labor contract and compulsory pension system has also been
introduced to guarantee the rights of people working in the
private sector in Guangzhou.
</P>
<P>
The sector has expanded its business scope from the service
industry to wide-ranging areas, including energy, transportation
and real estate. The city has already approved some 40 private
real estate agencies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
