<DOCNO> XIE19980722.0196 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-22 09:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> OIC Urges to Confront Israel's Jerusalem Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 22 (Xinhua) -- Assistant Secretary General of the
Organization of the Islamic Conference (OIC) Abdel Aziz Abu Ghush
Wednesday stressed the need to confront Israel's expansionist
measures in Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with Voice of Arabs radio here, Ghush called
for support to the Palestinian people in resisting and confronting
"Israeli plots" and in preserving the Arab and Islamic identity of
the holy city.
</P>
<P>
Ghush urged the OIC's Jerusalem Committee, which is to convene
next week in Moroccan capital Rabat, to come up with serious and
effective resolutions against Israeli high-handed policy.
</P>
<P>
He also called on the international community to shoulder its
responsibility to urge Israel to comply with relevant
U.N. resolutions and statements on Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
According to the Oslo accords, the fate of Jerusalem will be
negotiated in the Palestinian-Israeli final status talks. Before
that, neither side should take unilateral action to change the
city's status, geographic composition and other characteristics.
</P>
<P>
But on June 21, Israeli cabinet approved a Jerusalem expansion
plan that extend the city's municipal authority to eight Jewish
settlements in the West Bank, which stirred a storm of criticism
inside and outside Israel.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Security Council issued a presidential statement last
week to rebut the Israeli plan as a "serious and damaging
development" in the peace process and to urge Israel not to
proceed with the project.
</P>
<P>
Israel claims Jerusalem as its undivided and eternal capital
while the Palestinians want the Arab East Jerusalem as capital of
their future state.
</P>
<P>
Peace negotiations between the two sides were deadlocked in
March last year when Israel broke ground for a Jewish settlement
in East Jerusalem. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980722.0197 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Enjoys Growing Foreign Exchange Reserves </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 22 (Xinhua) -- China's foreign exchange reserves
hit 140.51 billion US dollars by the end of June, up 620 million
US dollars on the beginning of the year, according to a spokesman
for the State Administration of Foreign Exchange.
</P>
<P>
Expanding reform and policy adjustments have enabled China to
record positive progress in efforts to increase investments,
improve infrastructure, promote exports and use foreign capital,
according to the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
He said that has enjoyed balanced international payments over
the past six months, in spite of certain negative effects
resultant from the Asian financial crisis, the drastic devaluation
of the Japanese yen in particular.
</P>
<P>
China's foreign trade surplus reached 22.6 billion US dollars
during the period, with the figure growing by 26.6 percent on the
previous year's period to 4.8 billion US dollars. Direct foreign
investment totaled 20.5 billion US dollars, remaining basically at
the same level recorded during the first half of last year.
</P>
<P>
Supply and demand on the domestic foreign exchange market
remained in balance, with a wide margin growth in foreign exchange
savings on the part of both individuals and enterprises.
</P>
<P>
The June 30 Renminbi-US dollar exchange rate stood at
8.2798:1, with the rate remaining stable when compared to the
8.2796:1 level earlier this year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
