<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tajik President Vows to Catch Murderers of U.N. Observers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, July 22 (Xinhua) -- Tajikistan's President Emomali
Rakhmonov pledged Wednesday to find the murderers who killed four
United Nations observers Monday, the Itar-Tass news agency reports
said.
</P>
<P>
Rakhmonov made the pledge during a meeting with Jan Kubis,
U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan's envoy to the country.
</P>
<P>
Their discussions were believed to focus on the murder of two
U.N. military observers, a mission councillor and a Tajik driver,
Itar-Tass said.
</P>
<P>
Three of the victims were foreigners: Otaka Akino of Japan,
Ryszard Szevczek of Poland and Adolfo Siarpegu of Uruguay.
</P>
<P>
They were killed on their way from the district of Tavildara to
the town of Labidzhar, which is 170 kilometers east of the capital
Dushanbe. All bodies showed gunshot wounds.
</P>
<P>
The four men were reportedly going on a peace-keeping mission
when attacked.
</P>
<P>
In the aftermath of the assassination, Kubis said all staff
members of the U.N. mission in Tajikistan are recalled to the
capital from the regions.
</P>
<P>
Khabib Sanginov, head of the Dushanbe-based military
sub-commission of the National Reconciliation Commission, said the
murder was a premeditated act representing a stab in the back of
the whole peace process in Tajikistan and undermining the
country's prestige on the international arena.
</P>
<P>
However, he urged the media not to rush to premature
conclusions implicating some side in the crime, Itar-Tass added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980722.0199 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World's Biggest Mural In Southern China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANTOU July 22 (Xinhua) -- A large mural made of ceramic tile
was completed recently in the city of Chaozhou in south China's
Guangdong Province and has already been recognized by the Guiness
Book of World Records.
</P>
<P>
The mural is 62 meters long and 2.9 meters high. It is made of
more than 1,900 ceramic tiles and took 46 people three years to
create.
</P>
<P>
It is a copy of a 12th century horizontal scroll by Zhang
Zeduan, a renowned painter of Northern Song Dynasty (960-1127),
which was entitled "Riverside Scenes during the Qingming
Festival", depicting the people's lives in an eastern suburb of
the Song capital at Bianliang (in present day Kaifeng, Henan
Province), but is 100 times the size of the original.
</P>
<P>
The mural was made by craftsmen from the Jiangnan Porcelain
Corporation in Chaozhou. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980722.0200 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Stimulatory Policies Will Not Affect Reform Process </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 22 (Xinhua) - World Bank vice president and chief
economist Joseph Stiglitz today expressed confidence in China's
ability to rise above challenges posed by the financial crisis in
East Asia crisis and fulfill its long-term structural reform
program.
</P>
<P>
"China faces two economic challenges the first being the
transition from a socialist market economy with its own
characteristics, and the second the pursuit of short-term
stimulatory policies without harming the long-term agenda for
structural reform." according to Joseph Stiglitz, senior
vice-president of the World Bank.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at today's Beijing press conference, Stiglitz praised
China's sound economy and proper economic policies as two factors
enabling the nation to weather the financial storm. Stiglitz
expressed his firm belief that the government's stimulatory
policies will be effective in the short-term, and will not affect
the structural economic program in the long-term.
</P>
<P>
"The two challenges are complementary. China has the wisdom to
recognize the challenges and the capabilities to deal with them
effectively." according to Stiglitz.
</P>
<P>
He admitted that the crisis in East Asia has indeed had some
effects on China and has necessitated short-term policies to
stimulate gross domestic demand to ensure sustained growth.
</P>
<P>
Recent statistics show that the Chinese economy registered a
growth of seven percent during the January-June period, or one
percent lower than the annual target of eight percent. The
economy grew 8.8 percent in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Stiglitz explained that time is most often required to see the
effectiveness of economic policies, with monetary policies usually
having a lag of six to 18 months.
</P>
<P>
His view is obviously shared by Chinese economists, who point
out that increased investment is expected to boost the economy
significantly in the remainder of the year. Investment growth for
the first half year stood at 13.8 percent, up 3.5 percent on the
first quarter, with actual growth for June expected to reach 16.3
percent.
</P>
<P>
Stiglitz stressed the importance for China to maintain strong
growth since the economy is adapted to a high-growth scenario, and
noted that any significant slowing will have a variety of adverse
effects on both unemployment and profitability.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that the Chinese government is fully aware of
the adverse effects short-term policies might have on the
long-term reform agenda and will continue to emphasize reforms
when adopting related policies to stimulate the economy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980722.0201 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-22 </DATE_TIME>
