<HEADLINE> S. African Cinema Giant Aims to Conquer Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 22 (Xinhua) -- South Africa's biggest
cinema operator, Ster-Kinekor, plans to develop its cinema
complexes throughout Africa.
</P>
<P>
The company haW`qnveiled an aggressive expansion plan which
eyes the markets in Zimbabwe, Botswana, Namibia, Tanzania,
Uganda, Kenya, Mozambique, Malawi, Zambia, Gabon and Cote
d'Ivoire, Business Day paper reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Development executive Anton Botha said some of the group's
investment projects in these countries were at the final approval
stage.
</P>
<P>
The company, which has 72 percent market share in South
Africa, has also committed 62 million Rand (10 million U.S.
Dollars) over the next two years to expanding its local
operations by 12 complexes, and a further 26 projects are being
considered.
</P>
<P>
The 12 new cinema complexes, which translate into 70 screens
and 12,000 seats, will bring Ster-Kinekor's South African screen
capacity to about 500 at 75 complexes.
</P>
<P>
The company, which is wholy owned by entertainment and media
group Primedia, aimed to increase its market share by continuing
to develop and refurbish its complexes in major cities locally
and capturing new markets in smaller towns.
</P>
<P>
It would target predominantly black residential areas, Botha
said. A complex was planned for Soweto, the big black township
outside Johannesburg, and a few others were in the pipeline.
</P>
</TEXT>
