<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kuwait May Free Jordanian Prisoners: Jordan's FM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, July 22 (Xinhua) -- Jordan's Foreign Minister Jawad
Anani has said Kuwait may release the last batch of Jordanian
prisoners held in the emirate since 1991, the Jordan Times daily
reported on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"We have not received anything from the Kuwaiti side on this
issue, but unofficial information indicates that something
regarding this might take place," Anani, who is also a deputy
prime minister for development affairs, said.
</P>
<P>
"This is a step in the right direction towards normalizing
ties between the two countries," the foreign minister said. But he
did not elaborate.
</P>
<P>
Scores of Jordanians were jailed in Kuwait in 1991 for alleged
collaboration with Iraqi troops during their occupation of the
small Gulf state from August, 1990 to February, 1991.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait set free most of those prisoners in the past two years
except eight who have been sentenced to life imprisonment. Anani's
remarks came amid signs that Kuwait intended to warm up bilateral
ties.
</P>
<P>
On July 16, Kuwait's Crown Prince Sheikh Saad Al-Abdullah
Al-Salem Al-Sabah sent a message to his Jordanian counterpart
Hassan expressing willingness to restore rapprochement and
cooperation with Jordan.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait froze ties with Jordan after accusing it of siding with
Iraq during the 1990-91 Gulf crisis. It closed the Jordanian
embassy in Kuwait and recalled its ambassador.
</P>
<P>
They normalized relations in 1996, and in July 1997 resumed
commercial flights between each other's capital as an indication
of improved ties. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
