<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cambodia Admission Depends on Poll Results: ASEAN </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 22 (Xinhua) -- Whether Cambodia can join the
Association of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN) this year will be
decided by the results of its elections later this month, an ASEAN
official said here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"The question of the membership of Cambodia in the ASEAN will
depend on the results of the elections of July 26," Lauro Baja,
undersecretary of foreign affairs of the Philippines, told a press
briefing here Wednesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Baja, whose country is the chairman of this year's ASEAN annual
meetings, said an ASEAN Senior Officials Meeting, which ended here
earlier Wednesday, discussed regional and international issues,
mainly on Cambodia.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the ASEAN foreign ministers, who are scheduled to
start meeting here Friday, may decide on Cambodia's membership
depending on the results as assessed by a joint international
observer group, which is already in the country to see if the
polls are free and fair.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN had earlier last year decided to admit Cambodia into the
regional grouping together with Laos and Myanmar, but it later
deferred the admission owing to political turmoil in the country.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN now groups Brunei, Indonesia, Laos, Malaysia, Myanmar,
the Philippines, Singapore, Thailand and Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
The two-day SOM, together with a meeting of the ASEAN Standing
Committee, was held to make preparations for the AMM, including
the consideration of the political part of a joint communique to
be issued by the AMM.
</P>
<P>
Baja said the situation in the region will be one of the main
topics of the AMM, but the senior officials at the meeting had not
reached any decision on whether to issue a separate statement on
the financial situation in the region because most of them had not
received instructions from their countries.
</P>
<P>
The financial crisis, which broke out in July last year, has
caused serious problems to some ASEAN member countries, including
drastic currency devaluation and high unemployment rate.
</P>
<P>
On the possibility of an ASEAN shift in its policy from
non-intervention in member countries' internal affairs to
"flexible engagement" as proposed by the Philippines and Thailand,
Baja said the SOM had discussed the matter, but it will be up to
the foreign ministers to discuss and make a decision on it.
</P>
<P>
However, according to ASEAN official sources, other members are
not keen on the proposal. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980722.0215 </DOCNO>
