<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IBM to Release Copper Chip This Summer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, July 21 (Xinhua) -- IBM's first copper processor,
which uses copper wire rather than aluminum to connect
transistors, will come out later this summer, a computer
information provider reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Code-named Lone Star, the copper processor will run at speeds
of 400 MHz and lower, the Computer Net (CNET) quoted sources close
to the International Business Machines Corporation (IBM) as saying.
</P>
<P>
The report added that versions running at 333 MHz and 366 MHz
are expected to be available not later than this september.
</P>
<P>
While the first versions of the chip will only slightly boost
performance over current aluminum microprocessors, future copper
processors are expected to reach speeds up to 1 GHz (1,000 MHz),
experts said.
</P>
<P>
IBM's microprocessor operations often go unnoticed due to the
large shadow cast by chip-giant, the Intel Corporation. But the
release of the copper processors will highlight the Big Blue's
efforts to take the lead in one of the most critical new chip
technologies for the next decade.
</P>
<P>
Beyond the shift in metals, IBM will use a 0.18-micron
manufacturing process to produce these chips, a more advanced
technique than Intel currently uses on its production lines.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980722.0217 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fresh Strike Hits Philippine Airlines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 22 (Xinhua) -- Thousands of members of the
Philippine Airlines Employees Association (PALEA) staged a wildcat
strike early Wednesday morning which may finally sink the
debt-ridden national flag carrier.
</P>
<P>
Labeling the strike as a "reckless and ill-advised action," the
management of the Philippine Airlines (PAL) said in a statement
that the walkout was "illegal" since it was expressly prohibited
by the Labor Department.
</P>
<P>
The walkout of ground crew and flight attendants came less than
seven weeks after 625 pilots went on strike in protest of the
implementation of an alleged unfair early retirement policy,
forcing the airline to fire all striking pilots and massively
downsize its operations.
</P>
<P>
The PAL management said it failed to convince PALEA leaders not
to push through with their long-planned wildcat strike after
several weeks of fruitless marathon negotiations under the
auspices of the labor department.
</P>
<P>
The union was protesting the retrenchment of some 2,000 of
their members in line with the PAL's downsizing program under
which about 5,000 of the 13,500-strong workforce of the company
will be laid off in the near future.
</P>
<P>
Early this month, Labor Secretary Bienvenido Laguesma assumed
jurisdiction over the latest labor dispute at the PAL and ordered
the PALEA and the PAL management not to exacerbate the situation.
</P>
<P>
The PAL management said earlier that the airline, which is
already under the receivership of the Philippine Securities and
Exchange Commission, would be forced to shut down if its employees
stage another crippling strike.
</P>
<P>
The pilots' strike caused a total of 2 billion pesos (48.9
million U.S. dollars) in lost revenues, according to the PAL which
has incurred huge financial losses annually over the past 12
years. The strike has further aggravated the PAL's financial
situation.
</P>
<P>
In the last fiscal year ending in March 1998, PAL registered
8.1 billion pesos (198 million dollars) in financial losses, the
largest in a single fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
Soon after the pilots' strike, PAL, controlled by
Filipino-Chinese tycoon Lucio Tan, submitted a rehabilitation plan
to the Securities and Exchange Commission and asked the commission
to help it rehabilitate.
</P>
<P>
The plan, which has yet to be approved by the commission,
includes the layoff of one-third of its workforce, disposal of 40
of its 54 airplanes and suspension of many international and
domestic flight routes.
</P>
<P>
The PAL management said it will try to maintain limited
operations after the walkout of its ground crews and flight
attendants. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980722.0218 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-22 08:13 </DATE_TIME>
