<HEADLINE> Turkey to Buy 50 U.S. Choppers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, July 22 (Xinhua) -- Turkey is to buy from the United
States Sikorsky Company 50 S-70 Black Hawk helicopters and eight
CH-53E Super Stallion heavy-lift platforms worth 700 million
U.S. dollars, the Daily News newspaper reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"The Turkish government and Sikorsky are close to an agreement
for the utility and heavy-lift helicopter transfers, although
modalities of the possible deal are still under discussion," said
a senior government official, who declined to be named.
</P>
<P>
"Recently there has been a need for urgent acquisition of
utility helicopters that would be met through the Black Hawk
deal," he said.
</P>
<P>
If done, the deal would mark a major blow to the Franco-German
consortium Eurocopter, which always aims to expand their share on
the Turkish military jet market, defense sources said.
</P>
<P>
Sikorsky's intention regarding the copters came in early June
shortly after the French National Assembly officially passed a
motion condemning the alleged massacre of Armenians during the
rule of the Ottoman Empire early this century.
</P>
<P>
Turkish military has warned that the Turkish-French defense
cooperation would be undermined if the French legislature
continued debating the motion.
</P>
<P>
As a military power in the region, Turkey can only meet 20
percent of its defense equipment and has to purchase large amounts
of weapons and other equipments from the U.S. and other Western
countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
