<HEADLINE> Bank Interest Rates Decline in Kenya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 22 (Xinhua) -- Interest rates in Kenya continued
falling in the money market for the second week running,
according to a weekly update of the Central Bank of Kenya.
</P>
<P>
The interbank borrowing declined to 15.88 percent in the week
to July 17, from 16.87 percent in the previous week.
</P>
<P>
The 91-day Treasury Bill rate fell from 24.74 percent in the
auction dated July 13 to 24.57 percent in July 20 auction.
</P>
<P>
The average base lending rate for commercial banks also fell
from 27.78 percent to 27.76 percent in the week to Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said the down trend is a result of a general decline
in interest rates by a number of commercial banks in the wake of
the budget reading in June.
</P>
<P>
However, 1998 marks the seventh year since interest rates on
lending rose to well above 15 percent, according to an Optimum
Research report.
</P>
<P>
Over these seven years, Kenya has witnessed some of the lowest
levels of economic growth, and the highest levels of unemployment
and economic retrogression.
</P>
<P>
If the interest rates don't go below the 15 percent mark this
year, 1998 will be another tough year for the Kenyan economy as
the high rate constrains growth in investment, and causes
consumption in the economy to contract demand to fall, the
analysts warn. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
