<HEADLINE> Exhibit on ASEAN Culture Opens in Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 22 (Xinhua) -- Philippine Foreign Secretary
Domingo Siazon opened here Wednesday an exhibition displaying the
rich culture of the Association of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN)
on the occasion of the 31st ASEAN Ministerial Meeting.
</P>
<P>
The exhibit, divided into three parts, presents the rich
maritime cultural heritage of the region, shows the common aspects
of ASEAN culture and documents a variety of ASEAN-sponsored
activities.
</P>
<P>
In the part of maritime trade routes, a map of the Asian
maritime trade routes was shown together with samples of artifacts
retrieved from selected underwater sites in the Philippines.
</P>
<P>
Some common aspects of ASEAN culture being exhibited are
textile production and trade featuring textiles with different
colors, motives and materials from the nine ASEAN member
countries, namely Brunei, Indonesia, Laos, Malaysia, Myanmar, the
Philippines, Singapore, Thailand and Vietnam
</P>
<P>
Among the ASEAN activities being shown is a photo exhibit of
the various ASEAN-sponsored activities indicative of the closeness
of Southeast Asian countries through ASEAN.
</P>
<P>
The exhibition was unveiled when a series of important ASEAN
annual events are taking place in the Philippines, ASEAN's
rotating chairman this year.
</P>
<P>
The two-day ASEAN Standing Committee meeting and the ASEAN
Senior Officials Meeting closed here Wednesday. From July 24 to
29, the 31st ASEAN Ministerial Meeting, the Fifth ASEAN Regional
Forum and the ASEAN Post-Ministerial Conferences would also be
held here.
</P>
<P>
Among the highlights of the ASEAN events are the ongoing
financial crisis in East and Southeast Asia, nuclear proliferation
in South Asia, the forthcoming Cambodian elections, forest fires
in Southeast Asia, transnational crimes and water conservation.
</P>
<P>
The exhibit will last until July 29. 
</P>
</TEXT>
