<HEADLINE> Dhaka Takes Steps to Promote Labor Manpower Export </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, July 22 (Xinhua) -- The Bangladesh authority has decided
to open labor wings at Bangladeshi embassies in Dubai, Seoul and
Singapore to explore new labor markets and ensure welfare of the
expatriate workers there, press reports here said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The decision was made at a meeting of the cabinet committee on
employment of Bangladeshi nationals in foreign countries held here
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Besides, Bangladesh will also take initiatives to explore new
labor markets in South Africa, Namibia, Botswana and Malawi, Labor
and Manpower Secretary Ali Sarkar was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
The Executive Committee of the Bangladesh's National Economic
Council on July 20 approved a proposed target of manpower export
for the year 1998, according to which the country will export some
222,500 Bangladeshi workers to different countries.
</P>
<P>
About 119,000 workers have already been sent abroad in the six
months to June this year.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh exports manpower mainly to such countries as Saudi
Arabia, Kuwait, United Arab Emirates, Oman, Qatar, Bahrain,
Singapore, Malaysia, Libya and South Korea.
</P>
<P>
Manpower export is a major foreign exchange earner for the
country. Remittance from the expatriate wage earners in the July
1997-June 1998 fiscal year rose to 65.4 billion taka (about 1.39
billion U.S. dollars), up 3.61 percent from the previous fiscal
year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
