<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe to Set up More HIV Testing Centers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, July 22 (Xinhua) -- Five more voluntary HIV
counseling and testing centers will be set up in Zimbabwe this
year as the government tries to encourage people to open up about
AIDS.
</P>
<P>
Evidence from around the world has shown that infection levels
go down where voluntary counseling and testing is provided, the
daily Herald reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
In Uganda, which in the late 1980s had infection levels at 30
percent, infection levels have gone down and this has been partly
attributed to availability of counseling and testing services.
</P>
<P>
Most people who turned out to be HIV positive are known to
have changed their behavior and this helped in keeping the
infection rate down.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the Herald Tuesday, Zimbabwean Deputy
Minister of Health and Child Welfare David Parirenyatwa said the
walk-in centers were meant to give easy access to people wanting
to have their sero-status checked.
</P>
<P>
"These centers will offer quick counseling and testing
services free of unnecessary protocols and bureaucracies. The
centers will strive to be as patient-friendly as possible," the
minister said.
</P>
<P>
More than 1.5 million Zimbabweans are estimated to be infected
with HIV. This means that one in every four people has the HIV
virus. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
