<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan's Trade Surplus Up 66 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, July 22 (Xinhua) -- Japan's trade surplus from January
through June rose 66 percent from the same period last year due to
a decline in imports and depreciation of the yen against the
U.S. dollar, the Finance Ministry said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The trade surplus stood at 6,566.7 billion yen (about 48.8
billion dollars), up for the third consecutive six-month period,
the ministry said.
</P>
<P>
Exports edged up 2.2 percent to 25,267.7 billion yen (about
187.7 billion dollars), up for the eighth straight half-year term,
while imports marked the first fall since 1994, coming to 18,701
billion yen (about 138.9 billion dollars), down 9.9 percent from
the year-earlier level, it said.
</P>
<P>
The average foreign exchange rate used for the six-month report
was 134.6 yen to the dollar, compared with 120.41 yen a year
earlier.
</P>
<P>
In trade with the United States, Japan's surplus grew 37.7
percent from the same period last year to 3,073.7 billion yen
(about 22.8 billion dollars), up for the fourth straight half-year
period.
</P>
<P>
The surplus with the European Union (EU) jumped 89.7 percent to
2,015.3 billion yen (about 15 billion dollars), while that with
the financially troubled Asian countries, fell to 2,078.3 billion
yen (about 15.4 billion dollars), down 26.8 percent from the same
period last year.
</P>
<P>
"Exports to the U.S. and EU remained favorable, reflecting the
sound state of the economies in these regions, but those to Asian
countries were stagnant," a ministry official said.
</P>
<P>
"Expanding tempo of the trade surplus is expected to slow, as
the government's comprehensive economic stimulus package will
bring about positive impacts on the Japanese economy soon," the
official said.
</P>
<P>
An economist at a private financial institution, however,
expressed doubt about the effect of the stimulus package, saying
that it is unlikely to boost Japan's imports dramatically. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
