<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Spain Signs Two Accords With Bulgaria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SOFIA, July 21 (Xinhua) -- Bulgaria and Spain signed two
agreements here on Tuesday to cooperate in combatting organized
crime and developing tourism.
</P>
<P>
At a joint news conference following the signing ceremony,
visiting Spanish Prime Minister Jose Maria Aznar stressed the
significance of the agreement on issues relating to Bulgaria's
debt to Spain, the main obstacle to improving bilateral trade.
</P>
<P>
Aznar said the Bulgarian government plans to come up with a
final solution to the problem in 2.5 months.
</P>
<P>
Bulgaria's privatization program provides solid ground for
promoting trade and economic relations between the two countries,
Aznar said.
</P>
<P>
Bulgarian Prime Minister Ivan Kostov said the problems will be
settled through a debt for equity swap.
</P>
<P>
Apart from tourism and combatting organized crime, priorities
in future bilateral relations include inviting Spanish investment
to Bulgaria and boosting the commercial exchange.
</P>
<P>
Spain has already taken steps to relax the visa requirements
for Bulgarians, Aznar said. He stressed the need for tighter
controls in Bulgaria on visas for citizens from other countries
because of the problems of illegal immigration.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Aznar reiterated the support of Spain for
Bulgaria's efforts to join the European Union and NATO. He also
described the efforts of the Bulgarian government on reform as "a
real revolution that should be supported by all EU member states."
</P>
<P>
Bulgarian President Peter Stoyanov met with Spanish Prime
Minister Aznar the same day.
</P>
<P>
Aznar conveyed to President Stoyanov and Prime Minister Kostov
an invitation from Spanish King Juan Carlos to visit Spain next
year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
