<HEADLINE> Italian Government Wins Confidence Vote in Senate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, July 21 (Xinhua) -- The Italian government, led by Prime
Minister Romano Prodi, won a confidence vote by 176 to 119 with
one abstention in the Senate on Tuesday evening.
</P>
<P>
The government is very likely to win confidence vote of the
Chamber with the support of the Senate, local media reports said.
</P>
<P>
In a speech before the vote, Prodi said that the country was in
a new round of great reform, and called for "strong, decisive and
determined" support from all parties.
</P>
<P>
The confidence vote was conducted because of the differences
between the government and the Communist Refoundation Party (CR)
on the new economic policy and system reform.
</P>
<P>
The CR urged the government to give first priority to the
problems of unemployment and the great gap between the rich and
the poor in the southern area.
</P>
<P>
Focusing on development of the country's economy, the
government promised to consider appropriating money to that
region. 
</P>
