<HEADLINE> Southern Chinese Financial Institutions Prevent Unjust Competition </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, July 22 (Xinhua) -- Some provincial level financial
institutions in China's Guangdong Province have reached an
agreement on foreign exchange practices and dealing with unfair
competition.
</P>
<P>
The financial institutions have agreed to act in line with the
"rules for foreign exchange-related financial institutions in
Guangdong" to make a more favorable competitive environment for
the financial sector.
</P>
<P>
Lu Nanping, the deputy director of the State Foreign Exchange
Administration, says that the self-imposed rules are an attempt by
local financial institutions to eliminate chaos in the foreign
exchange business and to reduce risks.
</P>
<P>
Some financial institutions didn't follow government
restrictions in their business in the past and the resulting chaos
not only harms them but also endangers the state by causing
financial turmoil, Lu said.
</P>
<P>
The self-emposed rules call for the heads of 18 financial
institutions to meet regularly to review business practices. The
18 institutions involved have called for their business colleagues
to follow central bank regulations and to prepare sufficient
reserves to cover foreign exchange deposits. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
