<HEADLINE> India, U.S. Want to See Pakistan Stable, Secure </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, July 22 (Xinhua) -- India and the United States have
agreed that it is in their respective national interests to see
Pakistan as a stable and secure country, the Times of India
reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
This is said to be the most important agreement arrived at
during the third round of talks between India and the U.S.
concluded here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The two-day talks primarily on nuclear non-proliferation and
disarmament between U.S. Deputy Secretary of State Strobe Talbott
and the Indian Prime Minister's special envoy Jaswant Singh ended
without tangible results though both sides described them as
"constructive and ongoing".
</P>
<P>
According to the sources, India had conveyed three messages to
the U.S.
</P>
<P>
First, India is not an adversary of the U.S. and there are only
two issues which are not negotiable between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. has insisted that India should roll back or freeze
its nuclear weaponisation and missile programs while India has
made it clear that this is not negotiable.
</P>
<P>
Second, India asked Talbott to make it clear to his Pakistani
hosts that it would be self-defeating for Pakistan to link its
nuclear status with the Kashmir dispute.
</P>
<P>
And the third, India has spared no effort to make the U.S. into
believing that a nuclear India is a responsible power and its
foreign policy is not Pakistan-centric.
</P>
<P>
"We tried to dispel Washington's faulty impression that our
foreign and security policies would lead to war with Pakistan,"
the sources said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
