<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka's Earnings From Agriculture on Rise </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, July 22 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka earned 338.46 million
U.S. dollars from agricultural exports during the first five
months this year, an increase of 26 percent over the corresponding
period last year, according to Agricultural Ministry sources
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
A major share of the total agricultural earnings reflects the
earnings from tea during the period, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
According to available statistics tea fetched 261.5 million
dollars, showing a 37 percent increase.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, tea production increased from 76.6 million kilograms
during the same period last year to 81.3 million kilograms this
year, with an increase of six percent.
</P>
<P>
However, Sri Lanka's other two major traditional items coconut
and rubber showed a negative growth so far this year, the sources
said.
</P>
<P>
In the first quarter of 1998 rubber production declined from
42.2 million kilograms in the previous year to 32.1 million
kilograms this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
