<HEADLINE> 29 Districts Flooded, 6.4 Mln Affected in Bangladesh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, July 22 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh's 29 districts out of the
total of 64 had been flooded, with 6.4 million people affected
till Tuesday, press reports said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The official death toll caused by flood rose to 48, but
unofficial sources put the figure at about 100, the reports added.
</P>
<P>
The flood situation deteriorated again Tuesday with fresh
floods in the north and northwestern districts and inundation of
new areas in central districts following incessant rain in the
past few days, according to a bulletin of the Flood Information
Center (FIC).
</P>
<P>
All the major rivers in the country's four basins were still
flowing well above the danger level, the FIC said.
</P>
<P>
The Brahmaputra river was flowing 20 cm and 33 cm above danger
mark at two places, while the Ganges was running 30-57 cm above
danger level at three places.
</P>
<P>
The center forecast that the flood situation in the
Brahmaputra, Ganges and Meghna basins might aggravate further with
rise of water levels in most of the rivers while the situation in
the southeastern hill basin would improve in the next few days.
</P>
<P>
Various flood-borne diseases like diarrhea and dysentery have
broken out in many flood-hit districts as acute crisis of drinking
water was prevailing in those areas, reports noted.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Disaster Management and Relief has already
allocated over 2.2 million taka (about 46,800 U.S. dollars) and
2,175 tons of rice and other relief materials to the flood-hit
people.
</P>
<P>
The relief work is going on as the flood situation aggravates
further in many places of the country.
</P>
<P>
There are frequent heavy rains in the July-October monsoon
season in this South Asian country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
