<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vietnam Cuts Economic Targets for 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, July 22 (Xinhua) -- Vietnam has officially revised its
major 1998 economic targets downward, including a projected gross
domestic product (GDP) growth from nine percent to between six and
seven percent.
</P>
<P>
The standing committee of Vietnam's National Assembly (NA)
passed a resolution revising a number of major economic targets
set for 1998 at its meeting in Hanoi last Friday, the country's
major newspapers reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The industrial growth rate was cut from 13.5 percent to
between 10 and 11 percent and the agricultural growth target was
reset at 3.0 to 3.5 percent, down from the original 4.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
The export turnover growth target will be lowered from 25-26
percent to 10 percent with a trade deficit equal to 19 percent of
the total export value.
</P>
<P>
The inflation rate will be kept under 10 percent against the
previous seven percent, and the budget deficit should not exceed
four percent of total GDP.
</P>
<P>
The revision was made as a result of numerous difficulties
encountered by Vietnam which included natural calamities and the
ongoing financial crisis. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980722.0248 </DOCNO>
