<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Johnson Rises, Bubka Falls, and Sang Injured </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, July 21 (Xinhua) -- Olympic champion Michael Johnson
rose in the men's 400 meters while five-time world champion Sergei
Bubka no-heighted again in the men's pole vault at the Goodwill
Games here Tuesday, which saw a shocking injury to Chinese girl
gymnast Sang Lan who broke her spinal cord.
</P>
<P>
Russia won three golds from gymnastics and hauled one from
track and field to boost its title tally to 15, still one more
than the host United States. The host claimed three athletics gold
and one gymnastic laural.
</P>
<P>
One world record was surpassed, two meet records fell, and
Nigeria, Romania, Algeria, Australia, Kenya and Britain each
snatched one gold in the track and field competition.
</P>
<P>
Sang Lan, 17, fell on the ground head first during the warm-up
to the women's vaulting contest, suffering a serious spinal cord
injury.
</P>
<P>
Dr. Brock Schnebel, Goodwill Games chief medical officer,
claimed in an official statement:"She has a fractured-dislocation
of C-6 or C-7. This has resulted in an injury to her spinal cord.
At this time, she cannot move her legs. She has minimal motion of
her arms. She cannot feel from her mid-chest down. At present she
is receiving a MRI and treatment plans will be made based on the
results."
</P>
<P>
Johnson, who has been plagued by consistent injury and
unfitness in the past two years, made a strong comeback to win the
men's 400meters with a year's best 43.76, a new meet record. It
was his first sub-44 second run after the 1996 Olympics.
</P>
<P>
However, it was not a good day for Bubka, who opened at
5.70meters, and failed to clear it with his first two efforts
before he ruined the third chance by quitting mid-way during his
run-in.
</P>
<P>
The world pole vault king, who beat the world indoor and
outdoor records 35 times during his career, had a similar
no-height failure at the world championships in 1991.
</P>
<P>
Jeff Hartwig of the United States soared over 6.01 meters to
win the title, equalling the meet record.
</P>
<P>
World champion Maurice Greene of the United States proved that
he is the fastest man in the world when he beat almost all the
world big names in the men's 100 meters with a time of 9.96
seconds.
</P>
<P>
Ato Boldon of Trinidad and Tabago, who ran the year's best of
9.86early this season and won the 200 meter crown yesterday,
failed to bring out his best tonight, finishing second in 10.00
sharp to Brian Lewis of the United States' 10.25.
</P>
<P>
Mihaela Melinte of Romania bettered the listed world record in
the unfancied women's hammer with a 72.64 meter toss. Olga
Kuzenkova of Russia, who threw 73.80 last May in Russia, wound up
runner-up at 70.98. The organiser announced that Melinte's 72.64
effort beat the previous world record of 69.46.
</P>
<P>
Another meet record was set by Falilat Ogunkoya of Nigeria in
the women's 400 meters when she clocked 49.89 second, beating the
old mark of 49.96.
</P>
<P>
The men's mile race witnessed that defending champion
Noureddine Morceli of Algeria outkicked other big names with a
time of 3:53.39. William Tanui of Kenya burst over world 3,000 and
5,000 meters record holder Daniel Komen, also a Kenyan, on the
final box to take the silver.
</P>
<P>
Kenya made a clean sweep of the medals in the men's
10,000meters, with Julius Gitahi first in 27:49.26, Simon Maina
second in 27:49.65, and James Koskei third in 28:51.02.
</P>
<P>
Britain's world record holder Jonathan Edwards easily beat his
rivals in the men's triple jump with a 17.65 leap, and Joanna
Stone of Australia took the women's javelin gold with an awesome
heave of 66.29 meters. Another title went to Yelena Nikolayeva of
Russia, who cruised home 43:51.97 to win the women's 10km walk.
</P>
<P>
Russia almost swept three out of four individual titles in the
gymnastics competition, leaving the remaining one for the United
States.
</P>
<P>
Alexei Nemov, bronze medal winner in the men's all around, won
the floor exercises with 9.725 points. Nikolay Krukov scored 9.650
to win the men's pommel horse, while Svetlana Khorkina accumulated
9.825 points to take the women's unevenbars.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Vanessa Atler edged Russia's Elena Dolgopolova to claim
the women's vaulting with 9.662 points.
</P>
<P>
In today's basketball competition, Australia beat Lithuania
82-64, and Argentina downed Russia 69-65 in group A, while the
United States defeated Brazil 106-75, and Puerto Rico edged China
74-73.
</P>
<P>
In the water polo competition, Russia beat Italy 7-4, Spain
overpowered the United States 10-5, Italy edged Spain 6-5, and
Russia hammered the United States 10-5. 
</P>
</TEXT>
