<HEADLINE> U.S. Senate Appropriations Committee Approves Funding for IMF </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 21 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Senate Appropriations
Committee approved 18 billion U.S. dollars as additional funding
for the International Monetary Fund (IMF) Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
But the move could likely set up a battle with House lawmakers
who oppose giving more money to the international organization.
</P>
<P>
Committee Chairman Ted Stevens said replenishing the
International Monetary Fund is necessary to help it save troubled
economies across Asia and in Russia, and a refusal to approve the
Clinton administration's 18-billion-dollar IMF request could
damage the U.S. economy.
</P>
<P>
"If the global economy goes sour, our economy will go sour,"
Stevens warned.
</P>
<P>
This funding was attached to a 12.6-billion-dollar foreign
operations bill the Senate Appropriations Committee sent to the
full Senate for approval. The Senate approved a separate IMF
measure in March, but that has languished in the House.
</P>
<P>
The House Appropriations Subcommittee set aside only 3.4
billion dollars for the IMF. The full committee is expected to
take up the measure Wednesday. Differences between the House and
Senate versions would be resolved by a conference committee.
</P>
<P>
The latest IMF bailout came Monday when Russia agreed to
economic reforms as a condition for receiving an
11.2-billion-dollar loan.
</P>
<P>
The 12.6-billion-dollar foreign operations bill sent to the
Senate for approval for fiscal year 1999, beginning October 1,
maintains nearly the same level of funding as last year, but is
one billion dollars less than President Bill Clinton requested.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
