<HEADLINE> China, Guyana Pledge to Continue Good Relations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GEORGETOWN, Guyana, July 21 (Xinhua) -- Guyana's Prime Minister
Samuel Hinds and visiting Chinese Vice-Premier Qian Qichen pledged
on Tuesday to continue the good relations between their two
countries.
</P>
<P>
Qian, who arrived here on Monday, said the Chinese government
is willing to build a long-term stable cooperative relationship,
while Hinds said the Guyanese people and government would like to
extend existing cooperation to different sectors.
</P>
<P>
Qian told Hinds that common views have increased, friendship
has deepened and good results have been achieved through his
meeting with President Janet Jagan on Monday night.
</P>
<P>
Immediately after his arrival, Qian and Jagan met at the
president's office. They exchanged views on bilateral relations
and issues of common concern, a Chinese Foreign Ministry spokesman
said.
</P>
<P>
Jagan said that Guyana will continue to make efforts to
strengthen its ties with China and consolidate the achievements of
cooperation. She expressed the hope that her country would be
China's good friend in all areas, the spokesman told Chinese
reporters.
</P>
<P>
Qian said that relations between China and Guyana have
developed smoothly. The number of high-level visits is increasing
and cooperation in all areas has been effective since the two
countries set up diplomatic ties 26 years ago.
</P>
<P>
Guyana is an important country in the Caribbean, said Qian,
adding that the purpose of his visit was to promote good relations
between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese vice premier expressed his belief that bilateral
relations will be further strengthened in the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
Speaking of economic and trade relations, Qian said the Chinese
government would like to facilitate their development through
joint efforts based on equality and mutual benefits so that
cooperation can be a model for South-South cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Qian expressed his gratitude to the Guyanese
government for its support of China in international affairs and
its active effort in helping to develop relations between China
and other Caribbean nations.
</P>
<P>
On Monday night, Chinese Vice-Foreign Minister Yang Jiechi and
Guyanese Foreign Minister Clement Rohee signed an agreement on
mutual exemption of visas for officials between the two countries
and a separate agreement on economic and technology cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Guyana is the second stop of Qian's five Caribbean nation
tour. He will also visit Trinidad and Tobago, Cuba and Jamaica.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980722.0260 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italy Continues to Suffer From Forest Fires </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, July 21 (Xinhua) -- Italy spends an average of 1 trillion
lire (about 570 million U.S. dollars) each year in the last five
years to fight forest fires, yet flames continue to ravage its
woodlands, said a report released here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The combined size of the fire-damaged areas in the past five
years is equal to two percent of the Italian territory, the report
drawn up by the Forestry Corps said.
</P>
<P>
Destruction by fires was at its worst in 1993 when 203,143
hectares of woodlands went up in smoke.
</P>
<P>
In 1998, after the relatively uneventful first six months when
19,019 hectares were burned, fires in the first five days of July
alone caused a loss of 16,950 hectares.
</P>
<P>
July and August are the months with the highest risk of fire,
and the latest high rate of fires once more confirms the growing
inability of the responsible authorities to meet the summer
challenge.
</P>
<P>
Humans are responsible for 95 percent of fires in Italy and the
Forestry Corps has filed 8,664 charges of arson but 95 percent of
these are against persons unknown.
</P>
<P>
"One third of Italy is covered by forest and 70 percent of it
risks being attacked by fire," head of the Forestry Corps Fausto
Martinelli said, adding "It is imperative to improve intervention,
acting effectively and rapidly with the help of a public authority
to coordinate operations."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980722.0261 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Girl Gymnast Suffers Spinal Cord Injury </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, July 21 (Xinhua) -- China's Sang Lan, 17, suffered a
severely fractured-dislocation of her spinal cord when she fell on
the ground head first from a vaulting action during the warm-up to
the women's gymnastics competition at the Goodwill Games here
tonight.
</P>
<P>
The girl ran to the vaulting horse and jumped off with her
head hit the floor first.
</P>
<P>
Dr. Brock Schnebel, Goodwill Games chief medical officer, said
in an official statement:"I have been able to evaluate and speak
with Sang Lan through an interpreter, and evaluate her x-rays and
CAT scan. Unfortunately, she has a fractured-dislocation of C-6 on
C-7. This has resulted in an injury to her spinal cord."
</P>
<P>
Schnebel said:"At this time, she cannot move her legs. She has
minimal motion of her arms. She cannot feel from her mid-chest
down. This is consistent with a spinal cord injury at the level of
C-6,C-7. At present she is receiving an MRI and treatment plans
will be made based on the results."
</P>
<P>
Sang, who was born in China's Hunan province in 1981, won the
vaulting gold medal in the Chinese national gymnastics
championships last year. She didn't take part in the women's all
around competition at the current Games. 
</P>
</TEXT>
