<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Foreign Investors Interested in Buying Thai Assets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, July 22 (Xinhua) -- Foreign investors have shown
interest in purchasing assets of 56 failed finance companies in
Thailand, the Thai Financial Sector Restructuring Authority (FRA)
said.
</P>
<P>
Thailand has launched roadshows in the past few months at major
financial centers to find buyers of the assets of the finance
firms closed down by the Thai government late last year after the
economy nose-dived following the floating of the baht in July
1997.
</P>
<P>
The first stage of the roadshow in London had attracted foreign
interest in the closed companies' core assets, which consisted
mostly of loans, FRA Secretary-General Vicharat Vichitvadakan said
in a statement received Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"Thus far the feedback we are receiving from investors
indicates that there is significant investor interest in Thailand
and in the FRA sales process," Vicharat said.
</P>
<P>
Under an agreement with the International Monetary Fund, the 56
finance firms should be sold by the end of this year.
</P>
<P>
The FRA team met potential investors in London as well as
stock-exchange officials and media representatives. They will go
to New York before ending the roadshow in Boston.
</P>
<P>
Although the FRA is confident of selling non-core assets such
as computers, autos and other movable property to local buyers,
the authority needs to find big foreign capital to buy core assets
nominally valued at 770 billion baht (19.25 billion U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Last week, the authority said it had earmarked 60 percent of
total core assets for sale to foreign investors through the
roadshows.
</P>
<P>
But it predicts that major core assets such as corporate and
real-estate loans will only fetch around 50 percent of their
nominal value in the current economic climate. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980722.0264 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-22 </DATE_TIME>
