<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Myanmar Trades More with Asian Countries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, July 22 (Xinhua) -- Myanmar traded more with Asian
countries as compared with other parts of the world in the 1997-98
fiscal year which ended in March, with these countries accounting
for about 80 percent of its total export value and about 86
percent of its total import value.
</P>
<P>
The country's major trading partners in Asia including
Southeast Asia are China, India, Japan, Republic of Korea,
Malaysia, Singapore and Thailand.
</P>
<P>
Despite less export of rice, export of other commodities such
as cotton, jute, beans and pulses, silver and tin, petroleum
products, timber, fish and prawn, and sugar, increased in the year
especially through the border trade with neighboring Bangladesh,
China, India and Thailand, said another latest official report of
the country's financial, economic and social conditions.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar imported 14 percent more of the value of goods in the
1997-98 than the previous year. Major import items are capital
goods, industrial raw materials, spare parts and consumer goods.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar's foreign trade including the border trade increased by
12.8 percent in the 1997-98 over the year earlier, but a trade
deficit of 1.32 billion dollars still occurred.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar has also adjusted its border trade policy in an effort
to turn the border trade into normal trade by applying regular
trade procedures based on U.S. dollar in place of neighboring
currencies beginning November last year.
</P>
<P>
The country also promulgated later in April this year new
regulations for import and export, designating 22 goods items as
priorities for import.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, means for export promotion are being sought from the
private sector which contributed 76.5 percent to the export in the
1997-98 year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
