<HEADLINE> Sri Lankan Rebels Issued Weapons From Grocery Store </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, July 22 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka's rebels of the
Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam (LTTE) had been using a Colombo
grocery store as an issuing point of lethal material for their
operatives in the city.
</P>
<P>
According to Police sources Wednesday, the Terrorism
Investigation Division had unearthed such material from the
grocery store after a raid recently in the city.
</P>
<P>
Police have recovered three suicide jackets packed with four
kilograms of explosives each and cyanide capsules.
</P>
<P>
The shop, located opposite a Colombo police station at
Jampettah and owned by a Sinhalese, had been rented by a Tamil
shop keeper since 1990. The shop keeper had been funded by the
LTTE, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
Five arrests including that of the shop keeper and a relative
of his have been made so far in this connection.
</P>
<P>
Police and armed forces have tightened security in the capital
city in a bid to prevent possible rebel attacks.
</P>
<P>
In addition, over 4,000 police personnel will be deployed in
the city during the summit of the South Asian Association for
Regional Cooperation from July 29 to 31. 
</P>
</TEXT>
