<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai's Railway, Shipping Service Hookup </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, July 22 (Xinhua) -- The city of Shanghai increased
its container transport services at Yangpu Port and Jungonglu Port
on Tuesday to increase efficiency and speed in getting cargo to
other parts of China.
</P>
<P>
All formalities of container freight transiting the two ports
will be done just as soon as the containers land by one office and
they will be moved directly to rail service.
</P>
<P>
The ports' customs procedures have been simplified a great deal
from the previous mixture of communications office, railway
bureau, port administration, and customs office documents.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai has the country's largest container cargo handling
capacity and 71 container shipping companies operating nationally
and internationally. Its 12 overseas routes go to at least 110
ports abroad.
</P>
<P>
However, its rail service, which is the most effective means of
moving container cargo to distant inland areas at a comparatively
low cost, is still insufficient.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980722.0283 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia Dominates Gymnastics Individuals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, July 21 (Xinhua) -- Russia dominated the medals in
the individuals gymnastics on the third day of the fourth Goodwill
Games competitions in Long Island, New York on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Of the four apparatuses, men's floor exercise, pommel horse,
women's uneven bars and vault, the Russian gymnasts took three
gold, two silver and one bronze medals.
</P>
<P>
The United States placed second in medal tally after taking one
gold, two silver and one bronze medals. The other two bronze went
to Romania.
</P>
<P>
In the men's floor exercise, Russia's Alexei Nemov, the
reigning world champion in the event, won the title with a score
of 9.725points.
</P>
<P>
Nemov, who claimed the bronze medal on Monday night in the all
around, told a press briefing after the competitions that he was
flying and said that "Americans seem to be getting higher scores,
but that doesn't make any difference tonight."
</P>
<P>
The silver and bronze medals were carried by Jay Thornton, the
United States, with a score of 9.550, and Alexei Bondarenko,
Russia, respectively. Bondarenko, who also took the silver medal
in the all around event, finished with 9.525 points.
</P>
<P>
In the men's pommel horse, Russians claimed both the gold and
silver medals. Nikolay Krukov won the title with 9.650 points.
</P>
<P>
Krukov, who was the bronze medalist at the 1998 European
Championships in St. Petersburg, claimed 0.025 more point than his
compatriot, second-place finisher Alexei Bondarenko.
</P>
<P>
The bronze medal went to Yewki Tomita, United States, who got
9.375points.
</P>
<P>
In the women's events, Russia's Svetiana Khorkina bagged the
gold in the uneven bars with 9.825 points.
</P>
<P>
Khorkina, who took the gold in this event at the 1996
Individual World Championships and the 1995 World Championships,
told a press briefing that her secret of success was "a lot of
running".
</P>
<P>
Elise Ray of the United States and Romania's Simona Amanar tied
with 9.600 points to share the silver medal of the event.
</P>
<P>
The other gold medal was taken by America's Vanessa Atler, who
finished with 9.662 points in the vault event.
</P>
<P>
The 16-year-old Califonian was the current U.S. all-around and
vault national champions. She won the title by beating Russia's
Elena Bolgopolova with an advantage of 0.062 points.
</P>
<P>
Romania's Simona Amanar picked up the bronze medal of the event.
</P>
</TEXT>
