<HEADLINE> World Bank to Fund Philippine Farm Projects </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 22 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government will soon
get 30 million to 40 million U.S. dollars from the World Bank (WB)
to fund a 10 to 12 year program to boost agricultural productivity
as well as reduce poverty in the southern island of Mindanao.
</P>
<P>
Vinay Bhargava, WB country director for the Philippines, was
quoted Wednesday by the newspaper Business World as saying the
loan is for the first three to five years of the program which
will initially cover two provinces in Mindanao.
</P>
<P>
The first phase will begin within a year after the World Bank
completes consultations with targeted communities on needed
projects, Bhargava said.
</P>
<P>
Rahul Raturi, senior economist for WB's rural development and
natural resources unit, said the WB loan will primarily
concentrate on rural infrastructure and small- to medium-scale
irrigation systems.
</P>
<P>
The WB program will also introduce sustainable agricultural
production systems as well as diversified cropping systems through
better land and water management.
</P>
<P>
Access to credit, the country's agricultural inputs and more
effective technical services will also be improved.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the WB officials also said the bank will give a
150-million-dollar loan to the Land Bank of the Philippines for
its credit program for farmers and agribusiness firms. 
</P>
</TEXT>
