<HEADLINE> Indonesia's Capital City Air Getting Worse </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, July 22 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesian capital city's air
quality is on the decline as many motorists can no longer afford
to maintain their vehicle's exhaust systems, the Indonesian
Observer reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Many motorists are only spending their money on food and fuel,
and vehicle maintenance is a low priority.
</P>
<P>
The cost of spare parts has soared, meaning that vehicles are
now belching out more toxic fumes, putting the city's Blue Sky
program up in smoke.
</P>
<P>
Jakarta and other parts of the country also suffered severe air
pollution as a result of forest fires that commenced last year.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia has been the worst hit by the regional currency
turmoil with the rupiah losing over 80 percent of its value
against the U.S. dollar since July last year.
</P>
<P>
The economic crisis has resulted in soaring prices and
unemployment rate, hitting the poor people.
</P>
<P>
According to the Jakarta Statistics Office for Population
Statistics, more than 860,900 Jakarta residents lived in poverty
until June this year, accounting for 8.95 percent of the capital's
population.
</P>
<P>
The figure represented a 372 percent increase compared to 1996
when the number of Jakarta residents living in poverty reached
nearly 231,300.
</P>
<P>
The office attributed the drastic increase in the number of
Jakarta poor people to inflation which soared to 40.92 percent at
the start of last month from 11.70 percent in 1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
