<DOCNO> XIE19980722.0292 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Horse Back Folk Art Moves onto Stage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HOHHOT, July 22 (Xinhua) -- When Mongolians led by Genghis Khan
and Kublai Khan conquered China more than 700 years ago, folk
artists on horse back with four-stringed fiddle in hand told and
sang stories about their national heroes on the prairie.
</P>
<P>
Today, Lobsang, descendent of the ancient artists, tells and
sings stories in the Mongolian language on the stage, his head and
shoulder shaking to the rhythm of the fiddle in his hands.
</P>
<P>
His stories and other Mongolian programs performed today in
Hohhot, capital of the Inner Mongolia Autonomous Region, by
artists from a folk arts troupe have won the applause of both
Mongolian and Han audiences.
</P>
<P>
"I live in city, but their performance brought me back to the
prairie," said one Mongolian viewer.
</P>
<P>
"I can't understand what they are talking and singing about
without the explanations on the captions beside the stage," said a
Han viewer, "But I like their performance because it's full of
Mongolian flavor."
</P>
<P>
"The ancient Mongolian artists roamed on the prairie. And when
they came to the yurts of the herdsmen, they sat on the ground and
told and sang stories about what they had seen, while playing the
matouqin, the four-stringed instrument of the Mongol nationality,"
said Zhangxi, head of the troop.
</P>
<P>
The 56-year-old Lobsang was a student of Baja and Moyihan, two
Mongolian artists who performed for the late Chairman Mao Zedong
nearly 50 years ago.
</P>
<P>
Lobsang recalled that it took Baja and Moyihan decades of
effort to revive Mongol storytelling and singing and other
folk-art genres, and to move these arts from the Mongolian yurt to
the modern stage, thereby developing the complete art form called
Mongol Quyi.
</P>
<P>
Zhangxi said Mongolian Quyi on stage is greatly changed, from a
single singer to many, and the performance is now usually
accompanied by many unique instruments including the matouqin, wooden
clapper, dulcimer and drum.
</P>
<P>
On the basis of special melodies handed down from ancient
times, much of Mongol folk music has been absorbed into Mongolian
Quyi to give full play to its unique flavor.
</P>
<P>
So far, Mongolian Quyi has developed into more than 30 forms
including those adapted from Han Quyi such as comic
dialogues. "Pilgrimage To The West," "Romance Of The Three
Kingdoms" and other famous ancient books of the Han ethnic group
have been translated into the Mongolian language and are performed
in Mongolian Quyi.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980722.0293 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-22 </DATE_TIME>
