<HEADLINE> Brazil to Reduce Orange Juice Production </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
RIO DE JANEIRO, July 20 (Xinhua) -- Brazil, one of the largest
producers of orange juice in the world, will see a reduction in
juice production this year, the Brazilian Citric Exporters
Association said.
</P>
<P>
The association said the country expected to process 203
million boxes of oranges, each weighing about 48 kilograms,
compared with 1997's 318 million boxes. Orange juice production
will amount to about 820 million tons, which is also less than
last year.
</P>
<P>
The Brazilian orange juice industry still has 236 million tons
of processed juice from the last harvest, which will be sold this
year to maintain its world exporting position.
</P>
<P>
The drop of juice production in the country this year is a
result of a 30 percent reduction in the orange harvest.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, Brazilian orange production amounted to 405 million
boxes, while the export of orange juice was 1.3 million tons.
</P>
</TEXT>
