<HEADLINE> Johnson Wins Men's 400m in New Meet Record Time </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Johnson, who shocked the world with his rare 200 and 400 meters
double at the Olympics in 1996, hit the tape in 43.76 seconds, the
year's best in the world, to beat the old meet record of 44.79.
</P>
<P>
It was the fastest time Johnson produced after his Olympic
triumphs. The American has been troubled consistently by
injuries, and lost his edge in the past year.
</P>
<P>
Johnson reeled over the rest of runners on the home curve,
turning his head to see Tyree Washington hanging side by side with
him.
</P>
<P>
He found some reserved strength on the final stretch, kicking
hard to gain a clear gap till the finish.
</P>
<P>
World bronze medalist Washington finished second in 44.43
ahead of Antonio Pettigrew, 44.78.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. runners swept the top six spots in the event. 
