<HEADLINE> Real Estate Sector Improving on Southern Chinese Island </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAIKOU, July 22 (Xinhua) -- The real estate business in Haikou,
the capital of China's Hainan Province, improved in the first half
of the year after several consecutive years of negative growth.
</P>
<P>
In the first six months the land requisitioneded by the local
government from farmers increased 183 percent, and land sales were
up 790 percent on a year-on-year basis. Housing sales also
increased rapidly, with the number of households involved going up
100 percent, the floor space 90 percent, and the value 80 percent.
</P>
<P>
Haikou real estate market overheated in the first few years
after Hainan was granted provincial status in 1988, but the
central government put the brakes on it in 1993 and the situation
improved, although it put a damper on business.
</P>
<P>
Market analysts attribute the improvement in the first half of
the year to improvements in the local economy. Haikou's GDP was up
8.1 percent, the first time since 1993 that it was higher than the
national average.
</P>
<P>
Another reason is simplified procedures of trading and increased
bank loans.
</P>
<P>
However, the situation is still far from good because the city
has a surplus of more than 3 million square meters of housing,
worth 10 billion yuan (1.2 billion U.S. dollars). 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
