<HEADLINE> Doctors Going To Rural Pastoral Areas In Northwestern China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
URUMQI, July 22 (Xinhua) -- This year, northwest China's
Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region has sent 1,596 doctors to rural
and pastoral areas to provide long-term medical services for
ethnic minority farmers and herdsmen.
</P>
<P>
Xinjiang has 12 million farmers and herdsmen, or 70 percent of
the autonomous region's total population and many do not have a
chance to see doctors in cities far from where they live.
</P>
<P>
The 279 urban medical teams are helping the minority ethnic
people get better medical care close to home, and 30
poverty-stricken counties benefited from the help.
</P>
<P>
The doctors opened clinics and performed some operations at
local hospitals and brought some advanced equipment with them.
</P>
<P>
They also held a series of training courses for medical staff
at rural hospitals. 
