<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ukrainian Cabinet Sets Economic Targets for 1999 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, July 21 (Xinhua) -- The Ukraine Cabinet passed an
economic plan establishing financial targets for 1999, which sets
gross domestic product (GDP) growth at 2 percent.
</P>
<P>
According to the economic development plan for 1999, Ukraine's
GDP should reach 112 billion gryvna next year, a 2 percent growth
compared with this year's 101.1 billion gryvna.
</P>
<P>
The plan sets industrial and agricultural output value
increases next year at 1.8 percent and 2.5 percent respectively.
</P>
<P>
The Cabinet plans to reduce the budget deficit to 1.5 percent
of the GDP next year, while keeping, at the same time, the inflation
rate below 8 percent.
</P>
<P>
Efforts will be made to prevent the gryvna from devaluating
further, keeping the scope of devaluation against the U.S. dollar
within this year's 18 percent limit, the Cabinet said.
</P>
<P>
According to the Cabinet, at the end of 1999, the exchange rate
between gryvna and the U.S. dollar will stay at 2.42:1.
</P>
<P>
Ukraine's unemployment rate is expected to rise from this
year's planned 4.6 percent to 6.2 percent in 1999.
</P>
<P>
In the first half of 1998, Ukraine's real GDP growth reached
0.2 percent. The Cabinet's GDP target for the whole year is 0.5
percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
