<HEADLINE> Britain Reaffirms Policy on Lockerbie Trial </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 21 (Xinhua) -- The British government Tuesday
reaffirmed its policy on the Lockerbie trial, saying it still
wants the two Libyans accused of bombing the Pan Am flight 103 in
1988 to be tried in Scotland or the United States.
</P>
<P>
A report in Britain's Guardian newspaper published Tuesday said
that Britain and the United States have agreed the two Libyan
agents can face trial in The Hague under Scottish law.
</P>
<P>
However, a spokesman for Britain's Foreign Office dismissed
such it speculation, saying: "Our policy remains unchanged, and
that is Libya must surrender the suspects for trial in Scotland or
the U.S."
</P>
<P>
The Libyan government has repeatedly made clear it would not
hand over the two suspects unless the trial was held in a neutral
venue, while London and Washington insist that the trial could
only be held in Scotland or the United States.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Security Council imposed strict sanctions on Libya in
1992 for failing to hand over the two suspects, who were accused
of killing 270 passengers aboard Pan Am airliner over the Scottish
village of Lockerbie.  
</P>
</TEXT>
