<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canada Sees Labor Productivity Increased </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, July 21 (Xinhua) -- The Canadian business sector recorded
in 1997 its best performance in labor productivity since 1984,
Statistics Canada said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"Labor productivity in the business sector increased 2.9 percent
on the heels of strong economic growth and surging business
investment," the statistics agency said.
</P>
<P>
This performance was the strongest since 1984 when the country's
labor productivity grew 3.3 percent as the economy recovered from the
1982 recession.
</P>
<P>
Productivity is a measure of production efficiency that most
economists regard as the foundation of growth in a country's standard
of living.
</P>
<P>
It usually grows when businesses become more efficient and when
they increase the amount of machinery and equipment and advanced
technologies that workers use.
</P>
<P>
Until 1996, Canada's productivity gains were far less impressive
than they were during the mid-1980s, when the economy was recovering
more rapidly from a recession.
</P>
<P>
However, when the good performance in 1997 is taken into account,
the country's average productivity gains since 1991 have grown at
almost the same pace as during the previous economic cycle in the
1980s.
</P>
<P>
Labor productivity increased an average of 1.1 percent a year
between 1982 and 1991, while it increased an average of 1.2 percent
a year between 1991 and 1997, the agency said.
</P>
<P>
In the past seven years, the United States recorded an average of
1.3 percent a year in its labor productivity, 0.1 percent higher than
that of Canada, agency added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
