<HEADLINE> French NGOs Call on U.N. to Be Firm Toward Afghan  Taliban </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, July 21 (Xinhua) -- Seven French non-governmental
organizations which were recently driven out of Afghanistan by the
Taliban Tuesday called on the United Nations to adopt a very clear
stand toward the guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
The appeal was made by the representatives of the Action contre
la Faim, Acted, Medecins du Monde, Medecins sans Frontieres, Aide
Medicale Internationale, Pharmaciens sans Frontieres and
Solidarity, all of which were recently forced to leave the Afghan
capital Kabul.
</P>
<P>
They criticized the United Nations for signing an agreement
with Taliban in May, under which the U.N. was allowed to open
humanitarian agencies in Kabul but was subjected to restrictions
in recruiting women and local employees.
</P>
<P>
"The signing of this protocol has opened the door for a
discriminatory policy (by Taliban). We ask the United Nations to
stay but make sure that the access by the people to the aid will
be made in conformity with the ethics," said Jacky Mamou,
president of the Medecins sans Frontieres.
</P>
<P>
These NGOs, which left Kabul after the Taliban gave them an
ultimatum asking all their foreign personnel to regroup in a
ruined district of Kabul, held the U.N. responsible for the
present situation.
</P>
<P>
They pointed out that the departure of NGOs from Kabul would
lead to "a rise of epidemics, the problems of malnutrition and
the displacement of people."
</P>
<P>
They also expressed readiness to hold direct dialogue with the
Taliban on the basis of humanitarian principles for a resumption
of their activities in Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
These NGOs expect the United Nations humanitarian agencies and
the donating countries to take a very clear stand when the latters
meet in New York on Tuesday to seek a common stand on Afghanistan.
</P>
</TEXT>
