<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Welder's Sparks Might have Sparked Cruise Ship Fire </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 21 (Xinhua) -- A welder's spark in a laundry
room might have ignited lint and touched off a fire aboard the
giant cruise ship Ecstasy Monday, the president of Carnival Cruise
Lines said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The fire on the second deck quickly spread two decks above
Monday to the outside mooring area, where nylon rope fed the
flames, cruise line president Bob Dickinson said at a news
conference in Miami, Florida.
</P>
<P>
"There was welding going on in an area of the laundry room" and
alarms sounded there, The Associated Press quoted Dickson as
saying. "Perhaps a spark from the laundry room ignited some lint
in the vent tubes which caused a very high explosive-type fire,
which ended up in the mooring deck."
</P>
<P>
Plumes of smoke shot out the back of the ship shortly after it
left port.
</P>
<P>
Soon, flames were pouring out the back and many of the 2,575
passengers assembled on the main deck, wearing orange life vests.
The 10-deck Carnival Cruise Lines ship, which also had more than
900 crew members, was bound for Key West and then Cozumel, Mexico.
</P>
<P>
A National Transportation Safety Board (NTSB) team toured the
fire scene Tuesday morning. After Dickinson raised the welder
theory, Robert Francis, NTSB vice chairman, said it was too early
to draw any conclusions.
</P>
<P>
Fifty-four people were treated, most for smoke inhalation and
one with an undisclosed heart problem. Of the 54, 20 were taken to
hospitals and at least four people were admitted overnight.
</P>
<P>
A tugboat pulled the 70,367-ton ship back to the Port of Miami,
trailed by three boats spraying water on the lower levels. Crews
worked on cooling down hot spots before the ship got to shore.
</P>
<P>
Carnival Corp., the world's largest cruise lines, operates
ships under the Carnival, Holland America and Windstar brands. .
</P>
<P>
The Ecstasy, which entered service in June 1991, is in
Carnival's second-largest class of ships. 
</P>
</TEXT>
