<DOCNO> XIE19980722.0337 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Urges Tighter Regulation on Nursing Homes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 21 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
announced on Tuesday measures to crack down on nursing homes that
fail to give high-quality care to their patients, and to prod
states to do a better job in regulating them.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said he would ask Congress to pass legislation that
would require nursing homes to conduct a criminal background check
on workers and would set up a national registry of nursing home
employees convicted of abusing residents.
</P>
<P>
The legislation also would allow more employees to receive
training in preventing malnutrition and dehydration and
reauthorize the nursing home ombudsman program under the
Administration on Aging. The ombudsman provides information of
records of abuse and neglect at poorly run nursing homes.
</P>
<P>
But the Clinton administration said it would reject Congress'
suggestion that state inspectors can be replaced by inspectors
from private, accredited agencies. After experimenting with that
idea, administration officials have found it would not work.
</P>
<P>
Donna Shalala, the secretary of health and human services, said
"They actually put nursing home residents in jeopardy. We are
concluding, based on that experience, that we should continue with
well-trained state inspectors."
</P>
<P>
The Clinton administration also was taking several steps on its
own, such as directing state enforcement agencies to impose
immediate penalties on nursing homes that repeat serious
violations.
</P>
<P>
The Department of Health and Human Services was submitting a
900-page report to Congress making recommendations on nursing home
care improvement.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980722.0338 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bonn Expects 2.5 Percent Growth for Years until </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, July 21 (Xinhua) -- The German government said Tuesday
that it is expecting an average economic growth rate of about 2.5
percent every year between now and 2002 in Germany.
</P>
<P>
In a medium-term economic projection issued Tuesday, the German
Economics Ministry said that the brighter economic outlook, which
compares with an average expansion rate of around 1.5 percent over
the past five years, was expected to bring about a gradual
improvement on the job market.
</P>
<P>
The jobless total could be reduced to about 3.5 million by 2002
from an estimated 4.3 million for 1998, the ministry said.
</P>
<P>
The report also predicted that with an annual growth of about
6.5 percent, exports would continue to be the main driving force
behind Germany's economic upturn by 2002. Domestic consumption was
expected to remain weak with an average growth rate of just 2.0
percent.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile the ministry also predicted that the eastern German
economy would still fail to close the gap with the richer western
German economy. By 2002, productivity in eastern Germany was
expected to reach just 61 percent of that in the West compared
with 60.4 percent registered in 1997.  
</P>
</TEXT>
