<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kohl's Party Still Trails in Opinion Poll </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, July 21 (Xinhua) -- A large majority of German political
and business elites now expect that Germany's main opposition
Social Democratic Party (SPD) would win the country's next general
elections on September 27 this year, an opinion poll issued
Tuesday showed.
</P>
<P>
According to the opinion poll conducted by the German
Allensbach research institute, about 67 percent of the 602
questioned political and business leaders said that the leftist
SPD party would emerge as the strongest party after the general
elections.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, only 28 percent still believed that German
Chancellor Helmut Kohl's conservatives would remain as the
strongest party after the national vote.
</P>
<P>
Despite the finding that about 59 percent of those questioned
personally want Kohl to remain in office, 70 percent of them said
Kohl's SPD challenger Gerhard Schroeder was expected to be the
eventual winner.
</P>
<P>
A majority of them did not believe that the current economic
upturn in Germany would help Kohl to win the election.
</P>
<P>
The Allensbach poll, commissioned by the German economic weekly
Capital, also showed that the number of German political and
business leaders who expect a grand coalition between Kohl's
Christian Democratic Union (CDU) party and the SPD had increased
to 34 percent from just 23 percent registered three months ago.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980722.0342 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ambassador Qin on Extending Mandate of UNPREDEP </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, July 21 (Xinhua) -- China supports assisting in
the maintenance of Macedonia's stability and security, and the
international community should respect its political independence
and sovereignty, Chinese Permanent Representative to the United
Nations Qin Huasun said here on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the Security Council which met to vote on
extending the mandate of the United Nations Preventive
Deployment Force (UNPREDEP) in Macedonia, Ambassador Qin said
United Nations peacekeeping operations should have a proper
beginning and a proper end.
</P>
<P>
Qin said however, taking into account the request of the
Macedonian Government, as well as the concern expressed by
regional countries, China will not object to a further extension
of UNPREDEP's mandate.
</P>
<P>
Qin said China hoped that the adjustment of the mission's
mandate enabling it to assume monitoring responsibilities along
border areas would effectively contain illicit arms flows and
terrorist activities.
</P>
<P>
He said in the light of the overall intent of the
international community to maintain peace and stability, China
would vote in favor of extending the mandate of UNPREDEP.
</P>
<P>
Qin stressed that that vote, however, did not constitute any
change in China's principled position with regard to Security
Council resolutions 1101(1997), 1114(1997) and 1160(1998). 
</P>
</TEXT>
